rit\":\"bodhi­sattvayānika\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub sems dpa’i theg pa can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"33bb7c17-c48c-470f-936b-94aa51abd9bf\",\"authority\":\"b217f5ed-0529-454d-a07b-24544e9fcbe8\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"one billion\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱེ་བ་བརྒྱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"koṭīśata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bye ba brgya\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c3f73b51-40e1-4b68-8859-8a105851b92e\",\"authority\":\"0ccafca7-49ce-41ad-8426-fa67dd66567e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"one quintillion\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱེ་བ་ཁྲག་ཁྲིག་བརྒྱ་སྟོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"koṭī­niyuta­śata­sahasra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bye ba khrag khrig brgya stong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"64105151-6806-4ecf-9b65-72dbaacc4d62\",\"authority\":\"cc81a7fc-0f8f-479c-8ee5-a1682fc5dd49\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"one second\",\"tibetan\":\"ཐང་གཅིག\",\"sanskrit\":\"lava\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"thang gcig\"}},{\"uuid\":\"bf343427-6de2-4bc9-8df0-f1237ea4caad\",\"authority\":\"f00b932d-63e6-465a-b166-4149ea25da32\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"one trillion\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱེ་བ་བརྒྱ་སྟོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"koṭī­śata­sahasra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bye ba brgya stong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"41d53369-fb3a-4635-ac77-cdd3d19898e1\",\"authority\":\"2739ca12-1267-4630-a837-f4b14ed61480\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"one who gives birth\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐྱེད་པར་བྱེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"janayitrī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skyed par byed pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ed7270eb-cf0d-4e4a-9c32-77fb454281a5\",\"authority\":\"ada97b6c-58f1-4b83-ac6e-e233040106d3\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"oriented toward\",\"tibetan\":\"མངོན་དུ་བྱེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhimukha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mngon du byed\"}},{\"uuid\":\"064d24a6-3da5-4e30-bed5-7b6c0e0a5820\",\"authority\":\"2fa63dee-4c60-4d7c-8630-55b7a16c6580\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"outcaste among bodhisattvas\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་གདོལ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bodhi­sattva­caṇḍāla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub sems dpa’ gdol pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"bf032068-576a-414b-b7e7-6c9ecc4dee0b\",\"authority\":\"a6cfce42-e4db-447a-bc17-be262cf66506\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"outshone\",\"tibetan\":\"ཟིལ་གྱིས་མནན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhibhūta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zil gyis mnan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f295a6f0-ace2-43ed-b63c-96bcb8785083\",\"authority\":\"83bc2cf9-f0fd-4fec-8ed4-ba4e7c2e088d\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"overexcited\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡ་ཡ་པོར་མི་འགྱུར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"notplavate\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ya ya por mi ’gyur\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2322dec6-dd73-46cc-a3cc-3dadbf72bf2e\",\"authority\":\"b323586a-49e2-4a99-b97b-983ad913efcc\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSee \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/afcfacf3-e7c1-416a-8ac2-2bc54b5e739d\\\"/\u003en.279\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"own unique human body\",\"tibetan\":\"བདག་གི་དངོས་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ātmabhāva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bdag gi dngos po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"839fbe36-2bd3-4dc5-a69b-4509251afefe\",\"authority\":\"b3c2af0d-1a64-4946-81f5-c7f7f1809d08\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSee \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/afcfacf3-e7c1-416a-8ac2-2bc54b5e739d\\\"/\u003en.279\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"own unique physical body\",\"tibetan\":\"བདག་གི་དངོས་པོའི་སྐུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ātmabhāvaśarīra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bdag gi dngos po’i sku\"}},{\"uuid\":\"684d1298-bd22-4009-ac47-91c522c12893\",\"authority\":\"e0ec1ac4-808e-478d-a1e2-e8b2f6ecb00b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe first of the four truths of the noble ones. The term “suffering” includes all essentially unsatisfactory experiences of life in cyclic existence, whether physical or mental. These comprise (1) the suffering of suffering, i.e., the physical sensations and mental experiences that are self-evident as suffering and toward which spontaneous feelings of aversion arise; (2) the suffering of change, i.e., all experiences that are normally recognized as pleasant and desirable, but which are nonetheless suffering in that persistent indulgence in these always results in changing attitudes of dissatisfaction and boredom; and (3) the suffering of the pervasive conditioning underlying the round of birth, aging, and death.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"pain, painful, suffering\",\"tibetan\":\"སྡུག་བསྔལ་བ།, སྡུག་བསྔལ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"duḥkha, duḥkha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sdug bsngal ba, sdug bsngal ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"999cad0b-8e8c-42d8-aac9-011a2dec26ca\",\"authority\":\"e0ec1ac4-808e-478d-a1e2-e8b2f6ecb00b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe first of the four truths of the noble ones. The term “suffering” includes all essentially unsatisfactory experiences of life in cyclic existence, whether physical or mental. These comprise (1) the suffering of suffering, i.e., the physical sensations and mental experiences that are self-evident as suffering and toward which spontaneous feelings of aversion arise; (2) the suffering of change, i.e., all experiences that are normally recognized as pleasant and desirable, but which are nonetheless suffering in that persistent indulgence in these always results in changing attitudes of dissatisfaction and boredom; and (3) the suffering of the pervasive conditioning underlying the round of birth, aging, and death.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"pain, painful, suffering\",\"tibetan\":\"སྡུག་བསྔལ་བ།, སྡུག་བསྔལ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"duḥkha, duḥkha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sdug bsngal ba, sdug bsngal ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"08a8015c-bc31-48ae-8abb-2ac57ba086a5\",\"authority\":\"f1935ed0-dde8-489b-9272-1d2e52151e81\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSixth god realm of desire, meaning “Mastery over Transformations.”\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Paranirmitavaśavartin\",\"tibetan\":\"གཞན་འཕྲུལ་དབང་བྱེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"paranirmitavaśavartin\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzhan ’phrul dbang byed\"}},{\"uuid\":\"067d251d-4033-4730-9128-e7a2bf7c2153\",\"authority\":\"c5c62cf9-a830-4ac4-8b7b-2f4214dd7e4c\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"parapet\",\"tibetan\":\"མདའ་ཡབ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"khoḍakaśīrṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mda’ yab\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ee377164-b3bf-418c-9d21-f9355667e19d\",\"authority\":\"a8380c12-eac9-413f-854a-84d2c30981a9\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"parasite\",\"tibetan\":\"སྲིན་བུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kṛmi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"srin bu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d6d6593b-25d3-4049-97b4-3615b3c1fe97\",\"authority\":\"49d44990-c795-44ff-8472-3a1e6e4262cb\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eFifth of the thirteen god realms of form that correspond to the four meditative concentrations, meaning “Little Radiance.”\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Parīttābha\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་ཆུང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"Parīttābha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od chung\"}},{\"uuid\":\"af0dc62d-7832-49f4-b7b8-18fca7272c22\",\"authority\":\"81d99b49-feef-44e4-a5e6-a4708d3a8277\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eEighth of the thirteen god realms of form that correspond to the four meditative concentrations, meaning “Little Virtue.”\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Parīttaśubha\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་ཆུང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"parīttaśubha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge chung\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f8312a26-df41-417f-baed-6e401b1e5766\",\"authority\":\"39d5317f-2e1f-4ccb-b9a0-7af0b6066504\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"passing it by\",\"tibetan\":\"གཡུལ་ལས་འདས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"atikrāma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"g.yul las ’das\"}},{\"uuid\":\"80e88a46-a897-465d-884c-b724b1404eb0\",\"authority\":\"075d302c-776f-43d4-9c55-37ff782f5988\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eFourth of the five paths.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"path of cultivation\",\"tibetan\":\"བསྒོམ་པའི་ལམ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhāvanāmārga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bsgom pa’i lam\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a1dfb7e4-c4f3-4dd3-8988-ff50731b6fcd\",\"authority\":\"37525ef5-4a67-437f-b488-20dc89216689\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eFifth of the five paths.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"path of no more training\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་སློབ་པའི་ལམ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aśaikṣamārga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi slob pa’i lam\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5b884783-353d-4b51-9f6e-5b8ab29c823b\",\"authority\":\"849f4fdb-d52b-413e-a645-7e7ff71d5664\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSecond of the five paths.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"path of preliminary practice\",\"tibetan\":\"སྦྱོར་བའི་ལམ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prayogyamārga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sbyor ba’i lam\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6f632c62-dd2f-4261-a93d-6db315e8a6bf\",\"authority\":\"52e3c3f7-2555-4481-a548-6da2c8dc367e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThird of the five paths.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"path of seeing\",\"tibetan\":\"མཐོང་བའི་ལམ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"darśana­mārga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mthong ba’i lam\"}},{\"uuid\":\"69068b19-1508-4f88-983b-aabcc7be72b5\",\"authority\":\"c6a91528-55ad-4418-ba32-2a3500dfda08\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe term may encompass the first four of the five paths, as well as the first seven of the eight stages that culminate in the state of a worthy one. \u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"path of training\",\"tibetan\":\"སློབ་པའི་ལམ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śaikṣamārga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"slob pa’i lam\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ed8b1c94-1480-4d76-8c69-9697a1b7c4c3\",\"authority\":\"762dbf08-bad0-4e3c-a92e-e545c607b320\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe name of one of eight lotus pools in each of the gardens of Dharmodgata’s estate in Gandhavatī.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Patient\",\"tibetan\":\"བདེ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kṣamā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bde ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4ed793e5-b927-44f6-8bb0-e3cab55c110f\",\"authority\":\"ba946d68-5ee2-4f5a-822c-c339704c9072\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"pavilion\",\"tibetan\":\"དཀྱིལ་འཁོར་གྱི་ཁྱམས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"maṇḍalamāle\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dkyil ’khor gyi khyams\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5ada82eb-e5e4-4df5-873c-20b0f5055a46\",\"authority\":\"56b7d69f-2942-430e-95e8-acdedd600288\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"peaceful ways of life\",\"tibetan\":\"ཞི་བར་སྤྱོད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śamacaryā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zhi bar spyod pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ca2b836f-95b4-4a1e-b05a-f4b892099782\",\"authority\":\"76a11fb8-e48b-40b8-9702-c675f31d6069\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe second of four stages or experiences of breaking through on the path of preliminary practice.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"peak\",\"tibetan\":\"རྩེ་མོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mūrdhan\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rtse mo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"78a7f55d-6537-4695-a1c0-71eb963a2a00\",\"authority\":\"c2155e5b-2f0c-4800-81bc-5d4f2b8628b0\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"peaked temple\",\"tibetan\":\"ཁང་པ་བརྩེགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kūṭāgāra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"khang pa brtsegs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"360ef9fa-cc6f-4f0f-9fd4-c4b67089fe23\",\"authority\":\"b3e77a1c-bea5-41e5-8eba-bbb781ee40cc\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"perform an act of truth\",\"tibetan\":\"བདེན་པའི་བྱིན་གྱི་རླབས་བྱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"satyādhiṣṭhānaṃ kariṣyāmi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bden pa’i byin gyi rlabs bya\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fffa4f81-7bfa-4102-9276-e4bfc613553f\",\"authority\":\"304af17f-8eec-4e46-8c7c-f08b5a8e7203\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"performing the practices\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྱད་པ་སྤྱོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"cārikāṃ caranti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spyad pa spyod\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0177978e-49fe-4595-9bb7-50c69b0eb938\",\"authority\":\"755d0a18-948b-4e09-9026-a9ed70381e24\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"physical actualization\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐུ་ཡོངས་སུ་གྲུབ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kāyapariniṣpatti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sku yongs su grub pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cbb7e210-529e-41ff-babe-2a5a692b6915\",\"authority\":\"ca58dded-128a-41bb-ad45-3c4f96597b95\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSee \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/afcfacf3-e7c1-416a-8ac2-2bc54b5e739d\\\"/\u003en.279\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"physical body\",\"tibetan\":\"བདག་གི་དངོས་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ātmabhāva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bdag gi dngos po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2fc4f126-3bd7-41b7-ac24-617906330f5c\",\"authority\":\"76a38c5c-14d1-4c26-b781-4cb7acb50515\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSee \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/afcfacf3-e7c1-416a-8ac2-2bc54b5e739d\\\"/\u003en.279\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"physical relic\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śarīra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sku\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6ee48068-c346-4c86-9de7-86f897d4e85b\",\"authority\":\"bb4dfa90-bda0-4774-983e-1079d557a9cf\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"physically deformed\",\"tibetan\":\"དབྱིབས་མི་སྡུག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"duḥsaṃsthāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dbyibs mi sdug pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"aaeba2e6-a279-4a6d-af18-709a428b75ee\",\"authority\":\"474544b7-f5a4-4439-b00f-30a1e436a12d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThis term has three meanings: (1) the ultimate nature, (2) the experience of the ultimate nature, and (3) the quiescent state of a worthy one (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/em\u003e) to be avoided by bodhisattvas.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"pinnacle of reality\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡང་དག་པའི་མཐའ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhūtakoṭi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yang dag pa’i mtha’\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6d37f084-ca6a-4365-a2a6-94c3267bc2b5\",\"authority\":\"17160128-de13-40d3-b25f-0bc14a400a61\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe fourth of four stages or experiences of breaking through on the path of preliminary practice.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"pinnacle of worldly things\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇིག་རྟེན་པའི་ཆོས་ཀྱི་མཆོག\",\"sanskrit\":\"laukikāgradharma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jig rten pa’i chos kyi mchog\"}},{\"uuid\":\"534064f3-2b6e-47b2-9275-ae41efa5275a\",\"authority\":\"0baf976f-a73f-4674-bea3-56e3d670ba1a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe term \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003edhāraṇī\u003c/em\u003e has the sense of something that “holds” or “retains,” and so it can refer to the special capacity of practitioners to memorize and recall detailed teachings. It can also refer to a verbal expression of the teachings‍—an incantation, spell, or mnemonic formula‍—that distills and “holds” essential points of the Dharma and is used by practitioners to attain mundane and supramundane goals. The same term is also used to denote texts that contain such formulas.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"power of memory\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟུངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhāraṇī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzungs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2f6ea888-548c-45fa-b0a9-6b11c1beea03\",\"authority\":\"affdb66b-c6d1-409a-a476-2a7bee8bb540\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"powerful energy\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟི་བརྗིད་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahaujaska\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzi brjid chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d152f48e-5c78-4465-ad19-68f03a7830f2\",\"authority\":\"a2279721-c66c-42dd-9f83-575dfea4d087\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"practice generosity\",\"tibetan\":\"སྦྱིན་པ་བྱིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dānaṃ dattaṃ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sbyin pa byin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"481b8064-38df-4eae-9abc-c7a6f6277834\",\"authority\":\"acfa0545-54d9-4078-919c-1babd48d440a\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"practice of ascetic qualities, sorts of ascetic qualities, types of ascetic qualities\",\"tibetan\":\"སྦྱངས་པའི་ཡོན་ཏན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dhutaguṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sbyangs pa’i yon tan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b55c8245-cea0-4e2a-9687-2a85a37beb8d\",\"authority\":\"af66ea05-0fe0-4398-b4a1-5d99139a7c29\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eLiterally “Lord of Beings,” an epithet designating a god of the Brahmā realm but also referring to Śiva, Viṣṇu, and others.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Prajāpati\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐྱེ་དགུའི་བདག་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prajāpati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skye dgu’i bdag po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"17005e7a-e029-42eb-a4ed-ad8f20880fb7\",\"authority\":\"6d746984-2e8d-420a-80a6-30517c3c2068\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eKing of the powerful kingdom of Kośala, centered on the city of Śrāvasti. He was a contemporary of the Buddha Śākyamuni, becoming his disciple and patron.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Prasenajit\",\"tibetan\":\"གསལ་རྒྱལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prasenajit\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gsal rgyal\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6568d3d5-ad8d-41c7-8b38-be0d49a874ce\",\"authority\":\"aaedd3e6-aef7-4868-a158-176dec0de0c0\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"pregnant\",\"tibetan\":\"སྦྲུམ་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gurviṇī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sbrum ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3ad6f2dc-0ca5-4a52-b962-3a386f6efbc8\",\"authority\":\"f5acca21-a12e-40ad-b93a-29c99ea763b5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSee \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/cfa524c8-530f-42c5-84f4-76db1acd64db\\\"/\u003en.1024\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"preliminary practice\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡོངས་སུ་སྦྱང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kṛtaparikarma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yongs su sbyang ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f8c8ec2d-b6d2-44e6-8bb4-e6e34938f56f\",\"authority\":\"15a82eab-8cb4-48b0-ad11-094c9360334a\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"prey on weakness\",\"tibetan\":\"གླགས་ལྟ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"avatāragaveṣin\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"glags lta ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"773a28c0-d269-4a83-add8-cf1a172979ae\",\"authority\":\"e7fb12a3-1780-4825-a1b3-56cd93672dbe\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"principal characteristics of a great person\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐྱེས་བུ་ཆེན་པོའི་མཚན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahā­puruṣa­lakṣaṇāni\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skyes bu chen po’i mtshan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2e6ab6d0-661a-4953-a0ea-8227e8db9f31\",\"authority\":\"df69d052-37cb-446f-9930-f5eee491b669\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"proceeded based on faith, proceeding based on faith, proceeds based on faith\",\"tibetan\":\"དད་པས་རྗེས་སུ་འབྲང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śraddhānusāri\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dad pas rjes su ’brang\"}},{\"uuid\":\"73ffcea3-c020-438d-897b-328f0090cdfe\",\"authority\":\"5d9efc50-71a9-4a5c-bcda-d7a37afe102c\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"profit greatly\",\"tibetan\":\"རྙེད་པ་ལེགས་པར་རྙེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"lābhāḥ sulabdhā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnyed pa legs par rnyed pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a2963fa5-8af6-4003-9a92-f499ea9c2212\",\"authority\":\"ace100da-b895-4eef-b5ab-c505affd8785\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe twelfth of the thirteen levels of the god realm of form that correspond to the four meditative concentrations, meaning “Increasing Merit.” In some versions of the longer Prajñāpāramitā sūtras, which list sixteen realms instead of thirteen, this god realm has the name Apramāṇabṛhat (Tib. \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Bo-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003etshad med che ba\u003c/foreign\u003e). \u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Puṇyaprasava\",\"tibetan\":\"བསོད་ནམས་འཕེལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"puṇyaprasava\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bsod nams ’phel\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e938eacd-cc4a-4165-805c-e640d2d846fe\",\"authority\":\"63050a6e-0810-497f-a1fd-0cb013530a20\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eOf the several arhat disciples of the Buddha with the name Pūrṇa, this is Pūrṇa Maitrāyaṇīputra, Pūrṇa the son of Maitrāyaṇī. He is a Śākyan who became an arhat under the guidance of his uncle Ājñātakauṇḍinya before meeting the Buddha (his mother Maitrāyaṇī was Ājñātakauṇḍinya’s sister). He was considered “foremost in teaching.” See the 84000 Knowledge Base article \u003cref target=\\\"https://84000.co/kb-articles/disciples-named-purna#pura-maitrayaiputra\\\"\u003e“Disciples Named Pūrṇa.”\u003c/ref\u003e \u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Pūrṇa\",\"tibetan\":\"གང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pūrṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gang po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cedb8cf4-9d58-40cb-976e-0f841d70f50a\",\"authority\":\"17acbb0d-342f-4ac4-9853-d493afa4fd3e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"qualities of a buddha, quality of a buddha, quality of the buddha\",\"tibetan\":\"སངས་རྒྱས་ཀྱི་ཆོས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"buddhadharma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sangs rgyas kyi chos\"}},{\"uuid\":\"da120fb0-fc39-419b-9f2e-d54611ad0639\",\"authority\":\"440499b7-84dd-446f-8ccf-80bdc0540df3\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"quantify\",\"tibetan\":\"གྲངས་སུ་གཏོགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gaṇanā kṛtā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"grangs su gtogs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5d05565c-7425-4bfd-bd3c-e6512ac83dd2\",\"authority\":\"b5a161b5-2aa7-4c37-a473-82556d4a3e8b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe ancient capital of Magadha prior to its relocation to Pāṭaliputra during the Mauryan dynasty, Rājagṛha is one of the most important locations in Buddhist history. The literature tells us that the Buddha and his saṅgha spent a considerable amount of time in residence in and around Rājagṛha‍—in nearby places, such as the Vulture Peak Mountain (Gṛdhrakūṭaparvata), a major site of the Mahāyāna sūtras, and the Bamboo Grove (Veṇuvana)‍—enjoying the patronage of King Bimbisāra and then of his son King Ajātaśatru. Rājagṛha is also remembered as the location where the first Buddhist monastic council was held after the Buddha Śākyamuni passed into parinirvāṇa. Now known as Rajgir and located in the modern Indian state of Bihar.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Rājagṛha\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱལ་པོའི་ཁབ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"rājagṛha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyal po’i khab\"}},{\"uuid\":\"684a5a75-847b-4219-9ec1-eea81f33f645\",\"authority\":\"e0721416-150d-4272-aa81-956901b15c3d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eA bodhisattva named in this scripture as presently living in the buddhafield of the Buddha Akṣobhya.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ratnaketu\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་པོ་ཆེའི་ཏོག\",\"sanskrit\":\"ratnaketu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin po che’i tog\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c64a4d19-2f1a-4884-94d5-de59f7215265\",\"authority\":\"0ca118cc-a365-4a18-816b-efae44c945b2\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"ready mind\",\"tibetan\":\"སེམས་བདེ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kalyacitta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sems bde ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"eac0590f-cb36-4ca8-8fe6-d939c279cf6e\",\"authority\":\"cadd961b-3209-4461-ab80-b6e8eb5f64ec\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eFor an explanation of the term \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003esatkāya\u003c/foreign\u003e in this sense, used in such contexts as that of the Buddha’s body, as at \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/0115ac3b-9f32-44d4-bbce-c7cd0e5ce9c1\\\"/\u003e4.2\u003c/a\u003e, compared to the more usual “transitory collection,” see \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/d60694a0-b636-4e83-b104-ec86a6012cd1\\\"/\u003en.341\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"real body\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐུ་དམ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"satkāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sku dam pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"142a40b5-25c5-4943-a946-b060ea85a380\",\"authority\":\"7dda09e8-3e52-4303-b92b-e35096e57220\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"realizing the inexhaustible\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་ཟད་པ་མངོན་པར་བསྒྲུབ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"akṣayābhinirhāra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi zad pa mngon par bsgrub pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2dc8942a-1031-478b-b5b2-7aeffce30f22\",\"authority\":\"618a3a84-b3cd-4fcc-a864-b72aa260df03\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"rebuff\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་མཐུན་པར་རྗོད་པར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prativāṇī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi mthun par rjod par\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b9a61e36-059d-4e4a-a7f9-571be03108f9\",\"authority\":\"5b55d66b-5a09-42cb-8576-b54b569fef33\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"referent of the word\",\"tibetan\":\"གཞིའི་དོན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"padārtha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzhi’i don\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8a9caeff-2d39-411f-bc8d-cc742eee6aa6\",\"authority\":\"e475b4d4-2d13-4ddb-9949-98b497dcb6a4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSanskrit syntax uses the noun “refinement,” often translated as “purification.” \u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"refine\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡོངས་སུ་དག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pariśuddhi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yongs su dag pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"12bd0868-347f-44e7-a828-bfece3f113f9\",\"authority\":\"79bcd211-8726-46cd-8c5e-7a960d6bea4f\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"regional king\",\"tibetan\":\"མཁར་གྱི་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"koṭṭarāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mkhar gyi rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"280eec93-756a-42ca-ad23-701012f25a46\",\"authority\":\"a7367f8d-48a1-43de-b929-09d0558ee336\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"reliant\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉེ་བར་བརྟན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"upastabdha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nye bar brtan pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d4c8daa3-6129-4c68-9b07-48fa3a7973b6\",\"authority\":\"b72040dc-e0f7-4d9d-9ed9-ff2fb7d1d3de\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"relinquish\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤོང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prahīna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spong ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9d1b2cb9-d22d-4300-86e4-3541a30b7763\",\"authority\":\"6a2fc45c-110f-486b-8670-414acf8d8e19\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"repeatedly practices, repeatedly practicing\",\"tibetan\":\"གོམས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ābhyāsata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"goms pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ef6ab2e1-1656-4ac2-909e-91650d605c4d\",\"authority\":\"66fed278-2736-42a2-8a11-78e286968661\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"replete with all excellent qualities\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣམ་པ་ཐམས་ཅད་ཀྱི་མཆོག་དང་ལྡན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sarvākāravaropeta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam pa thams cad kyi mchog dang ldan pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"707c77e9-456a-4996-887a-8e8cc1cd9503\",\"authority\":\"51890b59-9675-43e3-8f9b-ac089ae43e44\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eScholar and translator also known as Zhalu Lotsawa (1441–1527). Renowned particularly for his expertise in Sanskrit. See bio at \u003cref target=\\\"https://treasuryoflives.org/biographies/view/Chokyong-Zangpo/11285\\\"\u003eTreasury of Lives\u003c/ref\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Rinchen Chökyong Zangpo\",\"tibetan\":\"ཞ་ལུ་ལོ་ཙཱ་བ་རིན་ཆེན་ཆོས་སྐྱོང་བཟང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zha lu lo tsA ba rin chen chos skyong bzang po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b3117f6c-8b33-404c-93db-0e331ab39488\",\"authority\":\"8ec374b1-5c6e-436b-ac28-bcd599362bec\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Rinchen Zangpo\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་ཆེན་བཟང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin chen bzang po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a98fb9e4-a24c-4692-864b-0a863947bcb4\",\"authority\":\"5b6cfd82-901e-41a0-a7c8-b8c32d5ff267\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"rise above, rising above\",\"tibetan\":\"མངོན་པར་འཕགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhyudgata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mngon par ’phags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b22c6e0e-bb50-4565-8f11-7809e85ba449\",\"authority\":\"c8be3eb7-6160-42d8-ac1f-fdc55cc66af0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eAccording to most lists (specifically those of the Pāli and some Abhidharma traditions), the (three) roots of virtue or the roots of the good or wholesome states (of mind) are what makes a mental state good or bad; they are identified as the opposites of the three mental “poisons” of greed, hatred, and delusion. Actions based on the roots of virtue will eventually lead to future happiness. The \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eDharmasaṃgraha\u003c/cite\u003e, however, lists the three roots of virtue as (1) the mind of awakening, (2) purity of thought, and (3) freedom from egotism (Skt. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003etrīṇi kuśala­mūlāni\u003c/em\u003e | \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ebodhi­cittotpādaḥ\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eāśayaviśuddhiḥ\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eahaṃkāramama­kāraparityāgaśceti\u003c/em\u003e|). \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"root of virtue, roots of virtue\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་བའི་རྩ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kuśalamūla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge ba’i rtsa ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c7fa2a32-c71f-43ed-8ce3-d769f5bfd939\",\"authority\":\"1adb9d47-1b19-42c3-9b33-10f13c2ce686\",\"definition\":\"$51\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sadāprarudita\",\"tibetan\":\"རྟག་ཏུ་ངུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sadāprarudita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rtag tu ngu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"39606232-7abe-46f6-835e-51128b461ce9\",\"authority\":\"6fbdb5b0-3b2a-4d90-a1e1-76b9a42657e0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eAn epithet of Indra, the god who presides over the Heaven of the Thirty-Three, and appears in many Buddhist texts, usually referred to using this name and addressed by his personal name Kauśika, as both protector and disciple of the Buddha. In the Perfection of Wisdom sūtras he is an important interlocutor.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śakra\",\"tibetan\":\"བརྒྱ་བྱིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śakra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"brgya byin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1832c605-dce5-4def-b570-22d8bf717b5d\",\"authority\":\"5639292d-64cd-48c8-b5a4-fcc21d5b497a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eName of the ancient tribe in which the Buddha was born as a prince; their kingdom was based to the east of Kośala, in the foothills near the present-day border of India and Nepal, with Kapilavastu as its capital.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śākya\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤཱཀྱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śākya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shAkya\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cb964334-adc9-4c58-9b74-5659b1047a31\",\"authority\":\"6b2196c0-2f4d-4716-814b-3908c0787587\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eAn eighth-century Indian paṇḍita who participated in translation from Sanskrit into Tibetan.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śākyasena\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"śākyasena\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3df1bcb6-86da-4978-8191-8dbd8f56b919\",\"authority\":\"028f92a7-eb1f-4d2a-9d19-a4c4c188481c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eOne of the Buddha’s closest and most able śrāvaka disciples, who had the moniker “foremost in learning”; also known as Śāradvatīputra. While in some Mahāyāna sūtras he is almost ridiculed in his role as an interlocutor representing the limited view of the disciples’ awakening, in the Perfection of Wisdom sūtras he is treated with respect but nevertheless expresses an understanding less vast than that of Subhūti, also a disciple.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e  \u003cp\u003eOne of the principal śrāvaka disciples of the Buddha, he was renowned for his discipline and for having been praised by the Buddha as foremost of the wise (often paired with Maudgalyā­yana, who was praised as foremost in the capacity for miraculous powers). His father, Tiṣya, to honor Śāriputra’s mother, Śārikā, named him Śāradvatīputra, or, in its contracted form, Śāriputra, meaning “Śārikā’s Son.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śāriputra\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śāriputra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shA ri’i bu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"de4c86bf-cc48-4608-9fa1-da94cf561735\",\"authority\":\"0dd64cdb-866f-48d6-9d93-3bd09af4135d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe term along with “voidness” (q.v.), has a variety of meanings, including empty and emptiness, and is also rendered in this text as “void” (q.v.) in other contexts. See also \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/5a40e91c-acae-48bf-b029-614b1fa3fd17\\\"/\u003en.1094\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"secluded, seclusion, void\",\"tibetan\":\"དབེན་པ།, དབེན་པ།, དབེན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"viveka, viveka, vivikta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dben pa, dben pa, dben pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"843397c4-de1c-4e2f-94c8-7f6447c071d5\",\"authority\":\"0dd64cdb-866f-48d6-9d93-3bd09af4135d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe term, along with “voidness” (q.v.), has a range of meanings, including empty and emptiness, but also a connotation of separation, rendered in this text as “seclusion” (q.v.) in certain contexts. See also \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/5a40e91c-acae-48bf-b029-614b1fa3fd17\\\"/\u003en.1094\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"secluded, seclusion, void\",\"tibetan\":\"དབེན་པ།, དབེན་པ།, དབེན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"viveka, viveka, vivikta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dben pa, dben pa, dben pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"06616fd0-7838-4433-a3e6-d142d6f50b29\",\"authority\":\"0dd64cdb-866f-48d6-9d93-3bd09af4135d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eOften also translated in this text as “devoid.” See also “voidness,” “void,” “seclusion,” and \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/5a40e91c-acae-48bf-b029-614b1fa3fd17\\\"/\u003en.1094\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"secluded, seclusion, void\",\"tibetan\":\"དབེན་པ།, དབེན་པ།, དབེན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"viveka, viveka, vivikta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dben pa, dben pa, dben pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"efacd175-91b7-484b-bfa8-68325bbdd6b2\",\"authority\":\"d302495a-694e-4ba5-a8e7-294fb46c1e63\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe direct witnessing of the distinctive knowing of liberation. One of the five “masses” (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003eskandha\u003c/foreign\u003e) particular to bodhisattvas. See notes \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/fe462982-6a3a-4b98-91e0-4c3b3cc314d9\\\"/\u003en.69\u003c/a\u003e and \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/ff25491f-137c-4103-884c-d2c385feecbd\\\"/\u003en.399\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"seeing the knowing of liberation\",\"tibetan\":\"གྲོལ་བའི་ཡེ་ཤེས་མཐོང་བ།, རྣམ་པར་གྲོལ་བའི་ཡེ་ཤེས་གཟིགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vimukti­jñāna­darśana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"grol ba’i ye shes mthong ba, rnam par grol ba’i ye shes gzigs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6a04e588-3afb-493b-b72a-f4c294a63f4e\",\"authority\":\"5fffaf6c-b938-4182-b91d-57a90be7be61\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sign, superficial feature\",\"tibetan\":\"མཚན་མ།, མཚན་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nimitta, nimitta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mtshan ma, mtshan ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5475bf32-88c2-4471-9cf6-eff28ffb3061\",\"authority\":\"5fffaf6c-b938-4182-b91d-57a90be7be61\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eAn inherent quality, like, for instance, the whiteness of a (white) cow. See \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/1af2e9ed-1e0a-4774-b0c7-87414484171b\\\"/\u003en.881\u003c/a\u003e\u003c!--note 874--\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sign, superficial feature\",\"tibetan\":\"མཚན་མ།, མཚན་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nimitta, nimitta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mtshan ma, mtshan ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f1b4c1aa-966e-462d-bb08-966fc8af7528\",\"authority\":\"25b4708f-9ff8-4f17-b58f-274a68284bd6\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe movements and sounds of the earthquakes that accompany a tathāgata’s realization of perfect awakening. See \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/f059a41a-2c11-4352-b06d-13ec1e6bdb18\\\"/\u003en.870\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"six changes\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣམ་པར་འགྱུར་བ་དྲུག\",\"sanskrit\":\"ṣaḍvikāraḥ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam par ’gyur ba drug\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cd0f4fae-60bd-44f4-a329-c3cf62644124\",\"authority\":\"4642579f-b854-496e-adc4-58924a4ddfae\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"small-minded\",\"tibetan\":\"བློ་ཆུང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"alpabuddhi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"blo chung ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"91eb4850-6549-4ee5-ae57-ec33c68112f1\",\"authority\":\"a2b21a1c-2244-4290-b73f-c2154eb27f11\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSomeone who has realized an awakening comparable to that of an arhat but without hearing the teachings of a buddha, on his or her own in isolation, and does not teach a path to others.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"solitary realizer\",\"tibetan\":\"རང་སངས་རྒྱས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pratyekabuddha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rang sangs rgyas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"41253775-b217-44fb-8aff-7d84d261319e\",\"authority\":\"b559d5ab-d7d5-4512-b6c5-09d203648856\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe name of one of the four gardens of Dharmodgata’s estate in Gandhavatī.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sorrow Free\",\"tibetan\":\"མྱ་ངན་བྲལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śokavigataṃ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mya ngan bral\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7fe7eeef-cc10-4e6b-ab6f-7f42a2725573\",\"authority\":\"3f0dc847-c791-4995-a9d4-bf3fb485724f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe name of one of the four gardens of Dharmodgata’s estate in Gandhavatī.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sorrowless\",\"tibetan\":\"མྱ་ངན་མེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aśoka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mya ngan med\"}},{\"uuid\":\"512bf5e4-ce16-4a44-9470-314d880dbc52\",\"authority\":\"ebb48fae-4edb-40ff-b9e7-188a2a3f4a98\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"source of qualities, ultimate realm of things\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་ཀྱི་དབྱིངས།, ཆོས་ཀྱི་དབྱིངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmadhātu, dharmadhātu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos kyi dbyings, chos kyi dbyings\"}},{\"uuid\":\"11e511b8-43dc-46a3-9026-37be0e9ad47d\",\"authority\":\"ebb48fae-4edb-40ff-b9e7-188a2a3f4a98\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"source of qualities, ultimate realm of things\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་ཀྱི་དབྱིངས།, ཆོས་ཀྱི་དབྱིངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmadhātu, dharmadhātu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos kyi dbyings, chos kyi dbyings\"}},{\"uuid\":\"97a4deca-2db4-4fd3-9943-31e3a6c22619\",\"authority\":\"9582c127-af6b-4368-9adb-3aff0837cd85\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"spiritual qualities\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་བའི་ཆོས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kalyāṇadharma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge ba’i chos\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c6eeefbc-2b12-4439-986c-1c38ae18a036\",\"authority\":\"4204829c-4c4b-4dc2-81db-5a65ff51eb9e\",\"definition\":\"$52\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śreṇika\",\"tibetan\":\"ཕྲེང་བ་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śreṇika\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"phreng ba can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"57c937d0-b335-4e93-b9ad-8534fa62a493\",\"authority\":\"c4a8c27b-cfe9-471c-ae59-3f21920b35a4\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"state of a worthy one\",\"tibetan\":\"དགྲ་བཅོམ་པ་ཉིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"arhattva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dgra bcom pa nyid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"06c4dd9a-a7f6-41fb-8826-06c47108934b\",\"authority\":\"90f35cee-4ac2-45ca-ae7d-8b9054c45d66\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eTenth of the thirteen god realms of form that correspond to the four meditative concentrations, meaning “Most Extensive Virtue.”\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śubhakṛtsna\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་རྒྱས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śubhakṛtsna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge rgyas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"394ccfa8-a88d-4d4a-82ef-d7e988d2fc9b\",\"authority\":\"49683249-3acc-459d-a835-81f51f85c518\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eA tenth-century Indian paṇḍita who participated in translation from Sanskrit into Tibetan.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Subhāṣita\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"subhāṣita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"22f9f523-3d5f-4683-ac40-82bee1ab5a5f\",\"authority\":\"9ae8a691-3333-4856-9d49-ea92ff3cd94b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eA disciple of the Buddha whose uniquely important role in the Perfection of Wisdom sūtras is to express and draw out the Buddha’s teaching on the perfection of wisdom, at the Buddha’s instigation, for the benefit of the audience of bodhisattvas although he himself is not among their number. Hari’s gloss: “He whose mental gift (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\"\u003ebhūtiḥ\u003c/foreign\u003e\u0026lt;\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\"\u003esampatti\u003c/foreign\u003e) is brilliance is (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\"\u003esu\u003c/foreign\u003e\u0026lt;\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\"\u003eśobhanā\u003c/foreign\u003e) foremost among those dwelling without conflict.” See also \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/ce682850-4446-4e92-b9e4-da871259b68d\\\"/\u003en.100\u003c/a\u003e, and for more on Subhūti see the introduction to the \u003ccite xml:lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eTwenty-Five Thousand\u003c/cite\u003e, \u003cref target=\\\"/translation/toh9.html#UT22084-026-001-21005\\\"\u003ei.78–90\u003c/ref\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Subhūti\",\"tibetan\":\"རབ་འབྱོར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"subhūti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rab ’byor\"}},{\"uuid\":\"922c15ba-fbb8-4764-be97-54a49a39229b\",\"authority\":\"a505d15b-71fe-4369-a62b-2dba3be79a0b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe eighty secondary physical characteristics of a buddha and of other great beings (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003emahāpuruṣa\u003c/em\u003e), which include such details as the redness of the fingernails and the blackness of the hair. They are considered “minor” in terms of being secondary to the thirty-two major marks or signs of a great being.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"subsidiary characteristics\",\"tibetan\":\"དཔེ་བྱད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anuvyañjanāni\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dpe byad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8af97a5c-29da-4eee-8ca2-2bc0522459c9\",\"authority\":\"16feb0d8-7415-470a-b641-b8c801167813\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"subtle hints\",\"tibetan\":\"ཐབས་ཕྲ་མོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sūkṣmeṇopāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"thabs phra mo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f587b001-44f4-4048-845d-8952d22f1ea5\",\"authority\":\"2e858dd3-b93d-4be6-aa7e-8cfdd9549e2a\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"subtle mindset\",\"tibetan\":\"སེམས་རྒྱ་ཆེན་པོ་མ་ཡིན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"avipulāni cittāni\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sems rgya chen po ma yin pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fd67b187-10df-4d63-a298-e1aa3ba34613\",\"authority\":\"230c8d1b-9468-4cf7-a72b-e15a00cd970f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eFourth of the five pure abodes, meaning “Extreme Insight.” Also the name of the principal city of the Heaven of the Thirty-Three.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sudarśana\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤིན་ཏུ་མཐོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sudarśana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shin tu mthong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4463e381-57dd-4277-b078-a2fcf2af7b22\",\"authority\":\"e9ae4f71-d873-4b82-bee9-bf559a7b53fe\",\"definition\":\"$53\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śuddhāvāsa\",\"tibetan\":\"གནས་གཙང་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śuddhāvāsa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnas gtsang ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"28dac5fc-1872-4ce1-87e8-e8ddfab20425\",\"authority\":\"b4e8696c-9f1d-42bd-8777-f7e6f37e7995\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe assembly hall in the center of Sudarśana, the city in the Heaven of the Thirty-Three (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eTrāyastriṃśa\u003c/em\u003e). It has a central throne for Indra (Śakra) and thirty-two thrones arranged to its right and left for the other thirty-two devas that make up the eponymous thirty-three devas of Indra’s paradise. Indra’s own palace is to the north of this assembly hall.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sudharma\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་བཟང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sudharma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos bzang\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2ba8f490-deb6-46b9-b264-c9a4235d2d42\",\"authority\":\"d995af90-8e59-4f3d-9e08-31c4b4b21761\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThird of the five pure abodes, meaning “Attractive.”\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sudṛśa\",\"tibetan\":\"གྱ་ནོམ་སྣང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sudṛśa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gya nom snang\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f204ed92-9b0b-444c-8ddd-e7c13c7036db\",\"authority\":\"ff79a6be-1e3d-441b-a66b-7b6b5d087319\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"supernormal supports\",\"tibetan\":\"རྫུ་འཕྲུལ་གྱི་རྐང་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ṛddhipādaḥ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rdzu ’phrul gyi rkang pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c0bb1887-4c4e-40b7-8df3-101f6b271c23\",\"authority\":\"3f223880-614a-47b9-a8c3-af47cb3d3627\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"supported, utterly supported\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡོངས་སུ་གཟུང་བ།, ཡོངས་སུ་བཟུང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"parigṛhīta, parigṛhītā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yongs su bzung ba, yongs su gzung ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"169c2ad8-dc41-4a8b-81d2-fa783b5d4211\",\"authority\":\"3f223880-614a-47b9-a8c3-af47cb3d3627\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSee \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/4c68459b-28b8-4884-800f-3b78d5baf15e\\\"/\u003en.307\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"supported, utterly supported\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡོངས་སུ་གཟུང་བ།, ཡོངས་སུ་བཟུང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"parigṛhīta, parigṛhītā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yongs su bzung ba, yongs su gzung ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6882b83e-6d4d-4178-8652-768c0ab6b718\",\"authority\":\"fb8ba4bf-a793-4c65-ab9e-cfeaccf913df\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"supreme perfection\",\"tibetan\":\"ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་སོན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"paramapārami\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"pha rol tu son pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4f4f5cf1-9362-4864-aad0-7a01354e4536\",\"authority\":\"6ab6c8b7-9711-489a-b353-3a16f4dd5f05\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"taking what is not given\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་བྱིན་པར་ལེན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"adattādāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma byin par len pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ba88d417-b0e3-432a-babf-877a261cff8b\",\"authority\":\"285a8525-75c9-4ab3-8d61-e257c5eb21ce\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eA \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/foreign\u003e is a buddha, one who has come from or gone to (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003eāgata\u003c/foreign\u003e or \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003egata\u003c/foreign\u003e) the actual nature (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003etathā\u003c/foreign\u003e), often etymologized as one who has “come to the way things are.” Ratnākaraśānti also glosses a tathāgata as one who has clarified the actual way things are (see \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/97d0c84e-f8c1-471c-9804-492a53eda3b7\\\"/\u003en.255\u003c/a\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"tathāgata\",\"tibetan\":\"དེ་བཞིན་གཤེགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tathāgata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"de bzhin gshegs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6fea0604-1e66-4e5e-b771-83205bf1c70d\",\"authority\":\"4a03dbbd-2f94-42f9-ba68-7ecc213d957c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe name of one of eight lotus pools in each of the gardens of Dharmodgata’s estate in Gandhavatī.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Temperate\",\"tibetan\":\"ངེས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"niyatā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nges pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"bb4fb512-0bd3-4e79-994c-c6cf9d432a02\",\"authority\":\"f7142ca3-ab9e-4d35-abac-304787568d4f\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"temple hall\",\"tibetan\":\"དཀྱིལ་འཁོར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhramaṇḍapa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dkyil ’khor\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7dac2a1e-1ed3-4816-9b8d-4e9ae2fd9a0d\",\"authority\":\"50455ffe-57ed-4802-83d7-95c67b3ab35e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSee \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/e78cd953-87e6-4025-93ae-0d19169f228e\\\"/\u003en.124\u003c/a\u003e\u003c!--note 122--\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"ten powers\",\"tibetan\":\"སྟོབས་བཅུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"daśabala\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"stobs bcu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"13b45b8e-d487-4bd2-beeb-aae9daae6fd8\",\"authority\":\"e4baac20-63c7-4a5c-ba5b-1864d6b49a6a\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"ten virtuous ways of acting\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་བ་བཅུའི་ལས་ཀྱི་ལམ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"daśa­kuśala­karma­patha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge ba bcu’i las kyi lam\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c8930b91-fdcb-40b8-ab5f-b63ffcafc7a7\",\"authority\":\"c3efd692-c59d-48d4-b6d3-d01d5c860871\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"thing that produces merit, thing that produces the merit\",\"tibetan\":\"བསོད་ནམས་བྱ་བའི་དངོས་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"puṇyakriyāvastu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bsod nams bya ba’i dngos po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e1ec55ce-1999-4c91-9f2d-3096113283c3\",\"authority\":\"3794e156-ffa6-4520-bfa1-8fe37a39cb39\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"things and nonthings\",\"tibetan\":\"དངོས་པོ་དང་དངོས་པོ་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhāvābhāva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dngos po dang dngos po med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c542957b-778b-4c58-9fd1-cd0bce29cc00\",\"authority\":\"8a3d70f8-04a8-4c22-908e-5d96144a3e27\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSee \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/f293ea18-7a51-49aa-b184-f1a1f975484f\\\"/\u003en.219\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"thirty-seven factors in awakening\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱང་ཆུབ་ཀྱི་ཕྱོགས་ཀྱི་ཆོས་སུམ་ཅུ་རྩ་བདུན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"saptatriṃśad bodhipakṣā dharmā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub kyi phyogs kyi chos sum cu rtsa bdun\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5d31124e-6a79-41ff-9dc5-d20638b00ecd\",\"authority\":\"e5e6de0b-23b0-48fa-a422-57b5cba6332d\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"totality of causes and conditions\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱུ་དང་རྐྱེན་ཚོགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"hetu­pratyaya­sāmagrī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyu dang rkyen tshogs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2539148a-b7d6-49c3-9dc3-aa394305d054\",\"authority\":\"ae930331-5399-4946-8b7a-44dcb3b76954\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"transgression\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྟུང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āpatti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ltung ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"14e898b0-8447-497a-98d1-743dc14f6632\",\"authority\":\"bfdbb746-6779-49b1-9b6f-262846a2373e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe mistaken focus of an important category of false views regarding there being a “self” that is related in various ways to the “collection” that is made up of the “transitory” constituents of experience or “constituents underlying the clinging to existence” (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003eskandha\u003c/foreign\u003es). See also \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/86caf8af-7627-4997-a6f9-09dfb7cb8de9\\\"/\u003en.1343\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"transitory collection\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇིག་ཚོགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"satkāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jig tshogs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9c39d3c9-58f0-4cdc-b4f6-dd7ef1c06f1c\",\"authority\":\"bf011878-08d1-4d68-9455-a7036f7d9091\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"trivial\",\"tibetan\":\"ངན་ངོན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"avaraka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ngan ngon\"}},{\"uuid\":\"dd571a94-b6b3-4e5a-acb3-f5c0068a3df0\",\"authority\":\"d5a9ed53-8d7f-4a71-ba55-23fdb5e67fda\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe real nature, true quality, or condition of things. Throughout Buddhist discourse this term is used in two distinct ways. In one, it designates the relative nature that is either the essential characteristic of a specific phenomenon, such as the heat of fire and the moisture of water, or the defining feature of a specific term or category. The other very important and widespread way it is used is to designate the ultimate nature of all phenomena, which cannot be conveyed in conceptual, dualistic terms and is often synonymous with emptiness or the absence of intrinsic existence.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"true nature\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་ཉིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmatā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos nyid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9a355540-ffac-4b2c-a67b-05ab60c4cc16\",\"authority\":\"6e5dc81d-3c8a-493e-9a77-987aa0ef3895\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"truth body\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་ཀྱི་སྐུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmakāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos kyi sku\"}},{\"uuid\":\"df752960-7e84-45ca-b93c-11183cc9ce04\",\"authority\":\"edf1481c-c58e-455d-91ac-4483ead30568\",\"definition\":\"$54\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Tuṣita\",\"tibetan\":\"དགའ་ལྡན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tuṣita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dga’ ldan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d54f7db2-be22-4bb6-8953-4cb74728ec05\",\"authority\":\"351f0b1d-f916-48f2-b514-c6ffa01e7960\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"two extremes\",\"tibetan\":\"མཐའ་གཉིས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"antadvaya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mtha’ gnyis\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d55b254c-92cb-4882-95c0-71542c62ee69\",\"authority\":\"a788cae8-0c9d-45be-ac4b-eda48948b0c8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eAs in other texts, mentions are made of five or six types. The five are (1) the knowledge of various types of magical powers, (2) the divine ear faculty, (3) the knowledge of others’ mindsets, (4) the knowledge that remembers occurrences in previous lives, (5) the divine eye faculty, all these first five being considered “mundane” (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\"\u003elaukika\u003c/foreign\u003e) achievements resulting from the fourth \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/foreign\u003e; they are therefore common to non-Buddhist practitioners. The sixth is (6) knowledge of the exhaustion of worldly influences (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\"\u003eāsravakṣaya\u003c/foreign\u003e), which is a supramundane (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\"\u003elokottara\u003c/foreign\u003e) achievement resulting from \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\"\u003evipaśyana\u003c/foreign\u003e. For explanations of the first five, see \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/81812b8a-d1e3-40ba-b7bf-c518ea28d2b7\\\"/\u003en.382\u003c/a\u003e\u003c!--note 375--\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"types of extrasensory knowledge\",\"tibetan\":\"མངོན་པར་ཤེས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhijñā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mngon par shes pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f0880e20-93b5-4e57-ba47-88569677dc6a\",\"authority\":\"ebdfcccb-d9f9-499d-8402-eab09e76445e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"ultimate resort\",\"tibetan\":\"དཔུང་གཉེན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"parāyaṇaṃ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dpung gnyen\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ec668581-6d76-4685-b567-c8bc7cb3c41e\",\"authority\":\"c559b351-d859-41c3-a1c9-c5c6b323ae07\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eSee also “free of attachment” and “nonattachment.”\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unattached\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་ཆགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"asaṅga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma chags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0221f7aa-d9bb-49b9-86af-d8e716ace9af\",\"authority\":\"d514f645-8f8b-4c0c-a4c6-7f074cc8000f\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unchanged, untransformed\",\"tibetan\":\"འགྱུར་བ་མེད་པའོ།, རྣམ་པར་མ་བསྒྱུར་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"avikṛtā, avikṛtā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam par ma bsgyur ba, ’gyur ba med pa’o\"}},{\"uuid\":\"774c8de1-4765-408e-8e62-1a0b0dee8cd4\",\"authority\":\"d514f645-8f8b-4c0c-a4c6-7f074cc8000f\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unchanged, untransformed\",\"tibetan\":\"འགྱུར་བ་མེད་པའོ།, རྣམ་པར་མ་བསྒྱུར་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"avikṛtā, avikṛtā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam par ma bsgyur ba, ’gyur ba med pa’o\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cd35d9e4-576e-4c60-9d07-144110b0c808\",\"authority\":\"23c245b3-7714-473b-a26f-32bcb0d46dbc\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unconditioned\",\"tibetan\":\"མངོན་པར་འདུས་མ་བྱས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anabhisaṃskṛta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mngon par ’dus ma byas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4434d430-b51a-4219-b09a-897de5306704\",\"authority\":\"154005cf-5cb8-4ca8-b8aa-77151280650e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unconscionable\",\"tibetan\":\"གློ་བ་ལ་གཅགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kaukṛtyaṃ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"glo ba la gcags\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d0bf98ce-1d85-4751-abd2-a3da0982fbd4\",\"authority\":\"f9c9e8f6-c54e-4aed-96d4-4e8f8c6ae23b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"uncreated\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་བགྱིས་པ།, མ་བྱས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"akṛtā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma bgyis pa, ma byas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"21334d35-f81a-462d-8f11-3159cec591aa\",\"authority\":\"bdbc40e7-2545-4eba-82b8-32b77d189371\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"under the influence of Māra’s magical power\",\"tibetan\":\"བདུད་ཀྱི་བྱིན་གྱིས་བརླབས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mārādhiṣṭhita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bdud kyi byin gyis brlabs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"46f2a296-7357-49fe-ae2e-19a49ada7bc0\",\"authority\":\"3e523fee-f637-4794-9b63-632a8f392842\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"undifferentiable actual nature\",\"tibetan\":\"གཞན་མ་ཡིན་པའི་དེ་བཞིན་ཉིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ananyatathatā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gzhan ma yin pa’i de bzhin nyid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7c1799ea-7242-4208-a69e-5412a2e29c2d\",\"authority\":\"d7be350c-e276-4d42-b78b-7b2daf88d34f\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unenmeshed\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་གཏོགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aparyāpanna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma gtogs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2c1636de-e437-4af8-8145-08cb7335d974\",\"authority\":\"4c1bb3f1-afea-46e3-a816-847cb066cebc\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unentangled\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་ཆགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"asakta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma chags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9212e3e6-5e47-4184-955a-8d5c84543d8c\",\"authority\":\"43108fd7-7574-4e75-ab05-c50a05ee1420\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unequaled\",\"tibetan\":\"མཉམ་པ་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"atulya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mnyam pa med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f58a3224-f54a-4976-b3c5-9c1583342572\",\"authority\":\"7e97bca4-c4df-40eb-8db6-bff1c58008b8\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unfalsifiable actual nature\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་ལོག་པའི་དེ་བཞིན་ཉིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"avitathatā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma log pa’i de bzhin nyid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"310dc75f-b046-4d4e-bf5d-d180a968fbb5\",\"authority\":\"136a014a-9bc9-471e-a1fe-719136759e36\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unfrightened mindset\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡིད་མི་སྐྲག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anuttrastamānasa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yid mi skrag pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9fcae89e-a2a1-4758-bd41-dbff4d145fb6\",\"authority\":\"db64d858-57ad-4f02-9ebb-847dc4ae0770\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unharmed\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་སྣད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anupahata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma snad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d59dc8d2-9f9d-4fcc-83f7-6a956fc587cb\",\"authority\":\"ab630110-e938-411f-b545-5ce96812977f\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"uninjured\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་སྨས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"akṛta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma smas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8d017774-aa9d-4033-a6a0-fda55fba03c3\",\"authority\":\"a47639c2-1710-446a-ae45-5cfb6551d616\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe Tibetan translates both \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003eapramāṇa\u003c/foreign\u003e and \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003eaparimāṇa\u003c/foreign\u003e as \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Bo-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003etshad med pa\u003c/foreign\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unlimited\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚད་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aparimāṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshad med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"36a946e2-7f4b-4c18-ae03-46864436b78f\",\"authority\":\"91d02b5d-0070-4b0b-b9bd-39fbdb2ddcd5\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unproliferating\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤྲོས་པ་མ་མཆིས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aprapañca\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spros pa ma mchis pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2019b5f0-cfe4-4d1d-92b5-73a9245488bd\",\"authority\":\"f5c3ee19-4495-42d1-abb0-efbfee31236e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unshared\",\"tibetan\":\"ཐུན་མོང་མ་ལགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"asādhāraṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"thun mong ma lags pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a4b4781f-82e4-4c69-835c-0d5e48c47a02\",\"authority\":\"755ca903-aca9-485e-83c4-a410a927ec53\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unsurpassable\",\"tibetan\":\"ཟིལ་གྱིས་མི་ནོན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anabhibhūta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zil gyis mi non pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"025da177-4bdf-47b4-b3f7-639bedf16eb9\",\"authority\":\"ea1e107c-77b9-427a-ae7e-5ef330020201\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unsurpassed\",\"tibetan\":\"བླ་ན་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anuttara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bla na med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0938e97e-16e8-4dc8-90a9-f0e0a58c7160\",\"authority\":\"65bc0ad1-0ff7-4242-9648-b5610bee9602\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unvirtuous friend\",\"tibetan\":\"སྡིག་པའི་གྲོགས་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pāpamitra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sdig pa’i grogs po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"af03d367-aed3-4d32-aeb7-e599064f4c82\",\"authority\":\"7a667176-f52b-4cd0-9144-9c551dafeabf\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unwavering\",\"tibetan\":\"བརྟན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dṛḍha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"brtan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a46d6a95-a6d5-49af-8068-a26aab200bea\",\"authority\":\"4fa75224-9358-47e9-8306-f922c749e6cb\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"uphold\",\"tibetan\":\"སྲུང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"rakṣati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"srung ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ad7eee76-e531-4c8d-a6e7-c74cf30a718c\",\"authority\":\"6d2a3fb0-8bb5-4486-95a8-33ce6ac2a229\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"uplifted mindset\",\"tibetan\":\"སེམས་རབ་ཏུ་བཟུང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pragṛhītāni cittāni\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sems rab tu bzung ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9ee5c550-3cb3-445a-a658-565f8bfd3d45\",\"authority\":\"e23ad958-a5a4-48d3-83ad-28ae572e54b2\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe palace of Śakra (Indra) in the Heaven of the Thirty-Three.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vaijayanta Palace\",\"tibetan\":\"རྣམ་པར་རྒྱལ་བའི་ཁང་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vaijayanta­prāsāda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rnam par rgyal ba’i khang pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"85a0e3f1-ad8c-44ce-839f-8903612b40ba\",\"authority\":\"3d58ef2a-3ca7-41be-bc51-6e392c9774e7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eVajrapāṇi means “Wielder of the Vajra.” In the Pali canon, he appears as a yakṣa guardian in the retinue of the Buddha. In the Mahāyāna scriptures he is a bodhisattva and one of the “eight close sons of the Buddha.” In the tantras, he is also regarded as an important Buddhist deity and instrumental in the transmission of tantric scriptures. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vajrapāṇi\",\"tibetan\":\"ལག་ན་རྡོ་རྗེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vajrapāṇi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lag na rdo rje\"}},{\"uuid\":\"91107107-3f31-4442-8365-9099041efadf\",\"authority\":\"c93c2e27-5650-435e-b7b4-4a0ba26dad8f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eA term of address for monks, meaning “blessed in life.” “fortunate,” “possessed of life’s (joy).” See \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/9afe2818-6a0a-487f-84cb-ea3d9a38f626\\\"/\u003en.81\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"venerable\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ayuṣmān\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshe dang ldan pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"803ba49d-1a79-42c7-a363-0cde26f4d5e4\",\"authority\":\"15f21e33-302e-4196-bb71-d8de9ca7a4eb\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"virtuous\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kalyāṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d40bc2f8-5a66-4112-b5c8-799cc534a17b\",\"authority\":\"d1577cef-f674-4c5b-8d02-859939561e36\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"virtuous and unvirtuous qualities\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་བ་དང་མི་དགེ་བའི་ཆོས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kuśalākuśala­dharma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge ba dang mi dge ba’i chos\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cb1774cb-402d-465e-a33f-c45b2edb5bae\",\"authority\":\"9861c4ef-4f1e-4332-bb65-01b36e4285a7\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"virtuous friend\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་བའི་བཤེས་གཉེན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kalyāṇamitra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge ba’i bshes gnyen\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1258a233-15e6-4285-8209-e64d216a9798\",\"authority\":\"fb94d08a-4273-46dc-b857-e1962e88f22b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"vital faculty\",\"tibetan\":\"སྲོག་གི་དབང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"jīvitendriya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"srog gi dbang po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"76fb6812-3e9d-4c5b-98d9-aee79d4a61e9\",\"authority\":\"1eeca287-cfdc-482f-8bd0-060222a4099c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eOften meaning the state of being isolated, solitary, or secluded, but also “lacking (something),” and almost synonymous with “emptiness.” See also “void” and “secluded,” translations of the related term \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\"\u003eviveka\u003c/foreign\u003e (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Bo-Ltn\\\"\u003edben pa\u003c/foreign\u003e) and \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/5a40e91c-acae-48bf-b029-614b1fa3fd17\\\"/\u003en.1094\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"voidness\",\"tibetan\":\"དབེན་པ་ཉིད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"viviktatva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dben pa nyid\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9704e772-b86a-4db9-ae36-ab2e91f2cd8d\",\"authority\":\"d697fbaf-b2e9-4bb9-997f-c77a1c26edfa\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"vulnerability\",\"tibetan\":\"གླགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"avatāra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"glags\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d86dc1c3-f802-46fe-9bd6-4b2321d77a32\",\"authority\":\"260cb623-12cc-40a0-acf0-ce0b1a47aceb\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe Gṛdhra­kūṭa, literally Vulture Peak, was a hill located in the kingdom of Magadha, in the vicinity of the ancient city of Rājagṛha (modern-day Rajgir, in the state of Bihar, India), where the Buddha bestowed many sūtras, especially the Great Vehicle teachings, such as the Prajñāpāramitā sūtras. It continues to be a sacred pilgrimage site for Buddhists to this day.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vulture Peak\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱ་རྒོད་ཀྱི་ཕུང་པོའི་རི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gṛdhrakūṭa-parvata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bya rgod kyi phung po’i ri\"}},{\"uuid\":\"23e021ed-df6a-4f14-a93a-9727a988896c\",\"authority\":\"13823815-16f8-4de5-bde6-265886c9f691\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe first of four stages or experiences of breaking through on the path of preliminary practice.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"warming up, warmth\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ūṣman\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"drod\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8e5153df-d01f-4825-a3b3-d9f0bea924df\",\"authority\":\"282286c0-5aa3-427e-aa45-a255f368db61\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eRatnākara’s gloss suggests that \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003epada\u003c/foreign\u003e here means a “step” along the path rather than the Tibetan translation as “word” (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Bo-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003etshig\u003c/foreign\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"way of proceeding\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚིག་གི་རྣམ་གྲངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"padaparyāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshig gi rnam grangs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"23e821ec-fd7d-4f83-8f04-52fd5cb1324c\",\"authority\":\"f6d22691-401f-41fb-ba79-b091d526b7d4\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"weak mindset\",\"tibetan\":\"སེམས་དམན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"hīnacitta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sems dman pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4ec70a92-384a-4cf4-a887-4dc5f099cd7c\",\"authority\":\"6bf41442-af29-48dd-9faa-a6cec658c5b2\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"weak-minded\",\"tibetan\":\"བློ་དམན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mandabuddhi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"blo dman pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f3510365-2649-4ff1-ba02-c61e0063975c\",\"authority\":\"e7e8e4e9-eff8-458d-bb3c-27b1857e3ba4\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"weak-willed\",\"tibetan\":\"སེམས་པ་དམན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"hīnasattva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sems pa dman pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"da3119d6-8309-4c6c-9706-e9b94b7d8e4b\",\"authority\":\"37faa2ef-6c9a-4a32-b406-16f7cfd1ad52\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"wheel of Dharma\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་ཀྱི་འཁོར་ལོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmacakra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos kyi ’khor lo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"61d00384-8938-4c76-8fdf-5266156492db\",\"authority\":\"c99154be-6441-4ac7-a5bd-d8cfc6cc77fb\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"white water lilies\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀུ་མུ་ད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kumuda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ku mu da\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ac00ca2c-1928-488a-958e-103e94448fb0\",\"authority\":\"f4817ee1-d653-4b17-963e-67bd2b6cb717\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"wisdom truth body\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡེ་ཤེས་ཆོས་ཀྱི་སྐུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"jñānadharma–kāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ye shes chos kyi sku\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2b0d3a59-d064-4f37-895c-4dcaf017a5bc\",\"authority\":\"966019e7-988f-46fc-96b9-d58d04f46d01\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"wish to come near\",\"tibetan\":\"འོང་འདོད་པར་འགྱུར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"upasaṃkramitavyaṃ maṃsyante\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’ong ’dod par ’gyur\"}},{\"uuid\":\"10cd4b1f-a54e-4fb3-a141-1425c2be756f\",\"authority\":\"4b2b6bb3-bab3-4945-86de-a44c642bfac5\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"without any constituents remaining\",\"tibetan\":\"ཕུང་པོ་ལྷག་མ་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anupadhiśeṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"phung po lhag ma med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ee5e5a9f-ef48-49c8-9807-70dc161a1005\",\"authority\":\"2e3c3154-eb67-45ca-bd01-2902827c64ec\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"without equal\",\"tibetan\":\"མཉམ་པ་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"asama\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mnyam pa med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"321cd27d-0c6e-44b0-8da9-89d54c1e9891\",\"authority\":\"514cc592-e440-4073-b4dd-8db37279d096\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"without forsaking\",\"tibetan\":\"བརྩོན་པ་མ་བོར་བར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anikṣiptadhura\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"brtson pa ma bor bar\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4f22fb11-9da9-4711-a6b3-72dbd6ac9ed4\",\"authority\":\"a6d9a77c-56e8-4284-8692-848efcbffb47\",\"definition\":\"$55\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"world system\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་ཁམས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"lokadhātu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jig rten gyi khams\"}},{\"uuid\":\"86981a5b-d566-434a-8400-2956eadee2b8\",\"authority\":\"f856854b-2f97-4d78-be64-3a695244fc89\",\"definition\":\"$56\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"worldly influences\",\"tibetan\":\"ཟག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āsrava\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zag pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3fcaec25-ccff-4616-b4f0-bc31081cb012\",\"authority\":\"d95e6f28-87de-429e-b185-d12873ac760c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eA “worthy one” (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/foreign\u003e) refers to a disciple who has reached the final stage of a disciple’s realization. Indian scholars gave six or more etymologies for \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/foreign\u003e. This translation follows the etymology “someone who is worthy,” i.e., worthy of the generosity (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003eniṇḍārha\u003c/foreign\u003e) of others and worthy of the veneration (\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003epūjārha\u003c/foreign\u003e) of others. Note that Tibetan translators follow a different one: “someone who has eliminated the enemies” \u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003e(ari\u003c/foreign\u003e+\u003cforeign xml:lang=\\\"Sa-Ltn\\\" type=\\\"term\\\"\u003ehatavān\u003c/foreign\u003e), i.e., the emotional defilements. See \u003ca href=\\\"/entity/passage/878933d3-acc1-4ed3-8303-e73285f08705\\\"/\u003en.68\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"worthy one\",\"tibetan\":\"དགྲ་བཅོམ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"arhat\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dgra bcom pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0bfd188b-9094-4805-bdd7-9758fcacf5f7\",\"authority\":\"b6bae17d-8e1c-4f88-bc1d-49f99038a139\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThird god realm of desire, meaning “strifeless.”\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Yāma\",\"tibetan\":\"འཐབ་བྲལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yāma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’thab bral\"}},{\"uuid\":\"895a0815-88b6-4871-8b34-fa2ab5208e06\",\"authority\":\"2e9e5a6b-562b-449d-97c5-1b54d1aae3bc\",\"definition\":\"\u003cnote type=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe name of the future tathāgata that the woman Gaṅgadevī is foreordained to become by the Buddha, in the narrative found in all the long Perfection of Wisdom scriptures. \u003c/p\u003e \u003c/note\u003e \",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Yellow-Flowered\",\"tibetan\":\"གསེར་གྱི་མེ་ཏོག\",\"sanskrit\":\"suvarṇapuṣpa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gser gyi me tog\"}}]}]\n"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"57:I[916077,[\"/_next/static/chunks/2fb4b456dae69409.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/6165fecb8e0eae36.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/1cfd6a6ab8fe5d2f.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/15d7387d42764915.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\"],\"ReaderBodyPanel\"]\n58:T127d,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"དེ་ནས་སངས་རྒྱས་ཀྱི་མཐུས་ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་རབ་འབྱོར་གྱིས་བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་ལ་འདི་སྐད་ཅེས་གསོལ་ཏོ། གང་བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་ཀྱིས་འདི་སྐད་དུ་རབ་འབྱོར་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་རྣམས་ཀྱི་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལས་བརྩམས་ཏེ། ཇི་ལྟར་བྱང་ཆུབ་\nསེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་རྣམས་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བར་འགྱུར་བ་དེ་བཞིན་དུ་ཁྱོད་སྤོབས་པར་བྱོས་ཤིག་ཅེས་བཀའ་སྩལ་པ། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཞེས་བརྗོད་པ་གང་ལགས་པ་དེ་ལ་བཅོམ་ལྡན་\nའདས་འདི་ལྟ་སྟེ་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཞེས་བགྱི་བ་འདི་ཆོས་གང་གི་ཚིག་བླ་དགས་ལགས། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་འདི་ལྟ་སྟེ་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཞེས་བགྱི་བའི་ཆོས་དེ་བདག་གིས་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མ་མཐོང་ངོ་། །བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་འདི་ལྟ་སྟེ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་\nཔ་ཞེས་བགྱི་བའི་ཆོས་དེ་ཡང་བདག་གིས་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མ་མཐོང་ངོ་། །བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་འམ་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའི་ཆོས་ཀྱང་བདག་གིས་མ་འཚལ་མ་དམིགས་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མ་མཐོང་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ཡང་མ་འཚལ། མ་\nདམིགས་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མ་མཐོང་ན་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་གང་ཞིག་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་གང་ལ་གདམས་ཤིང་རྗེས་སུ་བསྟན་པར་བགྱི། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་འོན་ཀྱང་ཡང་གལ་ཏེ་འདི་ལྟར་སྨྲས་པ་དང་བསྟན་པ་དང་ཉེ་བར་བསྟན་པ་ལ། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་\nདཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་སེམས་མི་འགོང་ཀུན་ཏུ་མི་ཞུམ་བག་མི་ཚ། བག་འཁུམས་པར་མི་འགྱུར་འདིའི་ཡིད་ཕྱིར་ཕྱོགས་པར་མི་བགྱིད་བཅོམ་ཞིང་ཕྱིར་ཕྱོགས་པར་མི་འགྱུར། མི་དངང་ཀུན་ཏུ་མི་སྐྲག་ཀུན་ཏུ་སྐྲག་པ་དང་ལྡན་པར་མི་འགྱུར་ན། འདི་ཉིད་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་[F.3.a]དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་རྗེས་སུ་བསྟན་པར་བགྱི་བ་ལགས་སོ། །འདི་ཉིད་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་དེའི་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པར་རིག་པར་བགྱིའོ། །འདི་ཉིད་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་\nགདམས་པ་ལགས་སོ། །གལ་ཏེ་དེ་ལྟར་གནས་ན་དེ་ཉིད་འདིའི་གདམས་པ་དང་རྗེས་སུ་བསྟན་པ་ལགས་སོ། །"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"59:Tceb,བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་གཞན་ཡང་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་\nཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་སྤྱོད་ཅིང་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་བསྒོམ་པས་གཟུགས་ལ་གནས་པར་མི་བགྱིའོ། །དེ་བཞིན་དུ་ཚོར་བ་ལ་མ་ལགས་འདུ་ཤེས་ལ་མ་ལགས་འདུ་བྱེད་རྣམས་ལ་མ་ལགས་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་ལ་གནས་པར་མི་བགྱིའོ། །ཅིའི་སླད་དུ་ཞེ་ན། གལ་ཏེ་\nགཟུགས་ལ་གནས་ན་གཟུགས་མངོན་པར་འདུ་བྱེད་པ་ལ་སྤྱོད་ཀྱི་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་སྤྱོད་པ་མ་ལགས་སོ། །དེ་བཞིན་དུ་གལ་ཏེ་ཚོར་བ་དང་འདུ་ཤེས་དང་འདུ་བྱེད་རྣམས་དང་གལ་ཏེ་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་ལ་གནས་ན་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་མངོན་པར་འདུ་བྱེད་པ་ལ་སྤྱད་ཀྱི་\nཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་སྤྱོད་པ་མ་ལགས་སོ། །དེ་ཅིའི་སླད་དུ་ཞེ་ན། མངོན་པར་འདུ་བྱེད་པ་ལ་སྤྱོད་ན་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ཡོངས་སུ་འཛིན་པ་མ་ལགས་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་རྣལ་འབྱོར་དུ་བགྱིད་པ་ཡང་མ་ལགས་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ཡོངས་\nསུ་རྫོགས་པར་བགྱིད་པ་ཡང་མ་ལགས་སོ། །ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ཡོངས་སུ་རྫོགས་པར་མ་གྱུར་ན་ཡོངས་སུ་མི་གཟུང་བ་ཡོངས་སུ་གཟུང་བས་ཐམས་ཅད་མཁྱེན་པ་ཉིད་ལ་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བར་མི་འགྱུར་རོ། །དེ་ཅིའི་སླད་དུ་ཞེ་ན། ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་\nགཟུགས་ཡོངས་སུ་གཟུང་བ་མ་མཆིས་སོ། །དེ་བཞིན་དུ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་ཚོར་བ་དང་འདུ་ཤེས་དང་འདུ་བྱེད་རྣམས་དང་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་ཡོངས་སུ་གཟུང་བ་མ་མཆིས་སོ། །5a:T11cd,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"དེ་བཞིན་དུ་\nགལ་ཏེ་ཚོར་བ་ལ་མ་ཡིན། འདུ་ཤེས་ལ་མ་ཡིན། འདུ་བྱེད་རྣམས་ལ་མ་ཡིན། གལ་ཏེ་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་ལ་མི་སྤྱོད། རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པའི་མཚན་མ་ལ་མི་སྤྱོད། རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་མཚན་མའོ་སྙམ་དུ་མི་སྤྱོད། རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པའི་སྐྱེ་བ་ལ་མི་སྤྱོད། རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པའི་འགག་\nཔ་ལ་མི་སྤྱོད། རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་འཇིག་པ་ལ་མི་སྤྱོད། རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་སྟོང་པའོ་སྙམ་དུ་མི་སྤྱོད། བདག་སྤྱོད་དོ་སྙམ་དུ་མི་སྤྱོད་དོ། །བདག་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའོ་སྙམ་དུ་མི་སྤྱོད། བདག་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའོ་སྙམ་དུ་དམིགས་པ་ལ་མི་སྤྱོད་ཅིང་། གལ་ཏེ་[F.7.b]ཡང་དེ་འདི་སྙམ་དུ་གང་དེ་ལྟར་སྤྱོད་པ་དེ་ནི་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་སྤྱོད་པ་སྟེ། དེ་ནི་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་སྒོམ་པར་བྱེད་པ་ཡིན་ནོ་སྙམ་དུ་མི་སེམས་པ་སྟེ། །ད་ལྟར་སྤྱོད་པའི་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་ནི་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་\nསྤྱོད་པ་ཡིན་ནོ། །དེ་སྤྱོད་ཀྱང་སྤྱོད་དོ་སྙམ་དུ་ཉེ་བར་མི་རྟོགས། མི་སྤྱོད་དོ་སྙམ་དུ་ཉེ་བར་མི་རྟོགས། སྤྱོད་ཀྱང་སྤྱོད་ལ་མི་སྤྱོད་ཀྱང་མི་སྤྱོད་དོ་སྙམ་དུ་ཉེ་བར་མི་རྟོགས། སྤྱོད་པ་ཡང་མ་ཡིན་ལ་མི་སྤྱོད་པ་ཡང་མ་ཡིན་ནོ་སྙམ་དུ་ཉེ་བར་མི་རྟོགས། སྤྱད་པར་བྱ་བའོ་སྙམ་དུ་ཡང་ཉེ་བར་མི་\nརྟོགས། སྤྱད་པར་མི་བྱའོ་སྙམ་དུ་ཡང་ཉེ་བར་མི་རྟོགས། སྤྱད་པར་བྱ་བ་ཡང་ཡིན་ལ་སྤྱད་པར་མི་བྱ་བ་ཡང་ཡིན་ནོ་སྙམ་དུ་ཉེ་བར་མི་རྟོགས། སྤྱད་པར་བྱ་བ་ཡང་མ་ཡིན་ལ་སྤྱད་པར་མི་བྱ་བ་ཡང་མ་ཡིན་པ་ཉིད་དོ་སྙམ་དུ་ཉེ་བར་མི་རྟོགས་སོ། །དེ་ཅིའི་ཕྱིར་ཞེ་ན། ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་ནི་ཉེ་\nབར་མ་རྟོགས་ཤིང་མ་ཟིན་པས་སོ། །འདི་ནི་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོའི་ཏིང་ངེ་འཛིན་ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་ལེན་པ་མེད་པ་ཞེས་བྱ་བ་སྟེ། ཡངས་པ་མདུན་དུ་བྱས་པ་ཚང་མེད་པར་ངེས་པ་ཉན་ཐོས་དང་རང་སངས་རྒྱས་ཐམས་ཅད་དང་ཐུན་མོང་མ་ཡིན་པའོ། །ཏིང་ངེ་\nའཛིན་འདིས་གནས་པའི་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་ནི་མྱུར་དུ་བླ་ན་མེད་པ་ཡང་དག་པར་རྫོགས་པའི་བྱང་ཆུབ་མངོན་པར་རྫོགས་པར་འཚང་རྒྱའོ། །"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"5b:Tc85,ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་ཤཱ་རིའི་བུས་གསོལ་པ། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་འོ་ན་དེ་དག་ཅི་ལྟར་མཆིས། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་ཀྱིས་\nབཀའ་སྩལ་པ། ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ་ཅི་ལྟར་མེད་པ་དེ་བཞིན་དུ་ཡང་དག་པར་ཡོད་དེ་དེ་ལྟར་མེད་པ་དེའི་ཕྱིར་མ་རིག་པ་ཞེས་བྱའོ། །དེ་དག་ལ་བྱིས་པ་སོ་སོའི་སྐྱེ་བོ་ཐོས་པ་དང་མི་ལྡན་པ་རྣམས་མངོན་པར་ཆགས་ཏེ། དེ་དག་གིས་ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་མེད་པ་ལ་བརྟགས་སོ། །དེ་དག་\nགིས་དེ་ལ་བརྟགས་ནས་མཐའ་གཉིས་ལ་ཞེན་པས་ཆོས་དེ་དག་མི་ཤེས་མི་མཐོང་སྟེ། དེའི་ཕྱིར་དེ་དག་མེད་བཞིན་དུ་ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་ལ་རྟོག་གོ། །བརྟགས་ནས་མཐའ་གཉིས་ལ་མངོན་པར་ཆགས་སོ། །མངོན་པར་ཆགས་པ་དེའི་གཞིས་དམིགས་པ་ལ་གནས་ནས་\nའདས་པའི་ཆོས་ལ་རྟོག་གོ་མ་འོངས་པའི་ཆོས་ལ་རྟོག་གོ་ད་ལྟར་བྱུང་བའི་ཆོས་ལ་རྟོག་གོ། །དེ་དག་གིས་བརྟགས་ནས་མིང་དང་གཟུགས་ལ་མངོན་པར་ཞེན་ཏོ། །དེ་དག་གིས་མེད་པའི་ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་ལ་བརྟགས་སོ། །དེ་དག་གིས་མེད་པའི་ཆོས་དེ་དག་ཐམས་ཅད་ལ་\nབརྟགས་པས་ལམ་ཡང་དག་པ་ཇི་ལྟ་བ་བཞིན་དུ་མི་ཤེས་མི་མཐོང་ངོ་། །ལམ་ཡང་དག་པ་ཇི་ལྟ་བ་བཞིན་དུ་མ་ཤེས་མ་མཐོང་བས་ཁམས་གསུམ་ལས་ངེས་པར་མི་འབྱུང་ཡང་དག་པའི་མཐའ་ཁོང་དུ་མི་ཆུད་དེ་དེའི་ཕྱིར་དེ་དག་བྱིས་པ་ཞེས་བྱ་བའི་གྲངས་སུ་འགྲོའོ། །དེ་དག་[F.9.a]ཆོས་བདེན་པ་ལ་ཡིད་མི་ཆེས་སོ། །ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ་ཡང་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་རྣམས་ནི་ཆོས་གང་ལ་ཡང་མངོན་པར་ཞེན་པར་མི་བྱེད་དོ། །དེ་སྐད་ཅེས་བཀའ་སྩལ་པ་དང་། 5c:Tce2,དེ་སྐད་ཅེས་སྨྲས་པ་དང་། ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་རབ་འབྱོར་གྱིས་ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་གང་པོ་བྱམས་མའི་བུ་ལ་འདི་སྐད་ཅེས་སྨྲས་སོ། །ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་[F.13.a]པ་གང་པོ་གང་གི་ཚེ་སྒྱུ་མའི་སྐྱེས་བུའི་གཟུགས་གང་ཡིན་པ་དེ་ནི་མ་བཅིངས་མ་གྲོལ་བའོ། །དེ་བཞིན་དུ་སྒྱུ་མའི་སྐྱེས་བུའི་ཚོར་བ་གང་ཡིན་པ་དང་། སྒྱུ་མའི་སྐྱེས་བུའི་འདུ་ཤེས་གང་ཡིན་པ་དང་། སྒྱུ་མའ"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"ི་སྐྱེས་བུའི་འདུ་བྱེད་རྣམས་གང་ཡིན་པ་དང་། \nཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་གང་པོ་གང་གི་ཚེ་སྒྱུ་མའི་སྐྱེས་བུའི་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་གང་ཡིན་པ་དེ་ནི་མ་བཅིངས་མ་གྲོལ་བའོ། །ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་གང་པོ་སྒྱུ་མའི་སྐྱེས་བུའི་གཟུགས་ཀྱི་དེ་བཞིན་ཉིད་གང་ཡིན་པ་དེ་ནི་མ་བཅིངས་མ་གྲོལ་བའོ། །དེ་བཞིན་དུ་སྒྱུ་མའི་སྐྱེས་བུའི་ཚོར་བའི་དེ་\nབཞིན་ཉིད་དང་འདུ་ཤེས་ཀྱི་དེ་བཞིན་ཉིད་དང་འདུ་བྱེད་རྣམས་ཀྱི་དེ་བཞིན་ཉིད་གང་ཡིན་པ་དང་ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་གང་བོ་སྒྱུ་མའི་སྐྱེས་བུའི་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པའི་དེ་བཞིན་ཉིད་གང་ཡིན་པ་དེ་ནི་མ་བཅིངས་མ་གྲོལ་བའོ། །དེ་ཅིའི་སླད་དུ་ཞེ་ན། ཡང་དག་པ་མ་ཡིན་པས་ན་མ་བཅིངས་མ་\nགྲོལ་བའོ། །དབེན་པས་ན་མ་བཅིངས་མ་གྲོལ་བའོ། །མ་སྐྱེས་པས་ན་མ་བཅིངས་མ་གྲོལ་བ་སྟེ། འདི་དག་ནི་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོའི་གོ་ཆ་ཆེན་པོ་བགོས་པ་ཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོ་ལ་ཡང་དག་པར་ཞུགས་པ་ཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོ་ལ་ཡང་དག་པར་གནས་པའི་གོ་ཆ་\nཆེན་པོ་གོ་ཆ་མེད་པའོ། །དེ་སྐད་ཅེས་སྨྲས་པ་དང་། ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་གང་བོ་བྱམས་མའི་བུ་ཅང་མི་སྨྲ་བར་གྱུར་ཏོ། །5d:Tdc0,དེ་སྐད་ཅེས་གསོལ་པ་དང་། བཅོམ་[F.13.b]ལྡན་འདས་ཀྱིས་ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་རབ་འབྱོར་ལ་འདི་སྐད་ཅེས་བཀའ་སྩལ་ཏོ། །རབ་འབྱོར་ཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོ་ཞེས་བྱ་བ་འདི་ནི་གཞལ་དུ་མེད་པའི་ཚིག་བླ་དགས་སོ། །རབ་འབྱོར་གཞལ་དུ་མེད་པ་ཞེས་བྱ་བ་འདི་ནི་ཚད་མེད་པའི་ཕྱིར་རོ། །རབ་འབྱོར་གང་ཡང་འདི་སྐད་དུ་\nཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོ་དེ་ལ་ཇི་ལྟར་ཡང་དག་པར་ཞུགས་པར་རིག་པར་བགྱི་བའམ། ཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོ་དེས་གང་ནས་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བར་འགྱུར་བའམ། ཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོ་དེ་ལ་གང་གིས་ཡང་དག་པར་ཞུགས་པའམ། ཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོ་དེས་གང་དུ་གནས་པར་འགྱུར་བ་འམ། \nཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོ་དེས་གང་ཞིག་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བར་འགྱུར་ཞེས་ཟེར་བ་ནི། ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་རྣམས་ཀྱི་སྒོ་ནས་ཡང་དག་པར་ཞུགས་ནས། ཁམས་གསུམ་ན"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"ས་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བར་འགྱུར་ཞིང་མི་དམིགས་པ་གང་ཡིན་པས་ཡང་དག་པར་ཞུགས་ཏེ་ཐམས་ཅད་མཁྱེན་པ་ཉིད་\nདུ་གནས་པར་འགྱུར་ལ། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བར་འགྱུར་ཏེ། འོན་ཀྱང་གང་ནས་ཀྱང་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བ་མེད་གང་གིས་ཀྱང་ཡང་དག་པར་མ་ཞུགས་གང་དུ་ཡང་གནས་པར་མི་འགྱུར་མོད་ཀྱི་གནས་པ་མེད་པའི་ཚུལ་གྱིས་ཐམས་ཅད་\nམཁྱེན་པ་ཉིད་ལ་གནས་པར་འགྱུར་ལ། ཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོ་དེས་གང་ཡང་ངེས་པར་མ་ཕྱུང་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བར་ཡང་མི་འགྱུར་ངེས་པར་ཕྱུང་བ་ཡང་མེད་དེ། དེ་ཅིའི་ཕྱིར་ཞེ་ན། གང་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བ་དང་གང་གིས་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བའི་ཆོས་དེ་གཉི་ག་ཡང་མེད་ཅིང་མི་དམིགས་\nཏེ། དེ་ལྟར་ན་ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་མེད་ཅིང་མི་དམིགས་པ་ལ་ཆོས་གང་ཞིག་ཆོས་གང་གིས་ངེས་པར་འབྱུང་བར་འགྱུར། དེ་སྐད་ཅེས་བཀའ་སྩལ་བ་དང་། 5e:T18e2,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"དེ་སྐད་ཅེས་བཀའ་སྩལ་པ་དང་བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་ལ་ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་རབ་འབྱོར་གྱིས་འདི་སྐད་ཅེས་གསོལ་ཏོ། །བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་སངས་རྒྱས་[F.14.b]ཀྱི་མཐུས་ལགས་སོ། །བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་གཞན་ཡང་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སྔོན་གྱི་མཐར་ཡང་ཉེ་བར་མ་རྟོགས་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཕྱི་མའི་མཐར་ཡང་ཉེ་བར་མ་རྟོགས་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་དབུས་སུ་ཡང་ཉེ་བར་མ་རྟོགས་སོ། །ཉེ་བར་མ་རྟོགས་པ་དེ་ཅིའི་སླད་\nདུ་ཞེ་ན། གཟུགས་མུ་མ་མཆིས་པས་ན་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཡང་མུ་མ་མཆིས་པར་རིག་པར་བགྱིའོ། །དེ་བཞིན་དུ་ཚོར་བ་དང་འདུ་ཤེས་དང་འདུ་བྱེད་རྣམས་དང་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་མུ་མ་མཆིས་པས་ན་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཡང་མུ་མ་མཆིས་པར་རིག་པར་བགྱིའོ། །གཟུགས་\nབྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའོ་ཞེས་ཉེ་བར་མ་རྟོགས་ཏེ་འདི་ཡང་མ་མཆིས་མི་དམིགས་སོ། །དེ་བཞིན་དུ་ཚོར་བ་དང་འདུ་ཤེས་དང་འདུ་བྱེད་རྣམས་དང་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའོ་ཞེས་ཉེ་བར་མ་རྟོགས་ཏེ། འདི་ཡང་མ་མཆིས་མི་དམིགས་སོ། །བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་དེ་\nལྟར་བདག་གིས་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའི་ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་ནས་ཐམས་ཅད་རྣམ་པ་ཐམས་ཅད་དུ་ཐམས་ཅད་མི་དམིགས་པས་བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་འདི་ལྟ་སྟེ། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཞེས་བགྱི་བའི་མིང་འདི་གང་ལ་ཡོད་པའི་ཆོས་དེ་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མི་མཐོང་ངོ་། །ཤེས་རབ་\nཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ཡང་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མི་མཐོང་མི་དམིགས་ཐམས་ཅད་མཁྱེན་པ་ཉིད་ཀྱང་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མི་མཐོང་མི་དམིགས་ཏེ། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་བདག་གིས་ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་ནས་ཐམས་ཅད་རྣམ་པ་ཐམས་ཅད་དུ་ཐམས་ཅད་ཡང་དག་པར་མ་མཐོང་ཞིང་མ་\nདམིགས་ན་ཆོས་གང་ཞིག་ཆོས་གང་གིས་ཆོས་གང་ལ་གདམས་ཤིང་རྗེས་སུ་བསྟན་པར་བགྱི། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་སངས་རྒྱས་ཞེས་བགྱི་བ་འདི་ནི་མིང་ཙམ་མོ། །བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཞེས་བགྱི་བ་འདི་ཡང་མིང་ཙམ་མོ། །བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་ཤེས་\nརབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ཞེས་བགྱི་བ་འདི་ཡང་མིང་ཙམ་མོ། །མིང་དེ་ཡང་མངོན་པར་མ་གྲུབ་སྟེ། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་ཇི་ལྟར་བདག་བདག་ཅེས་རྗོད་ཀྱང་བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་བདག་ཤིན་ཏུ་མངོན་པར་མ་གྲུབ་པ་བཞིན་ནོ། །དེ་ལྟར་ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་ངོ་བོ་ཉིད་མ་མཆིས་པ་ལ་[F.15.a]གང་ཞིག་གཟུང་དུ་མ་མཆིས་ཤིང་མངོན་པར་མ་གྲུབ་པའི་གཟུགས་གང་ལགས། ཚོར་བ་དང་འདུ་ཤེས་དང་འདུ་བྱེད་རྣམས་དེ་གང་ལགས། གང་ཞིག་གཟུང་དུ་མ་མཆིས་ཤིང་མངོན་པར་མ་གྲུབ་པའི་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་དེ་གང་ལགས། དེ་ལྟར་ཆོས་དེ་དག་\nཐམས་ཅད་ཀྱི་ངོ་བོ་ཉིད་མ་མཆིས་པ་གང་ལགས་པ་དེ་ནི་མངོན་པར་མ་གྲུབ་པ་ལགས་ལ། གང་ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་ཀྱི་མངོན་པར་མ་གྲུབ་པ་གང་ལགས་པ་དེ་ཡང་ཆོས་མ་ལགས་ཏེ། དེས་ན་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་མངོན་པར་མ་གྲུབ་པས་མངོན་པར་མ་གྲུབ་པ་ལ་ཅི་ཞིག་\nགདམས་ཤིང་རྗེས་སུ་བསྟན་པར་བགྱི། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་མངོན་པར་མ་གྲུབ་པ་ལས་གཞན་ན་ཆོས་ཐམས་ཅད་དམ་སངས་རྒྱས་ཀྱི་ཆོས་སམ་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའི་ཆོས་སམ་གང་བྱང་ཆུབ་ཏུ་སྤྱོད་པ་ཡང་མི་དམིགས་སོ། །"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"5f:T11bc,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་གལ་ཏེ་དེ་ལྟར་བཤད་ཅིང་དེ་\nལྟར་བསྟན་ཏེ་དེ་ལྟར་ཉེ་བར་བསྟན་པ་ལ། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོའི་སེམས་མི་འགོང་ཀུན་ཏུ་མི་ཞུམ་བག་མི་ཚ། བག་འཁུམས་པར་མི་འགྱུར་འདིའི་ཡིད་ཕྱིར་ཕྱོགས་པར་མི་བགྱིད་བཅོམ་ཞིང་ཕྱིར་ཕྱོགས་པར་མི་འགྱུར། མི་དངང་ཀུན་ཏུ་མི་སྐྲག་ཀུན་ཏུ་སྐྲག་\nཔ་དང་ལྡན་པར་མི་འགྱུར་ན་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་འདི་ནི་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་སྤྱོད་པའོ། །བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་འདི་ནི་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་བསྒོམ་པའོ། །བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་འདི་\nནི་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་ཉེ་བར་རྟོག་པའོ། །བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་འདི་ནི་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་ངེས་པར་སེམས་པའོ་ཞེས་དེ་ལྟར་རིག་པར་བགྱིའོ། །དེ་ཅིའི་སླད་དུ་ཞེ་ན། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་གང་གི་ཚེ་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་\nདཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་ལ་ཆོས་འདི་དག་ཉེ་བར་རྟོག་པ་དེའི་ཚེ། གཟུགས་ཉེ་བར་མི་རྟོགས་གཟུགས་ཉེ་བར་མི་འཛིན་གཟུགས་སྐྱེ་བར་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མི་མཐོང་གཟུགས་འགག་པར་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མི་མཐོང་། དེ་བཞིན་དུ་ཚོར་བ་མ་ཡིན་འདུ་ཤེས་མ་ཡིན་[F.15.b]འདུ་བྱེད་རྣམས་མ་ཡིན་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་ཉེ་བར་མི་རྟོགས་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་ཉེ་བར་མི་འཛིན་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་སྐྱེ་བར་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མི་མཐོང་རྣམ་པར་ཤེས་པ་འགག་པར་ཡང་དག་པར་རྗེས་སུ་མི་མཐོང་ངོ་། །དེ་ཅིའི་སླད་དུ་ཞེ་ན། འདི་ལྟར་གཟུགས་ཀྱི་སྐྱེ་བ་མ་མཆིས་པ་གང་\nལགས་པ་དེ་ནི་གཟུགས་མ་ལགས། གཟུགས་ཀྱི་འཇིག་པ་མ་མཆིས་པ་གང་ལགས་པ་དེ་ནི་གཟུགས་མ་ལགས་ཏེ། དེས་ན་སྐྱེ་བ་མ་མཆིས་པ་དང་གཟུགས་ཞེས་བགྱི་བ་འདི་ནི་གཉིས་སུ་མ་མཆིས་ཤིང་གཉིས་སུ་བགྱིར་མ་མཆིས་སོ། །དེས་ན་འཇིག་པ་མ་མཆིས་པ་\nདང་གཟུགས་ཞེས་བགྱི་བ་འདི་ཡང་གཉིས་སུ་མ་མཆིས་ཤིང་གཉིས་སུ་བགྱིར་མ་མཆིས་ཏེ། གང་ཡང་འདི་སྐད་དུ་གཟུགས་ཞེས་བགྱི་བ་འདི་ནི་གཉིས་སུ་མ་མཆིས་པའི་གྲངས་སུ་གཏོགས་སོ། །"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"60:Tfca,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"དེ་སྐད་ཅེས་སྨྲས་པ་དང་། ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་རབ་འབྱོར་གྱིས་ཚེ་[F.16.b]དང་ལྡན་པ་ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ་ལ་འདི་སྐད་ཅེས་སྨྲས་སོ། །ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ་ཁོ་བོ་ནི་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་དཀའ་བ་སྤྱད་པ་སྤྱོད་པར་མི་འདོད་དོ། །གང་ཞིག་དཀའ་བའི་འདུ་ཤེས་ཀྱིས་སྤྱོད་པ་དེ་ནི་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔར་ཡང་མི་འགྱུར་ཏེ། དེ་ཅིའི་ཕྱིར་ཞེ་ན། \nཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ་དཀའ་བའི་འདུ་ཤེས་བསྐྱེད་ནས་ནི་སེམས་ཅན་གཞལ་དུ་མེད་གྲངས་མེད་པའི་དོན་བྱ་བར་མི་ནུས་སོ། །འོན་ཀྱང་བདེ་བའི་འདུ་ཤེས་ཉིད་དུ་བྱས་ནས་དེ་སེམས་ཅན་ཐམས་ཅད་ལ་མར་འདུ་ཤེས་པ་དང་ཕར་འདུ་ཤེས་པ་དང་བུར་འདུ་ཤེས་པ་དང་བུ་མོར་འདུ་ཤེས་\nབསྐྱེད་པར་བྱས་ཤིང་། དེ་བཞིན་དུ་སྐྱེས་པ་དང་བུད་མེད་དག་ལ་འདུ་ཤེས་དེ་དག་བྱས་ནས། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའི་སྤྱད་པ་སྤྱོད་དོ། །དེ་བས་ན་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོས་སེམས་ཅན་ཐམས་ཅད་ལ་མར་\nའདུ་ཤེས་པ་དང་ཕར་འདུ་ཤེས་པ་དང་བུར་འདུ་ཤེས་པ་དང་བུ་མོར་འདུ་ཤེས་པ་དང་བདག་ཉིད་ཀྱི་བར་དུ་ཡང་འདུ་ཤེས་བསྐྱེད་པར་བྱ་སྟེ། ཇི་ལྟར་བདག་ནི་ཐམས་ཅད་ནས་ཐམས་ཅད་རྣམ་པ་ཐམས་ཅད་དུ་ཐམས་ཅད་སྡུག་བསྔལ་ཐམས་ཅད་ལས་ཐར་བར་བྱ་བ་དེ་བཞིན་དུ་སེམས་ཅན་\nཐམས་ཅད་ཐམས་ཅད་ནས་ཐམས་ཅད་རྣམ་པ་ཐམས་ཅད་དུ་སྡུག་བསྔལ་ཐམས་ཅད་ལས་ཐར་བར་བྱའོ་ཞེས་དེ་ལྟར་སེམས་ཅན་ཐམས་ཅད་ལ་ཡང་འདུ་ཤེས་བསྐྱེད་པར་བྱ་སྟེ། བདག་གིས་སེམས་ཅན་འདི་དག་ཐམས་ཅད་ཡོངས་སུ་མི་གཏང་ངོ་། །བདག་གིས་སེམས་ཅན་འདི་\nདག་ཐམས་ཅད་སྡུག་བསྔལ་གྱི་ཕུང་པོ་དཔག་ཏུ་མེད་པ་ལས་ཐར་བར་བྱའོ། །བདག་གི་ལུས་བརྒྱར་གཏུབས་ཀྱང་ཆུང་ངུ་ན་འདི་དག་ལ་བདག་གིས་གནོད་སེམས་ཀྱང་མི་བསྐྱེད་དོ་སྙམ་དུ། དེ་ལྟར་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོས་སེམས་བསྐྱེད་པར་བྱའོ། །"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"17:[\"$\",\"$L57\",null,{\"titles\":[{\"uuid\":\"de0d6025-34b2-468c-91ce-0ec623a13938\",\"title\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Eight Thousand Lines\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"563850b2-e993-4638-8050-79ba5e84a20d\",\"title\":\"Aṣṭasāhasrikāprajñāpāramitā\",\"language\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"a7f3dfc8-70fa-4a71-84a3-0fa9dcd54243\",\"title\":\"《般若波羅密多八千頌》\",\"language\":\"zh\",\"type\":\"otherTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"e13364ce-22e6-4b8e-b313-606bb58230b1\",\"title\":\"Toh 12\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"toh\"},{\"uuid\":\"060030f9-6daa-4210-86e7-3d848a2ca946\",\"title\":\"shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa brgyad stong pa\",\"language\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"35ee779b-e426-420a-ab23-4bfb99ae0922\",\"title\":\"sher phyin brgyad stong pa\",\"language\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"otherTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"735f7277-b695-4dc2-81a5-3b2d35672615\",\"title\":\"ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་བརྒྱད་སྟོང་པ།\",\"language\":\"bo\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"93fb8b5d-e0bc-487d-89f2-724269be57b7\",\"title\":\"The Noble Perfection of Wisdom in Eight Thousand Lines\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"longTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"c6b3bf3a-5c7f-42ae-8626-3933c5f62b07\",\"title\":\"Āryāṣṭasāhasrikāprajñāpāramitā\",\"language\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"longTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"59413352-1511-4e64-b952-b9d2a506219b\",\"title\":\"འཕགས་པ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་བརྒྱད་སྟོང་པ།\",\"language\":\"bo\",\"type\":\"longTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"d8a8a418-830f-46bf-9f6b-a5574ad2a167\",\"title\":\"’phags pa shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa brgyad stong pa\",\"language\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"longTitle\"}],\"frontMatter\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2bd50793-8cf8-449f-b3be-77f9083b31e1\",\"sort\":2,\"type\":\"summaryHeader\",\"label\":\"s.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":7,\"uuid\":\"fb2e7556-8c84-401e-8df4-2e166131246e\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Summary\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"aa1d5ee3-b77d-48ee-a5a2-e8129f32c4c5\",\"sort\":4,\"type\":\"summary\",\"label\":\"s.1\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":438,\"uuid\":\"aa1d5ee3-b77d-48ee-a5a2-e8129f32c4c5\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Eight Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":48},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e0f50329-219b-4bd1-af07-d111108f6dbc\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is a keystone of the Prajñāpāramitā literature. It presents the Buddha’s teaching on the topic in a relatively compact text that nevertheless covers the entire range of important points he taught, and is therefore considered to be one of the six “mother” works. It has been hugely influential in Mahāyāna Buddhist thought across Asia, and gave rise to many commentaries in India and Tibet.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":48,\"end\":438}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b66e0a67-153d-4908-aef9-78fec06fe531\",\"sort\":7,\"type\":\"acknowledgmentHeader\",\"label\":\"ac.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"uuid\":\"b5cbe177-718f-4edf-a09d-7bc9f38d3732\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Acknowledgements\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b48414b4-5738-4519-be30-53f7d33a476f\",\"sort\":9,\"type\":\"acknowledgment\",\"label\":\"ac.1\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":339,\"uuid\":\"6271dc35-99d9-49ae-970b-4c743806c369\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translated by the Padmakara Translation Group under the direction of Pema Wangyal Rinpoche and Jigme Khyentse Rinpoche. Greg Seton translated the text, compiled extensive annotations to it from the commentaries, and wrote a preliminary version of the introduction. Charles Hastings contributed valuable editorial help during these stages. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":339}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":339,\"end\":715,\"uuid\":\"63e6d9a0-2e30-49fa-8243-822fe146313b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The translation was then completed under the patronage and supervision of 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha. John Canti edited the translation and annotations. He also edited and rearranged the introduction, and added further material to it. Ven. Konchog Norbu copyedited the text. Sameer Dhingra and Celso Wilkinson were in charge of the digital publication process.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":339,\"end\":715}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6a05b44c-7bf9-47a3-a84d-582f87ed68ed\",\"sort\":12,\"type\":\"acknowledgment\",\"label\":\"ac.2\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":283,\"uuid\":\"6a05b44c-7bf9-47a3-a84d-582f87ed68ed\",\"hasLeadingSpace\":true,\"leadingSpaceUuid\":\"4a9aac0f-5ac8-4dd4-ad6d-c41e48a06a30\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The translation of this text has been made possible through the generous sponsorship of AC, AN, C, CHUCKTSOU, CM, CY, Deva-DKSPS, FEN, HCM, JFH, K, KH, LR, NIEHYUPING, NP, SF, SPTF, RW, WAC, WF, Y, YL, YS, YUANSUEN, YY, YUSHUHUI, and the other anonymous members of the Nigrodha team.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":283}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c01ab2e6-dba6-4d1b-8f01-4a21fd877041\",\"sort\":14,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"i.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":12,\"uuid\":\"9ad0a169-0da5-490c-b7f4-771b4df8139c\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Introduction\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":12}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"741db68a-12f6-441f-ae56-3f41c6bc96ee\",\"sort\":15,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":8,\"uuid\":\"3f25aa10-c2c9-4a99-8d32-d9aae57be967\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Overview\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":8}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0a8d1c9e-c2d7-4011-8f69-eaa1c45b2873\",\"sort\":17,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.1\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":492,\"uuid\":\"0a8d1c9e-c2d7-4011-8f69-eaa1c45b2873\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in Eight Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":48},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1c691119-435b-4d6f-9551-6b362084eace\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":48,\"end\":50}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Aṣṭa­sāhasrikā­prajñā­pāramitā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":80},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"95b99cc3-c027-4ee2-ac5a-ff3e872748b1\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", hereafter \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":80,\"end\":92}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":106},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"df90bc0d-1a3d-478f-a1dd-c4316bfdd029\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") is one of the most important, influential, and revolutionary Buddhist scriptures. It presents the Buddha’s second turning of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":106,\"end\":237}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"wheel of Dharma\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":237,\"end\":252},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"da3119d6-8309-4c6c-9706-e9b94b7d8e4b\",\"uuid\":\"2eb57dce-f3a7-45ee-910a-e74e124fffa4\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and thus some of the quintessential teachings at the core of the Mahāyāna. It may be close to the earliest textual form of the Prajñāpāramitā literature that, as it blossomed, forever transformed the Buddhist landscape in India and beyond.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":252,\"end\":492}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6fe2f041-5f4a-4328-8511-f7934d07bd9f\",\"sort\":26,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.2\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":709,\"uuid\":\"6fe2f041-5f4a-4328-8511-f7934d07bd9f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":18},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"aa136324-2d3b-4c28-96e2-d2b69f94a4ab\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is revered as one of the six “mother” Prajñāpāramitā texts, so called because they include the complete set of topics identified in the most influential of the Indian commentaries, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":200}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Ornament of Clear Realization\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":200,\"end\":233},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d24f4acd-79bb-45c4-b826-141528ac5d66\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":233,\"end\":235}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Abhisamayālaṃkāra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":235,\"end\":252},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bfc1e88c-c677-49b2-bb63-6d94f36b8369\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), as comprising the full range covered by the Prajñāpāramitā teaching. But for those without the time, interest, stamina, or need to study the other, longer “mother” texts, the lesser level of detail with which the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":252,\"end\":468}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":468,\"end\":482},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"28c29af5-1d8c-453a-b96d-dbe5996a62ca\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" covers that full range of topics makes it more accessible. The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":482,\"end\":546}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":546,\"end\":560},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"72c0ca10-32c3-4263-bb2c-5f2f07216dcf\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" seems to have been extensively read and studied in India, and was translated into Chinese and Tibetan more times than virtually any other scripture.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":560,\"end\":709}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0d63fde4-dc81-4aac-8d99-553b620dd5d6\",\"sort\":38,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.3\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":778,\"uuid\":\"0d63fde4-dc81-4aac-8d99-553b620dd5d6\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Prajñāpāramitā sūtras are widely seen as presenting the Buddha’s core teaching on the emptiness of phenomena and their ultimate lack of defining characteristics. Yet as scriptures they are not easy to understand fully, and gave rise to a very large commentarial literature, starting with Nāgārjuna’s treatises and in a later period \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":336}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Maitreya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":336,\"end\":344},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"34e9bd80-03ca-4582-8295-19dcf8d87219\",\"uuid\":\"17fdcd65-529b-4396-aefe-8cb215714b54\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"-Asaṅga’s \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":344,\"end\":354}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament of Clear Realization\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":354,\"end\":383},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"651c708d-d4ef-4f56-87d1-eaf902e6565f\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and its many subcommentaries. Of those subcommentaries, the ones composed by Haribhadra and Ratnākaraśānti, from their different viewpoints, are renowned for their elucidation of the difficult points in the text, of its implicit structure, and of how its underlying themes are crucial for a full understanding of the Buddhist path in general and for the practice of a bodhisattva in particular.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":383,\"end\":778}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2cd31c1f-7b97-49d6-acdb-02f14a1c7768\",\"sort\":44,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":350,\"uuid\":\"2cd31c1f-7b97-49d6-acdb-02f14a1c7768\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This translation therefore includes substantial notes drawing on these two commentaries, in order to allow as full an appreciation as possible of the depth and breadth of the scripture itself, and to point out some of the ways in which its style and wordplay‍—difficult to convey in a translation‍—are integral to how it conveys its intended message.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":350}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c9640207-ff6b-40cd-8de8-6d683006f014\",\"sort\":46,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.5\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":217,\"uuid\":\"c9640207-ff6b-40cd-8de8-6d683006f014\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"There is nevertheless an established tradition, mentioned in the text itself, of simply reading or reciting the sūtra respectfully without analysis, allowing its words to bring about their subtle effect by themselves.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":217}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"65357125-fb5e-48a1-ba2c-3d619ba6d527\",\"sort\":48,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":427,\"uuid\":\"65357125-fb5e-48a1-ba2c-3d619ba6d527\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This English rendering, made principally from the Sanskrit but with reference to the Tibetan translation, is the first full translation of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":143}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":143,\"end\":157},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f658ab38-7174-4a75-a32e-f1219d601d82\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". It is presented here so that readers of all kinds may read or study it, with or without guidance from the notes, in whatever way they wish. In particular, we hope that the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":157,\"end\":331}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":331,\"end\":345},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6ff8842d-46ca-4932-a884-821a58b5df77\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s own interpretable but playful use of language may amuse, intrigue, and inspire.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":345,\"end\":427}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"caae19af-0704-465d-ae51-5783361bec56\",\"sort\":54,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.7\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":175,\"uuid\":\"caae19af-0704-465d-ae51-5783361bec56\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"What follows in this introduction is a more detailed presentation of contextual and historical material, and some explanations of the approaches taken in translating the text.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":175}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3bf0c34f-0264-4388-87d9-a81e505d888d\",\"sort\":56,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":682,\"uuid\":\"3bf0c34f-0264-4388-87d9-a81e505d888d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Two synopses of the content, one according to the topics of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":60}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Ornament of Clear Realization\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":93},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a889d1fa-2f23-4dd2-8f5d-7b1b838aa3ee\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and one set out chapter by chapter, can also be found at the end of the introduction. Although in many respects the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":93,\"end\":210}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":210,\"end\":224},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"287c30a1-2b4d-4d85-a833-3d68a87236e7\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is less similar to the longer Prajñāpāramitā sūtras than they are to each other, it follows almost the same order as them in terms of narrative events, appearances of different interlocutors, topics discussed, and so forth. Some remarks and links to the passages paralleled in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":224,\"end\":506}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eighteen Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":506,\"end\":523},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c45927df-79d8-4b58-8dea-70359336a3ac\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":523,\"end\":525}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Twenty-Five Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":525,\"end\":545},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7fedc050-8951-4bf0-9245-4fbc7495d565\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":545,\"end\":551}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Hundred Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":551,\"end\":567},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"125732c3-902e-49da-802a-f0c1a602008a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" have been included so that interested readers may compare all these closely related accounts of the same material.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":567,\"end\":682}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1db335a6-2865-483e-99d6-ad338efd80b1\",\"sort\":67,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":39,\"uuid\":\"7d709c06-8dc1-498e-b0f0-f015bca583b5\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"History, Extant Texts, and Commentaries\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":39}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9c4afd2b-b75c-4a96-847a-5e6a49ddf635\",\"sort\":68,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":4,\"start\":0,\"end\":43,\"uuid\":\"34045c13-2ee8-4fe7-8b0f-c5ac6e21de8c\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Place Among the Perfection of Wisdom Sūtras\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1949ad2d-92f8-416f-b8b0-6c421e07606d\",\"sort\":70,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.9\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1122,\"uuid\":\"1949ad2d-92f8-416f-b8b0-6c421e07606d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"According to tradition, when the Buddha taught the Prajñāpāramitā scriptures, he entrusted their preservation to \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":113}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ānanda\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":113,\"end\":119},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7bd42065-689d-456d-8f83-789ac6366a8e\",\"uuid\":\"36253c25-63df-4d2a-9df5-387224176307\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":119,\"end\":124}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vajrapāṇi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":124,\"end\":133},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"85a0e3f1-ad8c-44ce-839f-8903612b40ba\",\"uuid\":\"1a2b3541-c79f-4682-97b2-bfc304ca207d\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", who initiated their oral transmission from an early date. But it was only centuries later, after Nāgārjuna (ca. 150–250 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":133,\"end\":255}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":255,\"end\":257},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":255,\"end\":257,\"uuid\":\"be5ec550-962a-4d9e-8692-6a85cd7a0d61\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") purportedly retrieved \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":257,\"end\":281}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Perfection of Wisdom in One Hundred Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":281,\"end\":335},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4ee19cc5-70cd-4237-8b99-6e3db5d925e9\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" from the nāga realm in written form, that these scriptures came to be transmitted far and wide. Today, in the Prajñāpāramitā section of the Kangyur‍—which in terms of pages takes up more than a fifth of the whole collection‍—there are twenty-three Prajñāpāramitā scriptures. Among them, the six main scriptures‍—the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":335,\"end\":652}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Hundred Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":652,\"end\":668},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6651188c-719a-4936-8823-65b9f6685398\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":668,\"end\":674}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Twenty-Five Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":674,\"end\":694},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"78f9bc36-3779-4c68-b75d-ab521ce63457\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":694,\"end\":700}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eighteen Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":700,\"end\":717},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"260df7e9-757f-436f-a46e-0c2913da44f2\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":717,\"end\":723}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ten Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":723,\"end\":735},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"12f73c99-f81d-4700-9a74-fe6bcb782ce7\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":735,\"end\":741}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":741,\"end\":755},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e0aa6b55-8ac6-44b2-90dd-c6fb64f4b8df\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":755,\"end\":765}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Verse Summary\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":765,\"end\":778},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b9af7fa2-fa57-42e5-815d-0775ee23c941\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"‍—are called the “mothers,” because each of them covers the full set of eight topics outlined in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":778,\"end\":875}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Maitreya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":875,\"end\":883},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"34e9bd80-03ca-4582-8295-19dcf8d87219\",\"uuid\":\"c71ab45b-750b-4a5c-854a-f9e1e71d8563\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"-Asaṅga’s \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":883,\"end\":893}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament of Clear Realization\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":893,\"end\":922},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"475934c5-41b1-402e-b865-68433eb462d3\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; eleven additional scriptures are called the “children” because they emphasize only certain of these topics. The six remaining scriptures are short texts that fall outside that classification scheme.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":922,\"end\":1122}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4e00c7a2-df1d-4804-be62-8ff48745d02a\",\"sort\":96,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.10\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":874,\"uuid\":\"4e00c7a2-df1d-4804-be62-8ff48745d02a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"While the Tibetan and Chinese traditions consider the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":54}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Hundred Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":54,\"end\":70},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d428da45-30d9-46fc-9b6e-ff52342eb495\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to be the source of the other twenty-two because it contains the most detailed exposition, traditional scholars in Nepal see the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":70,\"end\":200}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":200,\"end\":214},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"adbafe00-1c99-494d-b03f-da4c9ba307a1\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" as the original scripture. Western historians, too, based on the available philological evidence, have concluded that the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":214,\"end\":337}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":337,\"end\":351},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"be28dee3-60c5-488f-a2b1-b4c446d10f4e\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" probably represents the earliest form of the multiplicity of Prajñāpāramitā texts. Whichever the case, since all the “mother” scriptures follow the same outline, there are many similarities between them, and not only the topics discussed and the order in which they are discussed, but also the principal narrative events, appearances of different interlocutors, and other features are clearly paralleled across the texts,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":351,\"end\":773},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"aa851662-5360-4c6d-a21b-d98e738c008f\",\"label\":\"1\",\"uuid\":\"b78efdb6-09eb-4949-91d9-4261d8831d87\",\"start\":773,\"end\":773,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" even if the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":773,\"end\":786}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":786,\"end\":800},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3d047833-43c4-4298-93f8-70fa40ea860a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is notably less similar to the longer sūtras than they are to each other.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":800,\"end\":874},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"501ae3f4-3755-4267-8a9b-9560a92383a3\",\"label\":\"2\",\"uuid\":\"96e247d6-457a-4dcb-9992-787c74ef8b2c\",\"start\":874,\"end\":874,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a0a9b633-4b61-47e1-ba52-3daa9a16ac60\",\"sort\":109,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.11\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1293,\"uuid\":\"a0a9b633-4b61-47e1-ba52-3daa9a16ac60\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The view that the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":18}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":32},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"478192ae-e615-4b8c-b48a-fb1757932145\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is closest to what may have been the earliest form of the scripture, initially based on analysis of passages in the earliest Chinese translations and translation records, has been supported by the evidence of more recently discovered manuscripts, such as the Kharoṣṭhī manuscript from the Split Collection, which has been carbon-dated to between 47 and 147 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":32,\"end\":390}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":390,\"end\":392},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":390,\"end\":392,\"uuid\":\"477e58cf-0d0c-4e14-99b9-716bcecfdb6d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Among the range of extant texts belonging to the family of long Prajñāpāramitā scriptures it seems most closely related to the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":392,\"end\":530}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":530,\"end\":544},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"187decb8-5a5b-463f-ad51-fab42e390dd5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":544,\"end\":545},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"95f7d9d5-492c-444e-8c29-a2038664f370\",\"label\":\"3\",\"uuid\":\"3a89f4e2-f2a3-4eff-95b0-a1ea62d366f1\",\"start\":545,\"end\":545,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" It is important to bear in mind that the system of naming Prajñāpāramitā texts by numerical expressions of their length (such as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":545,\"end\":675}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":675,\"end\":689},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7c31d921-d333-4c85-b1be-bcec651dec63\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":689,\"end\":691}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Twenty-Five Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":691,\"end\":711},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"700b6a27-3bbb-4685-ae7c-141fcc458d84\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", etc.) was not used in any of the early Chinese translations, nor at the time of the earliest Indic manuscripts, and may only have been instigated by Bodhiruci in China in the early sixth century. The Kharoṣṭhī manuscript includes a section colophon in which its mentioned title, unsurprisingly, is thus only \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":711,\"end\":1021}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"prañaparamida\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1021,\"end\":1034},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1021,\"end\":1034,\"uuid\":\"e26a8815-8c0f-467f-a2ad-8dfe9e2b0282\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", but it is to the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1034,\"end\":1053}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1053,\"end\":1067},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8f97cdaf-d5bb-4c12-b58e-bc11e3520eb5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" subfamily that it bears the closest comparison, in contrast to the other subfamily, that of the longer Prajñāpāramitā scriptures that were later identified as the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1067,\"end\":1231}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Hundred Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1231,\"end\":1247},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"829ae678-efc0-4657-a776-033d7cd355e2\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1247,\"end\":1249}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Twenty-Five Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1249,\"end\":1269},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1301460b-874f-498a-846b-dcc7848d45be\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1269,\"end\":1275}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eighteen Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1275,\"end\":1292},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"611a4a23-5b4d-41ec-95eb-1b67c062466c\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1292,\"end\":1293}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"27586848-673b-4921-9b3a-721ceafb83f9\",\"sort\":133,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.12\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":562,\"uuid\":\"27586848-673b-4921-9b3a-721ceafb83f9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Manuscript fragments found near Bamiyan in Afghanistan and dated paleographically to the second half of the third century are more closely comparable to the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":157}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":157,\"end\":171},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"822bdd59-8a2c-47d5-b39a-b487ff77795b\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", to a degree that could justify their description as the earliest known Sanskrit witnesses of the text.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":171,\"end\":275},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"c9fd5df1-3a87-4e07-8a45-258ab531e037\",\"label\":\"4\",\"uuid\":\"ebd485e2-72d0-47a7-a594-a8eff3d4a95b\",\"start\":275,\"end\":275,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Nevertheless, the various versions of the scripture that we know today as the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":275,\"end\":354}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":354,\"end\":368},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3b3f7989-dfe9-44a8-acc6-b0fbf8d491e9\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" show evidence of significant expansion and evolution over time, as can be seen by comparing the extant Chinese translations made successively between the second and tenth centuries (see below).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":368,\"end\":562}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e93e3ddd-0bc0-42df-9fda-4c0e1660b286\",\"sort\":141,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.13\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":906,\"uuid\":\"e93e3ddd-0bc0-42df-9fda-4c0e1660b286\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Whatever its provenance or its significance, the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":49}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":49,\"end\":63},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d56a689e-9b80-4bf8-b46c-6560c64c1a82\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" stands out as one of the most revered of all Buddhist scriptures. The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":63,\"end\":134}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":134,\"end\":148},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"516dcf27-46ab-482e-8ba7-8af66c9da22e\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is still extant in more ancient Indian manuscripts than virtually any other text, and may have held a central place in many Mahāyāna Buddhist shrines. It also seems to have been among the most closely studied of all Prajñāpāramitā scriptures. Its level of detail made it complete but also accessible for those without the time, interest, stamina, or need to study the longer versions. This too may be the reason why it was translated into Chinese and Tibetan more times than virtually any other scripture‍—a total of seven times into Chinese beginning with Lokakṣema (179 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":148,\"end\":721}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":721,\"end\":723},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":721,\"end\":723,\"uuid\":\"dca9cc23-3c2a-4734-bec2-030d305d8967\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), and in many successive stages into Tibetan, beginning in the early imperial translation period in the late eighth century‍—by translators wanting to get the translation just right.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":723,\"end\":906}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cea68009-2d2c-4083-8190-ff2dcb991c13\",\"sort\":148,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":4,\"start\":0,\"end\":12,\"uuid\":\"f096a263-d359-4948-9e92-96d86fcd6486\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Extant Texts\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":12}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"82ea070a-d266-4358-81a5-8ebf3d446368\",\"sort\":149,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":5,\"start\":0,\"end\":8,\"uuid\":\"b7be56f4-7f8b-4c6c-9fdc-58e9ae21f705\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sanskrit\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":8}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a0dd4407-602b-45c2-97a3-2fe00089f1a9\",\"sort\":151,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.14\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":284,\"uuid\":\"a0dd4407-602b-45c2-97a3-2fe00089f1a9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The complete Sanskrit text is available in three successive editions, made by Mitra (1888), Wogihara (1932–35), and Vaidya (1960), from Nepalese manuscripts.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":157},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"285b92d5-88a0-4943-b64b-01dc0fc554a9\",\"label\":\"5\",\"uuid\":\"762b378b-5254-4f14-a2d9-7ee14869db47\",\"start\":157,\"end\":157,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The manuscripts themselves are of relatively recent date but are based on recensions dated to the eleventh or twelfth century.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":157,\"end\":284}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"83ff0f8a-6c7a-46cf-b37b-cf65c1d4cb7d\",\"sort\":155,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.15\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":292,\"uuid\":\"83ff0f8a-6c7a-46cf-b37b-cf65c1d4cb7d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Despite this late dating, the Sanskrit matches closely the fragmentary third-century manuscripts from Bamiyan mentioned above, even if the latter show more linguistic features characteristic of Buddhist Hybrid Sanskrit. It therefore appears to have been relatively stable over many centuries.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":292}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fb8c27a4-9066-4298-8a81-ce7195e7502a\",\"sort\":157,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.16\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":497,\"uuid\":\"fb8c27a4-9066-4298-8a81-ce7195e7502a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"There are suggestions in the Tibetan accounts of the various stages by which the successive Tibetan translations reached their present form that the numerous Sanskrit manuscripts consulted by successive translators may have not only been slightly different but also fell into two broad groups: those made before and after a revision of the text to conform to \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":359}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Ornament of Clear Realization\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":359,\"end\":392},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"de7d16dd-afaa-4e34-a860-0b5beb8338cd\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":392,\"end\":393},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"762d8bf3-00fe-4b1f-bf9f-8dee6e042ce5\",\"label\":\"6\",\"uuid\":\"8f7fcb6e-fa81-410b-bff3-91c221c39301\",\"start\":393,\"end\":393,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" However, the extant Sanskrit versions show no evidence of belonging to more than one principal lineage.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":393,\"end\":497}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5ffefb73-7602-4b4a-a3f6-14f013abbf84\",\"sort\":163,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.17\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":172,\"uuid\":\"5ffefb73-7602-4b4a-a3f6-14f013abbf84\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The extant Sanskrit text was used as the principal basis for this English translation, for reasons explained below. It corresponds quite closely to the Tibetan translation.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":172}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9c02a96d-9f11-43c7-bab0-8bf4dde0427d\",\"sort\":164,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":5,\"start\":0,\"end\":7,\"uuid\":\"35352348-e908-4dfa-8a75-d19e5fa8c56f\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Chinese\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"66b60796-1b07-49cd-9829-b80b0383b10c\",\"sort\":166,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.18\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":99,\"uuid\":\"4131b0f4-65ef-40c2-9dcd-4c4d5fc39f70\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The seven Chinese translations, made from the second through the tenth century \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":79}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":81},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":81,\"uuid\":\"9e364c6b-e4af-46b2-b70b-f7dc8fb34c5d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", are as follows: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":99}}]},{\"type\":\"bulletList\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":99,\"end\":1326,\"uuid\":\"177087d1-7ee3-4722-b072-2f3ec5f29208\",\"spacing\":\"horizontal\",\"itemStyle\":\"dots\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":99,\"end\":103}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Daoxing jing\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":103,\"end\":115},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"301b5a6e-1c58-4da7-84bd-9ed567219998\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (道行經) or \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":115,\"end\":125}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Daoxing banruo jing\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":125,\"end\":144},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fd9605f6-12e6-4207-8b5e-fbfe471bf500\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (道行般若經), Taishō 224, translated by Lokakṣema and others, probably from a Gāndhāri original, and dated by its colophon to 179 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":144,\"end\":270}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":270,\"end\":272},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":270,\"end\":272,\"uuid\":\"7c5e7618-a7f6-421d-a8d0-a3bc20b6c490\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":272,\"end\":273},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"0e6608b4-1985-4d1a-9272-62d3bce5e938\",\"label\":\"7\",\"uuid\":\"44fae3da-e6a5-401f-b77d-4b754267fe4b\",\"start\":273,\"end\":273,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":273,\"end\":274}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":99,\"end\":274,\"uuid\":\"f5829bbb-91a3-481e-b55e-10ca24a0ffea\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":99,\"end\":274,\"uuid\":\"f5829bbb-91a3-481e-b55e-10ca24a0ffea\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":274,\"end\":278}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Da mingdu jing\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":278,\"end\":292},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5135cc64-4250-4020-8a4f-f2f15becedd1\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (大明度經), Taishō 225, translated in the early third century, for the most part by Zhi Qian except for its rather different first chapter, which is thought to be the work of another translator.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":292,\"end\":483},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"791a0b44-40e2-4443-8cb2-a46d06bb9223\",\"label\":\"8\",\"uuid\":\"2bfd667f-4022-47a2-9658-f7cc4486d9f9\",\"start\":483,\"end\":483,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":483,\"end\":484}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":274,\"end\":484,\"uuid\":\"c24d131c-8f28-49ed-a86a-d7a04bea5e53\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":274,\"end\":484,\"uuid\":\"c24d131c-8f28-49ed-a86a-d7a04bea5e53\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":484,\"end\":488}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mohebanruo chaojing\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":488,\"end\":507},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"eef88edf-f21f-43c9-a9c6-a8c319fcffcd\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (摩訶般若鈔經), Taishō 226, canonically attributed to *Dharmapriya and Zhu Fonian and dated to 382 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":507,\"end\":601}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":601,\"end\":603},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":601,\"end\":603,\"uuid\":\"2214e9d0-0fdf-439f-a3e5-2ccd057ba239\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", although this is thought doubtful by some scholars.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":603,\"end\":656},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"e2217ddc-5079-4d9c-b0b4-586d5532f53d\",\"label\":\"9\",\"uuid\":\"02aa09da-caf0-4449-a2db-4dae50587b16\",\"start\":656,\"end\":656,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":656,\"end\":657}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":484,\"end\":657,\"uuid\":\"f5a71708-46e4-48df-8f2b-7f19f4c880d2\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":484,\"end\":657,\"uuid\":\"f5a71708-46e4-48df-8f2b-7f19f4c880d2\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":657,\"end\":661}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mohebanruo boluomi jing\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":661,\"end\":684},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a206b1a8-f8e1-4ffd-8d3c-c851bd03b5cc\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (摩訶般若波羅蜜經) or \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":684,\"end\":699}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Xiaopin banruo boluomi jing\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":699,\"end\":726},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"52d40a3c-ea24-48bd-9ab3-2910bebc1883\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (小品般若波羅蜜經), Taishō 227, translated by Kumārajīva in the early fifth century. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":726,\"end\":804}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":657,\"end\":804,\"uuid\":\"aaeb6659-3b54-486b-aad5-4f7246db129e\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":657,\"end\":804,\"uuid\":\"aaeb6659-3b54-486b-aad5-4f7246db129e\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Two of the sections or “assemblies” of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":804,\"end\":847}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Da banruo boluomiduo jing\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":847,\"end\":872},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bb9db7f9-6e4e-477f-848e-ad7dd21afb12\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (大般若波羅蜜多經), Taishō 220, the great compilation of Prajñāpāramitā texts translated by Xuanzang in the seventh century: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":872,\"end\":990}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":804,\"end\":990}},{\"type\":\"bulletList\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"the fourth in 29 chapters (vol. VII, 763b–865a), from an original in eight thousand lines, and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":990,\"end\":1085}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":990,\"end\":1085,\"uuid\":\"e4b639e2-6882-42ec-86b2-4828a1a17274\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":990,\"end\":1085,\"uuid\":\"e4b639e2-6882-42ec-86b2-4828a1a17274\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"the fifth in 24 chapters (vol. VII, 865c–920b), similar in content but much shorter. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1085,\"end\":1170}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":1085,\"end\":1170,\"uuid\":\"1470da9d-3d09-4551-80d6-77453826c74e\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":1085,\"end\":1170,\"uuid\":\"1470da9d-3d09-4551-80d6-77453826c74e\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":990,\"end\":1170,\"uuid\":\"6378de97-0625-4c51-8162-babcad0bd8da\",\"nesting\":1,\"spacing\":\"horizontal\",\"itemStyle\":\"dots\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":804,\"end\":1170,\"uuid\":\"e36c273c-c695-4b36-ba7c-95e0c2d41f5b\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1170,\"end\":1174}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Fo shuo fomu chusheng san fazang banruoboluomi jing\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1174,\"end\":1225},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d162cea6-c37b-4819-8770-b818ff63c096\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (佛說佛母出生三法藏般若波羅蜜多經), Taishō 228, translated by *Dānapāla in the late tenth or early eleventh century.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1225,\"end\":1326}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":1170,\"end\":1326,\"uuid\":\"90bb67af-a9fa-4ba6-8daf-b5b997f7fe39\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":1170,\"end\":1326,\"uuid\":\"90bb67af-a9fa-4ba6-8daf-b5b997f7fe39\"}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"15559c27-7423-4595-a419-ac935521720b\",\"sort\":223,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":5,\"start\":0,\"end\":7,\"uuid\":\"dcb0e875-e875-4b9a-87d8-005b3be1e1a0\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tibetan\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"23d6f209-0a11-4183-84f5-a61fcd38c73e\",\"sort\":225,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.19\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":250,\"uuid\":\"23d6f209-0a11-4183-84f5-a61fcd38c73e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Although this translation has been made principally from the Sanskrit, many readers may wish to read it along with the Tibetan text. It would therefore be an omission not to include here some mention of the complex history of the Tibetan translation.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":250}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"13caa0d9-43b1-4715-90da-398fc2c2d580\",\"sort\":227,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.20\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":149,\"uuid\":\"a28ba981-3acc-4679-90ac-d0fb857dfaad\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The colophon of the version of the Tibetan text in the Degé Kangyur records seven consecutive stages in its evolution from the earliest translation: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":149}}]},{\"type\":\"bulletList\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":149,\"end\":1012,\"uuid\":\"35bafb18-9b4f-41da-8d7b-49cd0e8938d6\",\"spacing\":\"horizontal\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1. in the early, imperially sponsored translation period (late eighth or early ninth century), translation, revision, and verification by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":149,\"end\":287}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śākyasena\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":287,\"end\":296},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"cb964334-adc9-4c58-9b74-5659b1047a31\",\"uuid\":\"748b9720-a579-4cd5-b0cd-73a1d808e817\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":296,\"end\":298}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Jñānasiddhi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":298,\"end\":309},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"86598882-1218-4887-8df3-6c016aa50628\",\"uuid\":\"a6f9f5bd-53cc-4d41-a1fe-c823106d6123\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and the editor-lotsāwa \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":309,\"end\":334}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dharmataśīla\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":334,\"end\":346},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8ea02329-4d61-49a0-8072-b3dc4aa7c7e3\",\"uuid\":\"5319f456-f52a-421b-8dcb-eb7ce3465559\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Chönyi Tsültrim); \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":346,\"end\":366}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":149,\"end\":366,\"uuid\":\"a05c38fc-15fd-4e97-937c-c125a7cf51b7\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":149,\"end\":366,\"uuid\":\"a05c38fc-15fd-4e97-937c-c125a7cf51b7\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2. in the late tenth century, harmonization with “the commentary” by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":366,\"end\":435}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Subhāṣita\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":435,\"end\":444},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"394ccfa8-a88d-4d4a-82ef-d7e988d2fc9b\",\"uuid\":\"8c277bc2-f2b4-41a9-9b2b-a0edf4680568\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":444,\"end\":449}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Zangpo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":449,\"end\":463},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"b3117f6c-8b33-404c-93db-0e331ab39488\",\"uuid\":\"651eb78b-e347-42ba-965e-3e01ab28205f\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":463,\"end\":465}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":366,\"end\":465,\"uuid\":\"ddd0abb2-ab4e-4cd0-9405-f9b2a52fd128\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":366,\"end\":465,\"uuid\":\"ddd0abb2-ab4e-4cd0-9405-f9b2a52fd128\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"3. in the early eleventh century, revision, correction, and editing by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":465,\"end\":536}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dīpaṃkaraśrījñāna\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":536,\"end\":553},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"1b7e341e-95b8-47c3-89e6-6c9610cefb0f\",\"uuid\":\"62fb6126-4b30-4042-b13b-285378124680\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":553,\"end\":558}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Zangpo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":558,\"end\":572},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"b3117f6c-8b33-404c-93db-0e331ab39488\",\"uuid\":\"4797392c-a3d5-499a-a4c1-bc7c8d5ea1c1\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" on the basis of “a commentary from Magadha”; \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":572,\"end\":618}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":465,\"end\":618,\"uuid\":\"f83628f0-d239-47da-89a1-524e355472cb\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":465,\"end\":618,\"uuid\":\"f83628f0-d239-47da-89a1-524e355472cb\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"4. verification of a passage by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":618,\"end\":650}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dīpaṃkaraśrījñāna\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":650,\"end\":667},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"1b7e341e-95b8-47c3-89e6-6c9610cefb0f\",\"uuid\":\"5c7ef407-cac2-4b57-b985-8a2cdb6a1ccb\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the translator \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":667,\"end\":687}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dromtön Gyalwai Jungné\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":687,\"end\":709},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"02f47f04-862d-4b90-82e9-f287aedfc7ad\",\"uuid\":\"95515b9a-23da-4365-9a49-50a40053d8c5\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":709,\"end\":711}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":618,\"end\":711,\"uuid\":\"b7fcac90-0674-4c88-b564-875956c2c3c6\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":618,\"end\":711,\"uuid\":\"b7fcac90-0674-4c88-b564-875956c2c3c6\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"5. verification by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":711,\"end\":730}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dromtön Gyalwai Jungné\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":730,\"end\":752},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"02f47f04-862d-4b90-82e9-f287aedfc7ad\",\"uuid\":\"3f26ccca-bf61-4842-80bb-34a5891e82a6\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", twice, against three Indian manuscripts; \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":752,\"end\":795}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":711,\"end\":795,\"uuid\":\"da12bd24-a3b9-469b-b54a-720a7bada672\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":711,\"end\":795,\"uuid\":\"da12bd24-a3b9-469b-b54a-720a7bada672\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"6. further verification of some minor points by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":795,\"end\":843}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dromtön Gyalwai Jungné\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":843,\"end\":865},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"02f47f04-862d-4b90-82e9-f287aedfc7ad\",\"uuid\":\"c44b26a4-a149-4cb5-bf58-ae42d7045ab0\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":865,\"end\":871}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":795,\"end\":871,\"uuid\":\"d8ca10c4-3b15-4b90-9364-100c7c327b27\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":795,\"end\":871,\"uuid\":\"d8ca10c4-3b15-4b90-9364-100c7c327b27\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"7. in the late eleventh or early twelfth century, verification by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":871,\"end\":937}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ngok Loden Sherab\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":937,\"end\":954},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"6b13fc98-09b7-4746-87ea-7f8e8a712005\",\"uuid\":\"880c9ffe-76b2-4d0a-894a-24e4a6745193\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" against a number of manuscripts from Kashmir and Magadha.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":954,\"end\":1012}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":871,\"end\":1012,\"uuid\":\"c15086a1-c230-48ec-af97-0cfa9e2d1867\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":871,\"end\":1012,\"uuid\":\"c15086a1-c230-48ec-af97-0cfa9e2d1867\"}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0464479e-0b61-4bec-9788-46f859a5908f\",\"sort\":266,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.21\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81,\"uuid\":\"2eeca942-5bfd-4e2e-9ac8-f83bcf635095\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"To these stages, the colophons in the Narthang and Lhasa Kangyurs add an eighth: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":81}}]},{\"type\":\"bulletList\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":319,\"uuid\":\"47425e8d-02d4-4adc-976d-a4f911b7fb27\",\"spacing\":\"horizontal\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"8. in the late fifteenth or early sixteenth century, further corrections by the Zhalu translator Pal \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":182}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Chökyong Zangpo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":182,\"end\":205},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"707c77e9-456a-4996-887a-8e8cc1cd9503\",\"uuid\":\"f08e3af0-e9ba-4100-bf65-7505b211ceba\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", who edited and verified the text from the earlier versions compared with several Tibetan and Indian manuscripts.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":205,\"end\":319}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":319,\"uuid\":\"a31a5b7c-37c4-4cb6-82a1-47480489b254\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":319,\"uuid\":\"a31a5b7c-37c4-4cb6-82a1-47480489b254\"}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5d5f7ebb-3cf1-4f7e-b88b-966946425494\",\"sort\":271,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.22\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":325,\"uuid\":\"5d5f7ebb-3cf1-4f7e-b88b-966946425494\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The colophons in two of the Kangyurs of the Themphangma line, the Stok Palace (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":79}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"stog pho brang\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":93},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":93,\"uuid\":\"7ee8a45e-839b-4b09-b740-2c585589ec79\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") and Zhey (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":93,\"end\":105}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"shel mkhar\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":105,\"end\":115},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":105,\"end\":115,\"uuid\":\"449c993d-0dee-4f73-a0c9-0db11b8d9ee5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") Kangyurs, and of one version of the text in the Phukdrak (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":115,\"end\":175}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"phug brag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":175,\"end\":184},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":175,\"end\":184,\"uuid\":\"e4c8f485-caf0-492d-8462-d55048d0dd7e\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") Kangyur, add further names and details, seemingly to this same stage of editing, and date it to an Iron Tiger year (possibly 1471 or 1531).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":184,\"end\":325}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0e7e5b45-466a-4c5e-9ceb-431b309d62a4\",\"sort\":279,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.23\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1432,\"uuid\":\"0e7e5b45-466a-4c5e-9ceb-431b309d62a4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In parallel to these details recorded in the colophons, traditional Tibetan scholarship identifies three textual traditions for the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":132}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":132,\"end\":146},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7619faf4-1ffb-48a0-ae71-36bc1e45ec21\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", differing only in minor stylistic phrasing, but distinguished‍—and named‍—according to how they render in Tibetan the Sanskrit name of the wandering ascetic \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":146,\"end\":305}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śreṇika\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":305,\"end\":312},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c6eeefbc-2b12-4439-986c-1c38ae18a036\",\"uuid\":\"53042e5f-8871-450f-8328-628123f931ba\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", who is mentioned in the first chapter (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":312,\"end\":353}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1.23\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":353,\"end\":357},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3b489e7b-21e9-4dcf-97d9-c44dc56b12a1\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/2ce0b422-a8ad-458f-bc27-e9219c120561\",\"entity\":\"2ce0b422-a8ad-458f-bc27-e9219c120561\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"translation\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") as having \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":357,\"end\":369}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"firm conviction\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":369,\"end\":384},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"14d822fc-e184-4e5e-affd-9e3b08918c08\",\"uuid\":\"55651ad8-51d9-42c3-a85f-3bfda5d53d9f\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in the Buddha’s teaching. The names of these three versions of the text are \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":384,\"end\":461}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’phreng ba can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":461,\"end\":475},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cf519dbc-958a-4ba4-96f8-7cc5bca24c9d\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (pronounced “Trengwachen”), \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":475,\"end\":504}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bzo sbyangs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":504,\"end\":515},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"65885e3b-56fe-4588-bedb-9b4fa3e5b107\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“Zojang”), and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":515,\"end\":532}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sde can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":532,\"end\":539},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"86797e50-5d67-4d9d-9b2d-efaf0226073a\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“Dechen”). The extant Sanskrit manuscripts use only the name \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":539,\"end\":602}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śreṇika\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":602,\"end\":609},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c6eeefbc-2b12-4439-986c-1c38ae18a036\",\"uuid\":\"a4bc4568-0193-4da3-a63b-ada554f7b0f6\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" for the wandering ascetic in this passage, but one of the greatest Sanskrit scholars in Tibet, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":609,\"end\":705}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Chökyong Zangpo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":705,\"end\":728},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"707c77e9-456a-4996-887a-8e8cc1cd9503\",\"uuid\":\"c4fe0778-69c7-4b98-89c4-a3fd7e76756a\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the last recorded reviser of the text (see the stage numbered 8 above), is said to have mentioned witnessing three different versions of the Sanskrit name (set out below) in different Indian manuscripts of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":728,\"end\":940}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":940,\"end\":954},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f0d35070-1cb9-4b1c-bc6a-8db315342ba7\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", each corresponding to the three renderings in Tibetan. He is also said to have confirmed that between these different manuscripts there were no other variants with a significant impact on meaning.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":954,\"end\":1152},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"0ef35234-d1f8-4e07-96d2-622354d310e5\",\"label\":\"10\",\"uuid\":\"2105a419-f8af-49a7-987d-a7b8ca0bf57f\",\"start\":1152,\"end\":1152,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Olkha Lelung Jedrung disagrees with earlier scholars who thought that these were three entirely different names for the same person, and expresses the opinion that the three Sanskrit names mentioned by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1152,\"end\":1355}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Chökyong Zangpo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1355,\"end\":1378},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"707c77e9-456a-4996-887a-8e8cc1cd9503\",\"uuid\":\"69697faa-2137-4c17-89fe-44473a35a7cf\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" are in effect no more than variants of the same name.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1378,\"end\":1432},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"735925a4-a2ad-40bc-bae5-1df68466003f\",\"label\":\"11\",\"uuid\":\"26375aef-9952-4706-9d6c-45dfaf88bc22\",\"start\":1432,\"end\":1432,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a9e6efc3-1a66-4f28-9b50-2b6e302a5da4\",\"sort\":306,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.24\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1415,\"uuid\":\"a9e6efc3-1a66-4f28-9b50-2b6e302a5da4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Although the Degé Kangyur catalog seems to say that the three versions correspond to different Sanskrit source manuscripts,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":123},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"6c2df32e-7f8e-4592-9b20-c0fab48ee30d\",\"label\":\"12\",\"uuid\":\"28c625b3-8805-4b91-ae9c-27238fcc3d63\",\"start\":123,\"end\":123,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" the most likely explanation for the existence of these three textual traditions, differing principally in this minor distinction alone, is that they represent the sequential results of specific revisions made (along with many others) over time to the original Tibetan translation. A study by Torricelli and Dudka, and another by Shōji, suggest that the earliest translation may have rendered the name as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":123,\"end\":528}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bzo sbyangs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":528,\"end\":539},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f78c68a8-f22a-4f8f-aad1-6e3972052088\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", that the name \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":539,\"end\":555}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sde can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":555,\"end\":562},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5dbedf1f-0c3a-4745-a782-021bea9ed962\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" may be characteristic of a revision made by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":562,\"end\":607}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Kamalaśīla\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":607,\"end\":617},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"cb43148b-eca9-4075-a5cb-a1e1d03682c8\",\"uuid\":\"06cbaf6a-979f-4b84-a992-bd3a7a010214\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and Kawa Paltsek, and that \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":617,\"end\":645}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’phreng ba can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":645,\"end\":659},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0cfbb84f-e291-48a3-8cac-56a190823297\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" was a revision introduced at a later stage in the editorial history of the text, perhaps with the coming to Tibet of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":659,\"end\":777}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Atiśa Dīpaṃkaraśrījñāna\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":777,\"end\":800},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"1b7e341e-95b8-47c3-89e6-6c9610cefb0f\",\"uuid\":\"5bd09a3b-3a52-4acb-a4a7-9feab01f751e\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Shōji does go so far as to divide the hypothetical Sanskrit manuscript traditions into two, A and B, with the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":800,\"end\":912}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bzo sbyangs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":912,\"end\":923},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fa9dfc18-2d82-4bf2-b3b4-573a77167c15\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":923,\"end\":928}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sde can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":928,\"end\":935},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a92341fd-afd0-4c40-bbc3-a354f98316f0\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Tibetan versions derived from A, and the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":935,\"end\":977}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’phreng ba can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":977,\"end\":991},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"25c206c0-4000-4e70-a8a5-1728b103f9ff\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" from B. Both of the studies mentioned assume that the commentary used by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":991,\"end\":1065}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Subhāṣita\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1065,\"end\":1074},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"394ccfa8-a88d-4d4a-82ef-d7e988d2fc9b\",\"uuid\":\"499f3626-812e-40ed-8353-43817de78601\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1074,\"end\":1079}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Zangpo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1079,\"end\":1093},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"b3117f6c-8b33-404c-93db-0e331ab39488\",\"uuid\":\"493c6b45-3b12-4cd0-8055-5b773074c8e3\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" for their revision of the sūtra (stage 2 above) was that of Haribhadra, the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1093,\"end\":1170}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Abhisamayālaṃkārāloka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1170,\"end\":1191},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"47fd0601-a337-449e-972f-c771a2309a9c\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (see below), and the integration of the name change from the commentary may suffice to explain the origin of the B lineage.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1191,\"end\":1315},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"a5f7ff08-6393-44ac-b257-1b1ae1a0fc20\",\"label\":\"13\",\"uuid\":\"3b37493a-6594-4443-aaa1-68cf6951f2c2\",\"start\":1315,\"end\":1315,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The use of all three names in the different sūtras and commentaries (see below) supports that view.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1315,\"end\":1415}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"97fa388a-af40-4744-a0c5-d955dbcd0a45\",\"sort\":334,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.25\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":120,\"uuid\":\"d35e9460-fa50-4012-b0bc-57d05f8a99be\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The details in the available Tibetan sources and modern studies on these three traditions can be summarized as follows: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":120}}]},{\"type\":\"bulletList\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":1619,\"uuid\":\"7fe01627-4df2-4573-9ae2-a2c2c62a46f5\",\"spacing\":\"horizontal\",\"itemStyle\":\"dots\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sde can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":127},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d0b7e1ab-e663-4432-8b0d-7ee783c50976\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\": taken by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":127,\"end\":138}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Chökyong Zangpo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":138,\"end\":161},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"707c77e9-456a-4996-887a-8e8cc1cd9503\",\"uuid\":\"c1d4f6ff-e693-4dd4-bc7a-6fc2bbbbda0f\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to render the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":161,\"end\":185}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Seniṣka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":185,\"end\":192},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3a06c386-58af-4219-afdd-b3a8196371d8\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The rarest of the three traditions, only one extant witness is known, an independent thirteenth-century manuscript in the LTWA collection.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":192,\"end\":332},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"98586d9e-6066-4d33-8aba-ce1b0845e90a\",\"label\":\"14\",\"uuid\":\"1016dd20-6325-42e0-88fe-57cb2693b4a0\",\"start\":332,\"end\":332,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Thought to have been a version resulting first from revisions made by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":332,\"end\":403}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Kamalaśīla\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":403,\"end\":413},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"cb43148b-eca9-4075-a5cb-a1e1d03682c8\",\"uuid\":\"28f05972-de43-433b-ba5c-fca83137ca8b\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and Kawa Paltsek in the eighth century to the very earliest translation, and then from further revisions made to that version by Dharmaśrībhadra and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":413,\"end\":563}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Zangpo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":563,\"end\":577},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"b3117f6c-8b33-404c-93db-0e331ab39488\",\"uuid\":\"1e0212aa-1d41-462b-b3bb-46e1751e111c\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in the early eleventh century, before \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":577,\"end\":616}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Atiśa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":616,\"end\":621},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"1b7e341e-95b8-47c3-89e6-6c9610cefb0f\",\"uuid\":\"484e6e91-c7d6-47a3-bcdd-a60df0aef4a1\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s arrival in Tibet. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":621,\"end\":642}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":642,\"uuid\":\"18a87767-057d-4a08-83f7-f002eae144e3\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":642,\"uuid\":\"18a87767-057d-4a08-83f7-f002eae144e3\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bzo sbyangs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":642,\"end\":653},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"14ce50f9-fd1f-4064-bd82-a8bf621bd8fc\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\": taken by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":653,\"end\":664}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Chökyong Zangpo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":664,\"end\":687},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"707c77e9-456a-4996-887a-8e8cc1cd9503\",\"uuid\":\"1eb50e03-027b-4206-9937-4dce914290da\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to render the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":687,\"end\":711}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śaniṣka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":711,\"end\":718},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"63bdbef1-8d11-4fe4-8e0f-11bbafae9466\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Witnesses of this version are found in the Toyo Bunko and the London (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":718,\"end\":790}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"shel dkar\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":790,\"end\":799},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":790,\"end\":799,\"uuid\":\"d1524c35-8ebe-4524-b8b5-8dd0dd636a0b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") Kangyurs, as one (F 11b) of the three versions of the sūtra in the Phukdrak Kangyur, and as some independent manuscripts. One of the latter\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":799,\"end\":940},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"72f2480d-97fb-45df-9cc7-0797ebdcbef7\",\"label\":\"15\",\"uuid\":\"41938647-bc0b-4ffe-bcc3-f7896c34bd5c\",\"start\":940,\"end\":940,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" has a colophon mentioning only the names of the early translators, suggesting that this version may represent the early translation in its unrevised form. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":940,\"end\":1096}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":642,\"end\":1096,\"uuid\":\"5c6b45e7-71cb-44b1-901f-e27b25551ad0\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":642,\"end\":1096,\"uuid\":\"5c6b45e7-71cb-44b1-901f-e27b25551ad0\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’phreng ba can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1096,\"end\":1110},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a9d7f3fb-ab0e-4120-bd92-4f678e12b61a\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\": taken by \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1110,\"end\":1121}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rinchen Chökyong Zangpo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1121,\"end\":1144},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"707c77e9-456a-4996-887a-8e8cc1cd9503\",\"uuid\":\"1a40b8d7-df33-4b7a-8df0-e0e62a377f10\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to render the Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1144,\"end\":1168}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Praniṣka.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1168,\"end\":1177},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ba09c4ae-610d-4624-817f-c174c9cc5040\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" This is the most widespread version of the sūtra in Tibetan and is the one witnessed in most independent versions of the text and in all Tshalpa and mixed Kangyurs, in the Stok Palace and Zhey Kangyurs among those of the Themphangma line, and the two other versions in the Phukdrak Kangyur. The two forms of the colophon found appended to such versions detail the full set of eight or more translation and revision stages, as outlined above.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1177,\"end\":1619}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":1096,\"end\":1619,\"uuid\":\"b9348191-51fa-4ea4-bc2f-96b1f3e9a4af\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":1096,\"end\":1619,\"uuid\":\"b9348191-51fa-4ea4-bc2f-96b1f3e9a4af\"}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8a976eff-b3ec-4219-8b39-5c3216e56b25\",\"sort\":370,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.26\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1053,\"uuid\":\"8a976eff-b3ec-4219-8b39-5c3216e56b25\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"It should be noted in this context that in the other Prajñāpāramitā sūtras, the name of the same wandering ascetic, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":116}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śreṇika\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":116,\"end\":123},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c6eeefbc-2b12-4439-986c-1c38ae18a036\",\"uuid\":\"32ed410d-36e7-4f66-9fdb-69b0e490a12a\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", is rendered in Tibetan as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":123,\"end\":151}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’phreng ba can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":151,\"end\":165},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"dc762709-8507-43a0-b641-3c7c237b33b3\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":165,\"end\":173}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Hundred Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":173,\"end\":189},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"10188575-6f38-46ca-8d68-9e709ad6bb27\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 8) and the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":189,\"end\":206}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Twenty-Five Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":206,\"end\":226},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"691d959b-ea17-4202-8233-0f68e0e51e38\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 9), but as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":226,\"end\":243}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bzo sbyangs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":243,\"end\":254},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"63aa888b-c755-4b38-9085-9a4ff93cbefc\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":254,\"end\":262}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eighteen Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":262,\"end\":279},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ff471c44-ed0e-472b-a6c0-63eb5f358592\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 10), the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":279,\"end\":294}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ten Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":294,\"end\":306},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4e287482-9775-4270-8e95-9bcf56180b81\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 11), and the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":306,\"end\":325}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Verse Summary\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":325,\"end\":338},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3abef4b4-c2e0-4021-9755-87ba84fa90dc\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":338,\"end\":340}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 13\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":340,\"end\":346},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d73d7f79-4b2f-4e70-95cf-6faaa444e765\",\"href\":\"/translation/toh13\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). Furthermore, in the Tengyur, the Tibetan translations of Bhadanta Vimuktisena’s commentary (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":346,\"end\":441}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 3788\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":441,\"end\":449},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2f5548af-2440-4fec-ac03-82e1e05e6b89\",\"href\":\"/translation/toh3788\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") on \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":449,\"end\":454}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Ornament of Clear Realization\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":454,\"end\":487},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0eab68a8-81d6-41f6-8c56-68fa67d3e051\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (see below) and of Ratnākaraśānti’s commentary (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":487,\"end\":536}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 3803\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":536,\"end\":544},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"52f2acdb-2575-4552-a0ec-9e94fd40502f\",\"href\":\"/translation/toh3803\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") on the present text (much referred to in the notes to this translation) both render the name as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":544,\"end\":642}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sde can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":642,\"end\":649},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8cc93577-030c-499c-a8c9-d5209107ad86\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", while those of Dharmaśrī’s commentary (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":649,\"end\":690}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 3802\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":690,\"end\":698},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6c381a11-f027-4bd2-a1f8-bcd8f09ed1b0\",\"href\":\"/translation/toh3803\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":698,\"end\":707}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Hundred Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":707,\"end\":723},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f65f7bb0-10fb-4c6d-916d-5fcecdb54a59\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the commentary on the three long sūtras attributed to Vasubandhu or Daṃṣṭrasena (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":723,\"end\":809}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 3808\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":809,\"end\":817},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3f59550c-7081-4440-9a28-21c8ef3b1126\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/009cb40f-b705-410b-91cc-7a638ff76054\",\"entity\":\"009cb40f-b705-410b-91cc-7a638ff76054\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh3808\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") both render the name as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":817,\"end\":843}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bzo sbyangs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":843,\"end\":854},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f7082585-2e25-41ab-9f7d-6f9a0797aa41\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". It is therefore intriguing that the classification of Tibetan translations based on the threefold variants of this name seems only to be mentioned with regard to translations of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":854,\"end\":1038}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1038,\"end\":1052},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ec1bf4e5-0a4d-420b-8089-24729d35155a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1052,\"end\":1053}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"eb65e842-4150-4e05-b752-45a6b0fa5868\",\"sort\":408,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.27\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":757,\"uuid\":\"eb65e842-4150-4e05-b752-45a6b0fa5868\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In any case, the Tibetan translation found in most Kangyurs is closely aligned with the extant Sanskrit and may be read with it, as will be seen using the bilingual view in the present translation as published online, which uses the text from the Degé Kangyur. Minor variants between different Kangyurs are comparatively infrequent and have not been recorded in the notes, given that the translation is based principally on the Sanskrit. Among the many available versions of the Tibetan text, of particular note is the magnificent volume in the Lhasa (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":552}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"zhol\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":552,\"end\":556},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":552,\"end\":556,\"uuid\":\"b1e6779c-d2f9-4066-9b1a-60f503920d78\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") Kangyur, printed from woodblocks made in the early 1930s, with two line drawings‍—each depicting a notable figure in the transmission of the sūtra‍—on the recto of every single one of its 523 folios.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":556,\"end\":757}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bbdf9743-bddb-4cd6-a0a6-e224e04cc8b5\",\"sort\":412,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.28\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":290,\"uuid\":\"bbdf9743-bddb-4cd6-a0a6-e224e04cc8b5\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In summary, the Tibetan translation seems to have been very carefully checked, edited, revised, and verified against a number of Sanskrit manuscripts, and indeed with the help of one or more of the Indian commentaries (although there is no record of which\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":255},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"fe68af45-7599-4b7c-8fd4-cff9e53329a9\",\"label\":\"16\",\"uuid\":\"fc4525c5-51e6-434e-b9df-69e398791b3f\",\"start\":255,\"end\":255,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), by many generations of scholars.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":255,\"end\":290}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"77064695-111c-4f8c-9eca-edb34e5bb265\",\"sort\":415,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":4,\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"uuid\":\"1b7f14f4-55c3-4a79-bc61-874c300a1a4a\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Commentaries\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"84ce143b-e9db-49c9-8323-8049b8bd2930\",\"sort\":417,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.29\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":521,\"uuid\":\"84ce143b-e9db-49c9-8323-8049b8bd2930\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Readers of this translation of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":35}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":49},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0a8111ad-748e-46f3-9d77-8cd83d806d52\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" will not necessarily be making use of the treatises and commentaries to help them understand how the tradition understands the esoteric meaning of the Prajñāpāramitā scriptures, for much in these works can indeed be understood on its own. Nevertheless, the selected material from the commentaries that we have included in the notes is quite extensive, and it may therefore be helpful to sketch out the historical background and ongoing role of the commentarial tradition.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":49,\"end\":521}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"69632e4f-ff8f-43f2-8d57-4afbbab1d9f6\",\"sort\":420,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":5,\"start\":0,\"end\":53,\"uuid\":\"d5b2af6c-895f-48f2-867f-747f119d01a0\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Commentaries on the Prajñāpāramitā Scriptures Overall\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":53}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0b84650c-6404-4e53-884c-0fa19b44147e\",\"sort\":422,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.30\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":221,\"uuid\":\"0b84650c-6404-4e53-884c-0fa19b44147e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Prajñāpāramitā scriptures themselves were much read and studied throughout the Mahāyāna Buddhist world, yet as standalone works they were almost certainly no less difficult to understand fully than we find them today.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":221}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f3fc3c5e-5cde-4c3c-8989-268312ff1a19\",\"sort\":424,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.31\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1186,\"uuid\":\"f3fc3c5e-5cde-4c3c-8989-268312ff1a19\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"If we extrapolate from the scriptures themselves, their intended audience includes two distinct spiritual types, namely, (a) the “faithful type” (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":146}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"śraddhānusārin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":146,\"end\":160},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":146,\"end\":160,\"uuid\":\"d2daf81b-0e3d-4dfc-9260-343e37577d9a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), those who have enough faith in the Mahāyāna teachings that they can enter the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":160,\"end\":241}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"path of preliminary practice\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":241,\"end\":269},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"5b884783-353d-4b51-9f6e-5b8ab29c823b\",\"uuid\":\"cc99c86e-c635-4a33-80bd-f95f3604f49b\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" through faith alone, and (b) the “intellectual type” (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":269,\"end\":324}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dharmānusārin\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":324,\"end\":337},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":324,\"end\":337,\"uuid\":\"89b18253-c6dc-4b65-9b84-2b06621959e0\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), those who have faith in the Mahāyāna teachings but require explanations that seem true to them analytically before they enter the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":337,\"end\":470}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"path of preliminary practice\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":470,\"end\":498},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"5b884783-353d-4b51-9f6e-5b8ab29c823b\",\"uuid\":\"fff50041-131f-433d-b17f-cf3f56001958\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":498,\"end\":499},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"4aa30b5f-9f30-43dc-9e0d-44a55771d04f\",\"label\":\"17\",\"uuid\":\"13ce47af-95d9-48cf-9492-d157d682fb12\",\"start\":499,\"end\":499,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" For the faithful type, it is just revering or reciting the scripture‍—even without any understanding of the esoteric meaning‍—that is said to have immediate worldly benefits and to set them quickly on the path to complete awakening. For the intellectual type, on the other hand, it is studying the esoteric meaning of the scripture that is supposed to have immediate worldly benefits and to lead eventually to complete awakening. The Prajñāpāramitā scriptures are aimed at both types, since hearing or reading them is a necessary condition for awakening, but on its own is not a sufficient condition for a clear understanding of the Perfection of Wisdom itself or its related practices.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":499,\"end\":1186}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c11809d2-89a1-4f9c-900f-ef0b12084d9d\",\"sort\":436,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.32\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":375,\"uuid\":\"c11809d2-89a1-4f9c-900f-ef0b12084d9d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Those wishing to practice the teachings were explicitly said to require the guidance of a teacher and to devote themselves wholeheartedly to study. As the Prajñāpāramitā sūtras spread across the Indian subcontinent and beyond, the direct guidance of teachers does not seem to have been enough. Out of the need for more extensive guidance, the commentarial tradition was born.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":375}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cfab8160-ad78-4fae-8ad1-2c32ffd3c851\",\"sort\":438,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.33\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":282,\"uuid\":\"cfab8160-ad78-4fae-8ad1-2c32ffd3c851\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The complexity of interpreting the language and meaning of these scriptures is witnessed by the large number of different commentaries and treatises composed over the centuries, and the variety of interpretive traditions.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":221},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"924238cc-d087-4f04-bd20-ef8521778dfc\",\"label\":\"18\",\"uuid\":\"dd4a2717-c5bb-4268-b375-ff0ff90de6df\",\"start\":221,\"end\":221,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Schematically, these can be seen as arising in three phases.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":221,\"end\":282}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d455b5a3-019a-4265-b699-b049d6a78b0a\",\"sort\":442,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.34\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":350,\"uuid\":\"d455b5a3-019a-4265-b699-b049d6a78b0a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"First, Nāgārjuna’s treatise, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Root Verses on the Middle Way\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":62},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8b80f3b1-b117-46ac-b63f-90440d3ecaa5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":62,\"end\":64}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mūlamadhyamakakārikā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":64,\"end\":84},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ecdd7d13-d8bc-4f85-9ac1-b20e5d6a9d4d\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":84,\"end\":86}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 3824\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":94},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"84271b21-6d83-4899-9ed8-36342b5bb6f5\",\"href\":\"/translation/toh3824\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), clarified their explicit teachings on emptiness, and the commentary attributed to him by the Chinese tradition, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":94,\"end\":209}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Instructions on the Great Perfection of Wisdom\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":209,\"end\":255},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"74eb75b4-80b4-4799-9900-143ae7541734\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":255,\"end\":257}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dazhidu lun\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":257,\"end\":268},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"94621afa-b4da-4012-99ff-04c60672ecf2\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", *\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":268,\"end\":271}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mahāprajñāpāramitopadeśa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":271,\"end\":295},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cfe90897-f85e-4457-80b0-8209ea23b8b7\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), unpacked their terminology and general implications.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":295,\"end\":350},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"52805295-ab41-4f56-8850-4444a31bf5bb\",\"label\":\"19\",\"uuid\":\"2aa3929f-a26e-44b2-b534-0a97fa68d1fc\",\"start\":350,\"end\":350,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5a8e8695-6b38-4735-915f-7b5080963e99\",\"sort\":457,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.35\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":613,\"uuid\":\"5a8e8695-6b38-4735-915f-7b5080963e99\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Next, according to some traditions, the great master Asaṅga (fourth century \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":76}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":76,\"end\":78},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":76,\"end\":78,\"uuid\":\"c13958d3-bfcd-44f1-8c0d-bed12a359bbf\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") found the logical coherence of the structure and content of these scriptures so difficult to grasp that he prayed to the bodhisattva \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":78,\"end\":213}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Maitreya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":213,\"end\":221},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"34e9bd80-03ca-4582-8295-19dcf8d87219\",\"uuid\":\"69fbc9ce-ec17-45bb-aee1-76bc376af62e\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" for guidance. In response to his prayers, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":221,\"end\":264}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Maitreya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":264,\"end\":272},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"34e9bd80-03ca-4582-8295-19dcf8d87219\",\"uuid\":\"73f4196f-5f7c-4d5d-92d5-6553d6d6e556\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is said to have transmitted to Asaṅga (along with four other works) the treatise called \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":272,\"end\":361}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Ornament of Clear Realization\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":361,\"end\":394},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"22e2e195-a71b-42ff-a6ee-cca063e3d88a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 3786, hereafter referred to as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":394,\"end\":431}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":431,\"end\":439},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1afe3dc6-1229-4918-8588-2403c8c2e39b\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), which reveals the implicit framework of eight topics necessary for understanding how the Prajñāpāramitā scriptures are structured around the stages and paths to awakening.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":439,\"end\":613},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"0e46825f-dd36-4057-bb8a-b79f725e94ac\",\"label\":\"20\",\"uuid\":\"1dde739a-5ab2-4087-a4e3-55ec4923768c\",\"start\":613,\"end\":613,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"395d29c2-c137-4455-90a4-c98b84fc03f3\",\"sort\":470,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.36\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":398,\"uuid\":\"395d29c2-c137-4455-90a4-c98b84fc03f3\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Finally, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":9}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Long Explanation of the Noble Perfection of Wisdom in One Hundred Thousand, Twenty-Five Thousand, and Eighteen Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":9,\"end\":138},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d266463f-0807-407c-a343-1bda6fbe62c4\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 3808), attributed by some to Vasubandhu (fourth to fifth century) and by others to Daṃṣṭrasena (eighth to early ninth century), presents the structure of the larger scriptures as involving three approaches to the topic: brief, intermediate, and detailed.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":138,\"end\":398},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"cf2139a1-c01a-4ead-9449-dbf92f4be745\",\"label\":\"21\",\"uuid\":\"6529fb31-8741-4cc0-ae4c-8773351ee914\",\"start\":398,\"end\":398,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bffbc96a-c532-4580-af6d-84dfd3e51142\",\"sort\":474,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":5,\"start\":0,\"end\":41,\"uuid\":\"ff0b6a67-6dff-4c01-848d-6695a5054396\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Commentaries on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":20,\"end\":34},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"76f997d0-864d-43bb-bfec-ef1fe51b4d12\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Itself\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":34,\"end\":41}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5bc22a26-d2fe-40bf-8b21-cd14dcf2c610\",\"sort\":478,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.37\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":469,\"uuid\":\"5bc22a26-d2fe-40bf-8b21-cd14dcf2c610\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Against this background of the Prajñāpāramitā treatises in general, Dignāga (480–540 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":85}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":85,\"end\":87},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":85,\"end\":87,\"uuid\":\"223f0815-b7b5-4968-990b-7e1f0c060c56\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") composed what purports to be a brief thematic summary of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":150}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":150,\"end\":164},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9afc08d4-aed2-4a7e-ac96-d3a9e8e61a44\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" called \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":164,\"end\":172}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Condensed Meaning\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":172,\"end\":193},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a3e48f0c-b958-4b0f-88aa-ecd880dd35ca\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":193,\"end\":195}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Piṇḍārtha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":195,\"end\":204},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5d1fcd08-0e40-4cd4-ad6d-7481c7f4f0f2\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":204,\"end\":206}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 3809\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":206,\"end\":214},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fd3a480c-f9ec-48c2-ba58-ca4a8b988f89\",\"href\":\"/translation/toh3809\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":214,\"end\":216},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"4ba2bebc-e60e-41af-a1b0-a4705ce7ab22\",\"label\":\"22\",\"uuid\":\"416f9750-e0e4-4223-b6d0-7cbe9cbff165\",\"start\":216,\"end\":216,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" But Dignāga’s summary highlights only specific aspects of the Perfection of Wisdom scripture, and the difficulties that nonspecialists had in understanding the philosophical and soteriological frameworks implied in the scripture seem to have continued.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":216,\"end\":469}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"964118cd-99ae-44d1-9432-9f804c065cdb\",\"sort\":492,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.38\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":748,\"uuid\":\"964118cd-99ae-44d1-9432-9f804c065cdb\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"For this reason, in the ninth century \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":38}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":40},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":40,\"uuid\":\"fa1ac0e1-2e26-4b74-8a49-cd0e2f5c8155\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", King Dharmapāla‍—who was devoted to the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":82}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":82,\"end\":96},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5b2b1333-42a5-47c7-98c5-7af368b5e75f\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" but confused about it‍—requested the great scholar Haribhadra to make it clear to him. In response, Haribhadra composed the commentary called \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":96,\"end\":239}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Light on the Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":239,\"end\":260},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2dfad0e8-9c3a-457f-9c11-6c0eb978d8c4\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":260,\"end\":262}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Abhisamayālaṃkārāloka\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":262,\"end\":283},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f74486d7-9695-45e2-9d23-4b71a20d77f6\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", hereafter referred to as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":283,\"end\":310}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Light\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":310,\"end\":315},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"28dfd12b-55ec-43aa-8774-3f7082fad01a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), which uses \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":315,\"end\":329}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Maitreya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":329,\"end\":337},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"34e9bd80-03ca-4582-8295-19dcf8d87219\",\"uuid\":\"d5f0aaed-2f38-431f-a104-5b9098218e65\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":337,\"end\":340}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":340,\"end\":348},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e4e17d42-06a2-4cfc-a4c5-29fc01d0588d\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to explain the structure and meaning of the topics in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":348,\"end\":407}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":407,\"end\":421},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"428b58fe-5ab0-45bc-9820-43ce6c5cec59\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Haribhadra’s \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":421,\"end\":436}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Light\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":436,\"end\":441},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0c72501a-351c-484e-9810-b900db77c972\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" quickly became the standard commentary for understanding the scripture. As well as its Tibetan translation preserved in the Tengyur (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":441,\"end\":575}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 3791\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":575,\"end\":583},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c7676877-0c9b-4b4d-ac5b-d9fa6b4f7ac4\",\"href\":\"/translation/toh3791\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), the complete Sanskrit text of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":583,\"end\":616}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Light\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":616,\"end\":621},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c3c7e6f3-d3f6-420a-a3b6-f4c05ed65bda\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" has been preserved and is available in several editions, notably one made by the Japanese scholar Unrai Wogihara in the 1930s.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":621,\"end\":748}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8ac05c81-29ae-4f24-aae6-b27d0219e213\",\"sort\":516,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.39\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":766,\"uuid\":\"8ac05c81-29ae-4f24-aae6-b27d0219e213\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In the eleventh century, Ratnākaraśānti composed \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":49}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Quintessence of the Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":49,\"end\":87},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6245950b-45cc-4098-a0b2-9ddf5e29c23e\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":89}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Aṣṭa­sāhasrikā­prajñā­pāramitā­pañjikāsārottamā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":89,\"end\":136},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9fe63c2f-c9ff-4f8d-a471-c2b445a1fe46\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", hereafter \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":136,\"end\":148}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Quintessence\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":148,\"end\":160},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ebe17e9b-ad14-46b1-8e43-67fba59e9276\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). It has been preserved in Tibetan translation in the Tengyur (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":160,\"end\":224}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 3803\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":224,\"end\":232},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0f7249f7-df72-46e0-8632-baa7b304ba9f\",\"href\":\"/translation/toh3803\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), and incompletely in a Sanskrit edition by Padmanabh Jaini, published in 1979.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":232,\"end\":312},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"8ec68791-a4c8-45d4-a180-7d17772133cd\",\"label\":\"23\",\"uuid\":\"126d2a11-46e5-44f5-a53a-eb61a74d9ed8\",\"start\":312,\"end\":312,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" As the only other commentary on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":312,\"end\":349}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":349,\"end\":363},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"02e7b2bc-0ef9-4133-bae7-d923f8977c6d\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", it addresses matters that Haribhadra had not covered and disputes some things that he had. But aside from unpacking the scripture, Ratnākaraśānti aimed to show‍—through his many commentaries‍—how central the Perfection of Wisdom is to both Mahāyāna and tantric practice, as in the concluding lines of his opening verses to \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":363,\"end\":688}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Instructions on the Perfection of Wisdom\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":688,\"end\":732},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1b7d7ef6-3843-4ed0-91d3-178d82cfc895\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":732,\"end\":734}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Prajñāpāramitopadeśa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":734,\"end\":754},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1908beb7-ddf6-4218-844c-e25c64532d9c\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":754,\"end\":756}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 4079\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":756,\"end\":764},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"111d9f37-cf9c-4387-a492-dab600eec9a5\",\"href\":\"/translation/toh4079\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"):\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":764,\"end\":766}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e047b8f0-a9b9-4d17-be69-4c49b88d8763\",\"sort\":536,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.40\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"blockquote\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":183,\"uuid\":\"4e6bafdf-0fbd-4f47-9bf0-6713db0eef14\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"lineGroup\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":183,\"uuid\":\"4d0cd027-b22e-40bd-8840-54a1e28e6ad7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"“By cultivating this blessed \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":29}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"supreme Perfection\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":29,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"6882b83e-6d4d-4178-8652-768c0ab6b718\",\"uuid\":\"25428b9f-a0a0-4168-ace6-1fbcdc62b62b\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" every day, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":59}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":59,\"uuid\":\"65dfe946-2a7d-4f6b-b7bb-a95292ad291e\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"One succeeds in the (methods of) the mantras \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":59,\"end\":104}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":59,\"end\":104,\"uuid\":\"95f18964-247d-4edf-8067-18e7b476358d\"}},{\"type\":\"line\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"And one holds the (methods of) the five perfections in the palm of one’s hand.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":104,\"end\":183}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":104,\"end\":183,\"uuid\":\"70633651-05bc-423a-be29-d1499e92b8d6\"}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"60a49521-60c5-40a0-9e04-5144035aa9a9\",\"sort\":544,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.41\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":855,\"uuid\":\"60a49521-60c5-40a0-9e04-5144035aa9a9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In this way, through the efforts of Indian scholars, the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":57}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":57,\"end\":71},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6cc9bb7a-c174-4b65-8e82-659ab02b45fc\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" came to be understood as one of the foundational scriptural authorities for the practice of both the Mahāyāna and Vajrayāna. Furthermore, since each commentator attempted to prove that the scripture aligns with his own philosophical position, it slowly became the interpretive battleground for different scholastic attempts to systematize the Indian Mahāyāna Buddhist logic of practice.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":71,\"end\":458},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"4aaa8ed5-f790-44e2-95ee-bf49b585780b\",\"label\":\"24\",\"uuid\":\"dfead7b2-5274-4453-975d-4a197e7d6f5b\",\"start\":458,\"end\":458,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Despite their different philosophical perspectives, the commentaries provide excellent access to the scripture’s meaning. Yet even when a commentary explains the esoteric meaning, the relevance and application of this meaning is not always perfectly clear in the words in the scripture itself. So serious scholastic study began to focus more on individual treatises than on the actual scriptures.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":458,\"end\":855}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8cbd3bc2-fa79-4f35-8f18-43aa4dccb633\",\"sort\":550,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.42\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":840,\"uuid\":\"8cbd3bc2-fa79-4f35-8f18-43aa4dccb633\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"From the eighth century onward, Indian scholastic study of the Perfection of Wisdom seems to have increasingly read the scriptures through the lens of one particular treatise, namely the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":187}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":187,\"end\":195},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3677d138-bebf-47fb-997a-8a7b16e5b490\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":195,\"end\":201}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":201,\"end\":209},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1fff13da-1b97-4b04-9f22-196baa4b2075\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" itself is a brief independent treatise that provides a versified outline of topics within the mother Prajñāpāramitā scriptures themselves.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":209,\"end\":348},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"9a6ab0ac-eeac-4205-8e92-718d323af0a7\",\"label\":\"25\",\"uuid\":\"095625c7-55ad-48b1-8da0-b9d6e5688b85\",\"start\":348,\"end\":348,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The outline has eight chapters, which include a total of seventy main topics and twelve hundred subtopics to be realized along the path. But the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":348,\"end\":494}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":494,\"end\":502},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"21499fbc-9534-411f-ab0b-8a013440c00a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" neither expands on these topics, nor explains how they are to be interpolated into the Mother Prajñāpāramitā scriptures themselves. Commentaries on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":502,\"end\":655}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":655,\"end\":663},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"836fbe97-271b-4f5c-acf3-1de7579dfce1\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" are required to show where exactly the individual \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":663,\"end\":714}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":714,\"end\":722},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0e8b3160-2c21-4d97-86b3-8028519942da\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" headings should be inserted into the scriptures and how those headings shed light on each stage of Mahāyāna practice.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":722,\"end\":840}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5479a35c-7498-451e-ba3d-0d9b93451334\",\"sort\":564,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.43\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1450,\"uuid\":\"5479a35c-7498-451e-ba3d-0d9b93451334\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Since the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":10}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":18},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"636e4e6c-79a1-476f-8c21-53bff7e8d40a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s outline of topics seems to be designed for the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":68}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Twenty-Five Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":68,\"end\":88},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2f752c4d-dac3-4d27-a9d6-5ef96a0b502b\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the first commentary on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":118}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":118,\"end\":126},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4c404961-d514-4243-bdc9-3caaeec6a7da\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" by Ārya Vimuktisena simply matched its seventy topics to that scripture. Among the twenty-one different Indian commentaries on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":126,\"end\":258}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":258,\"end\":266},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9c41ce38-b144-4f32-a8c1-1a222a5abb4b\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" still extant in Tibetan translations, only two commentaries matched its seventy topics to the much shorter \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":266,\"end\":374}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":374,\"end\":388},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"26d1d7f9-8d85-4297-8ae8-7b4585f16861\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". First, in the ninth century, Haribhadra’s \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":388,\"end\":432}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Light\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":432,\"end\":437},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"78d0f61b-ce9b-4012-8a7f-4200273869f0\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":437,\"end\":439}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ālokā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":439,\"end\":444},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c4816941-e55f-4e6c-a498-f8bbf3970093\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") did so from the philosophical perspective of the Madhyamaka school, and in the eleventh century, Ratnākaraśānti’s \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":444,\"end\":560}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Quintessence\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":560,\"end\":572},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5218e18c-dd76-4094-8ed3-f19350122300\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":572,\"end\":574}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sāratamā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":574,\"end\":582},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"86ba53eb-1a39-47d3-81a9-6317cca00d98\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") did so from the perspective of the Yogācāra school. In both these commentaries, the study of the Prajñāpāramitā is presented largely as a comparative theory of practice. That is to say, the commentaries show (a) how the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":582,\"end\":804}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":804,\"end\":818},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"df1b4e42-214e-4cfa-999e-754455e905e2\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" implicitly refers to the stages of the different paths of practice in the vehicle of bodhisattvas, and (b) how these compare to the stages of the different paths of practice in the vehicles of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":818,\"end\":1016}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"disciples\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1016,\"end\":1025},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"26e83d8b-3cde-40df-8a66-f26ecb8b6243\",\"uuid\":\"59bd065a-50ad-4f8b-aadb-87c3c8e97018\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1025,\"end\":1030}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"solitary realizers\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1030,\"end\":1048},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"91eb4850-6549-4ee5-ae57-ec33c68112f1\",\"uuid\":\"0ce02a79-bbf7-44dc-9daf-64b62ab7ef13\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The comparison presents the different theories of practice in the different vehicles, in detail, from multiple perspectives, at every stage of the path. This comparison seeks not just to prove the superiority of the Mahāyāna approach to practice, but also to clarify how it differs from other approaches to practice within the different vehicles‍—which might seem quite similar, but actually are not.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1048,\"end\":1450}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2abcf8e1-0c06-4e63-8bfa-b1020dc2a694\",\"sort\":590,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.44\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":570,\"uuid\":\"2abcf8e1-0c06-4e63-8bfa-b1020dc2a694\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Although the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":21},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3b25448e-c649-4542-90c7-8edd9c7e3d09\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s outline fits the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":41}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":41,\"end\":55},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"536992bc-98a2-4033-b044-2bc16d4ae0ff\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" to some degree, on occasions Haribhadra and Ratnākaraśānti themselves fail to connect one or another of the seventy topics to any passage at all in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":208}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":208,\"end\":222},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"eda24817-fc6d-4b56-b68f-7aa847e73a80\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Whether or not one regards this “fit” problem as stemming from an anachronistic attempt to read later doctrines and practices into the earlier \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":222,\"end\":367}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":367,\"end\":381},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"20351b9c-f385-462a-83ed-3570ad09948b\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", Haribhadra’s and Ratnākaraśānti’s commentaries still offer what is probably the best window into the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":381,\"end\":484}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":484,\"end\":498},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"fcde788b-0baa-4706-88bc-865811de26b4\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s early terminology and otherwise almost inaccessible esoteric meaning.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":498,\"end\":570}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c28263a8-41fc-48c0-a83a-1ca77f1b3507\",\"sort\":602,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.45\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":993,\"uuid\":\"c28263a8-41fc-48c0-a83a-1ca77f1b3507\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"So helpful was the guidance of these two commentators that when the seven (or eight, see above) different teams of Tibetan translators each translated or retranslated the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":171}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":171,\"end\":185},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f612a168-acc7-4445-9b29-274d35c6493c\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" into Tibetan between the eighth and sixteenth centuries, they all based their translations on the glosses and explanations that the two commentaries provided. Later, when the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":185,\"end\":361}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":361,\"end\":369},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"55d7b9bf-d2da-4803-a15c-3d57f9089eef\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" became the focus of Tibetan scholastic education in the different schools and lineages of Tibet, the Tibetans made direct reference to these same two commentaries in their own subcommentaries, sub-subcommentaries, and textbooks. In this way, the Tibetan tradition absorbed the Indian Prajñāpāramitā literature into its own works and continued to expand upon the topics. Over time, the Tibetans came to focus mainly on studying the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":369,\"end\":801}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":801,\"end\":809},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0c95d58c-ca86-4bc5-8168-8a611cc0e858\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" without making any reference to the scriptures themselves, since to achieve a serviceable understanding of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":809,\"end\":921}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":921,\"end\":929},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"24de2b43-4c9e-41f3-8e04-399a504810bb\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" alone is said to take years of dedicated, single-pointed study.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":929,\"end\":993},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"5a5db32b-4da0-4f32-bd22-e1633e7cc395\",\"label\":\"26\",\"uuid\":\"25c40077-e335-4b7a-959a-253f6981e383\",\"start\":993,\"end\":993,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7173504e-a2a7-4aec-b7eb-9f95129f29cf\",\"sort\":613,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.46\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":939,\"uuid\":\"7173504e-a2a7-4aec-b7eb-9f95129f29cf\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"From this focus on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":23}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":23,\"end\":31},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c2a1a145-2e7b-469b-b4ce-f1227ba0238c\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" came the notion that reading the treatise was the equivalent of reading the scriptures. This may be true in the sense that the seventy topics are indeed said to be the most relevant points made by the scriptures. However, it may lead to distortions of understanding in that (a) the scriptures themselves present the topics in a literary style and genre very different from those of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":31,\"end\":418}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":418,\"end\":426},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cc8cd710-a584-4ee2-8afc-899e1863156a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and aim to affect the reader in different ways; (b) there are many things in the scriptures not mentioned at all in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":426,\"end\":547}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":547,\"end\":555},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bdc2a68d-5da2-456e-9a11-5d0376a254c8\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; and (c) the function of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":555,\"end\":585}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":585,\"end\":593},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"da5cb6af-a0b6-454b-9e44-1d2f8d85ea0a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" itself is an intertextual one of illuminating the words of the scriptures, rather than of being understood on its own. Thus, anyone interested in learning more about the Prajñāpāramitā would do well to read the scriptures in conjunction with the commentarial tradition and to keep in mind that the Prajñāpāramitā scriptures have their own value.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":593,\"end\":939}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ed4e9bb4-d4c7-4732-ab3a-0767cb52687a\",\"sort\":623,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.47\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1272,\"uuid\":\"ed4e9bb4-d4c7-4732-ab3a-0767cb52687a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Another reason for reading the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":31}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":31,\"end\":45},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"64916e32-c7d7-4414-a261-06f6ffc374c0\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is that despite the widespread reverence for it, relatively few Buddhists outside the scholastic setting have any knowledge even of its contents, not to mention its meaning. In the Himalayas today, devoted Buddhists still occasionally perform or sponsor monastic recitations of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":328}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":328,\"end\":342},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d4863d04-c223-4dd2-95c3-2cf8e16bdeeb\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". But a far more common practice, across the modern Mahāyāna Buddhist world, is to chant aloud daily‍—or occasionally write out‍—the one-page \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":342,\"end\":484}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":484,\"end\":495},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1b4447fd-0166-4934-85b5-526831c5e9fc\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":495,\"end\":496},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"7362476a-667e-481f-adb8-17584536d5ce\",\"label\":\"27\",\"uuid\":\"790396a1-0589-45c4-8fa0-fd0bb1c30273\",\"start\":496,\"end\":496,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Since the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":496,\"end\":507}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Heart Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":507,\"end\":518},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f7da5bd2-5cde-4e3c-bd49-3aee090ed77b\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" focuses on the topic of emptiness and is held to be a condensed version of all Prajñāpāramitā scriptures, many modern Buddhists‍—and even Western Buddhist Studies scholars with limited exposure to traditional scholastic studies‍—have erroneously come to believe that “emptiness” is the central topic of all the Prajñāpāramitā scriptures, too. In fact, emptiness is barely mentioned by name in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":518,\"end\":916}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":916,\"end\":930},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c01fd1f5-0f22-4e74-95e6-39eb0cca71f4\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and is not even included in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":930,\"end\":963}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":963,\"end\":971},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e1eb5faa-1060-4ada-b3f0-ddeade4ecc8c\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s list of the seventy main topics or twelve hundred subtopics, which are considered so central and important to Tibetan Buddhist practice that some monastic universities focus solely on them for up to six years \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":971,\"end\":1183}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"before\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1183,\"end\":1189},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1183,\"end\":1189,\"uuid\":\"151b9952-04ce-4e17-8634-f57f6c6639ad\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"emphasis\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" turning to classical texts on philosophy, logic, and debates related to emptiness.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1189,\"end\":1272},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"e9aba872-d0d1-442e-b3cb-37175fb89a3c\",\"label\":\"28\",\"uuid\":\"e839eff5-1ac7-4ddf-9d8a-6d162006e2d9\",\"start\":1272,\"end\":1272,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5cb1f352-298b-49dc-8efb-e9d7708b9728\",\"sort\":641,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"uuid\":\"fc025b6c-fbef-4ac8-ad1a-c74d31204845\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Style and Themes\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2f91def8-f368-41a9-8f18-81a10bd5f35d\",\"sort\":643,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.48\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":601,\"uuid\":\"2f91def8-f368-41a9-8f18-81a10bd5f35d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Given the sūtra’s seminal role in the development of Mahāyāna Buddhism outlined above, modern readers eager to explore the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":123}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":123,\"end\":137},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f01e50cb-ba4e-468b-bf95-375ca4fde905\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" may be surprised to learn that it does not seek to convey the “wisdom” mentioned in its title in the manner that they might expect from works belonging to other well-known literary or religious genres‍—including the Pali Buddhist suttas. Instead, it is the way the very words of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":137,\"end\":421}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":421,\"end\":435},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1409b57e-14b6-41f2-bec7-25909516e1d5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" are crafted that is designed to provide, to those who revere, recite, and study them, a performative and provocative means for achieving complete, perfect awakening.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":435,\"end\":601}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"507ffe02-a2f3-49af-939f-0243c071f747\",\"sort\":649,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.49\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":650,\"uuid\":\"507ffe02-a2f3-49af-939f-0243c071f747\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Some of the scripture’s Mahāyāna themes‍—such as how a bodhisattva transcends \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":78}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"cyclic existence\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":78,\"end\":94},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"70c46af5-0c80-4d15-a018-cac10ce06459\",\"uuid\":\"4e2133bc-f556-41bf-ad6b-f4f9747d4ac0\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" through engendering a \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":94,\"end\":117}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mindset of awakening\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":117,\"end\":137},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"0762121b-91b4-401f-88bd-8ce6afdba30f\",\"uuid\":\"cd0e6690-e1e6-4d93-831e-88d6b95c88dc\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" “free of duality and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":137,\"end\":159}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"free from creating duality\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":159,\"end\":185},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"9fea1c3a-8171-4a64-b63b-3e1024aa180b\",\"uuid\":\"37816dda-3c83-4565-b997-844373386f54\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”‍—will certainly be familiar to many readers; these themes will be summarized chapter by chapter below. But the way that the scripture communicates these subjects may come as a surprise. That is to say, the meaning is often communicated only indirectly through the repartee of the dialogues, the negations of opposites, elusive implications, paradoxical statements, esoteric references to unspecified practices, play on words, and the use of heuristic etymologies.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":185,\"end\":650},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"5083d08e-6cee-4b21-83b1-ef909c73035f\",\"label\":\"29\",\"uuid\":\"ed72a88a-5b23-4e57-8337-a9ef32ebde7f\",\"start\":650,\"end\":650,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b850a9ba-6a92-45be-bac5-506cbb76cd75\",\"sort\":658,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.50\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":345,\"uuid\":\"b850a9ba-6a92-45be-bac5-506cbb76cd75\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Furthermore, the reason for which this literature is primarily studied in the Indian and Tibetan scholastic traditions is the understanding it brings not so much of the emptiness with which the Prajñāpāramitā is often associated, but rather of the framework it sets out for the “path,” the implicit meaning behind the texts’ explicit statements.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":345}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e2289731-68eb-401e-b0e0-489b797a9e1d\",\"sort\":659,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":45,\"uuid\":\"ce27e6bb-6372-4cae-b3dc-fb9f3f0b8700\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Modern-Day Translations of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":31}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":31,\"end\":45},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"34c55566-ab65-483f-a383-69dc87b88104\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bccf9e49-b675-4e45-a8d0-39c69b10961c\",\"sort\":662,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.51\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":758,\"uuid\":\"bccf9e49-b675-4e45-a8d0-39c69b10961c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The few translations of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":28}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":42},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"eca995d6-f7ad-4524-8bdf-28562ee88ab5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" into modern languages that have been made are mostly incomplete and not readily available. The first and most complete was a French translation made by Eugène Burnouf between 1837 and 1839 from two of the manuscripts sent from Nepal by B. H. Hodgson. Burnouf lamented that he had been unable to consult any commentarial works, but nevertheless produced a painstaking and remarkable translation, comparing his manuscripts with others of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":483}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Twenty-Five Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":483,\"end\":503},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4575d624-db1c-4649-a8a7-3a2033fd2d15\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":503,\"end\":508}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Hundred Thousand-Line\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":508,\"end\":529},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"de309620-2d06-471b-84bc-1fcc6043544d\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" sūtras and with the Tibetan text. Of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":529,\"end\":571}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":571,\"end\":585},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"685a3383-1c9c-4c28-a590-39256eb0cfd5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s thirty-two chapters, he completed the first twenty-seven and most of the twenty-eighth, but apart from a few extracts his translation remained unpublished until recently.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":585,\"end\":758},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"a59196c6-4a4b-41db-9e90-3aeb38d23e7e\",\"label\":\"30\",\"uuid\":\"6e51d43b-01eb-4f2a-9c5a-dce7419fa8c5\",\"start\":758,\"end\":758,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c338cdd6-b345-4a95-9e2c-773dc3b52c16\",\"sort\":673,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.52\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":306,\"uuid\":\"c338cdd6-b345-4a95-9e2c-773dc3b52c16\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eleven chapters were translated into German by Max Walleser in 1914, and a number of single chapters or other short excerpts in French and German were published in the first half of the twentieth century. A complete translation of the Sanskrit into Japanese by Kajiyama and Teruyoshi was published in 1974.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":306}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"499db24c-a0bd-440a-b531-8fdf7a64ae1f\",\"sort\":675,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.53\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":548,\"uuid\":\"499db24c-a0bd-440a-b531-8fdf7a64ae1f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Meanwhile, in 1958, the great pioneer of Prajñāpāramitā studies in English, Edward Conze, first published his influential and widely read translation of the text. Although it is complete in the sense that it covers all thirty-two chapters, Conze chose to omit or paraphrase much of the repetitive detail that is characteristic of the original, but that he considered would be an impediment to modern readers. As we shall discuss further below, in this respect, valuable though it has been, his translation is significantly less than a complete one.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":548}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6b99ab31-9ab6-4357-81eb-3a935c482311\",\"sort\":676,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"f03f28f0-f69e-4d94-b8bb-459a825cfa05\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Notes on This Translation of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":33}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"98e553b7-066c-4b30-aef1-cc57faeb4d88\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"65ed5d5e-2ca3-45b6-940c-4bf08ec0597c\",\"sort\":678,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":4,\"start\":0,\"end\":22,\"uuid\":\"f886e040-30bb-4f33-b5e5-3a966fcf6241\",\"class\":\"section-title\",\"hasLeadingSpace\":true,\"leadingSpaceUuid\":\"2affae65-fe05-41e1-9867-905bf9ff5697\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sources and Approaches\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"377999e9-0d6e-4e99-994b-747741a7e056\",\"sort\":680,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.54\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":659,\"uuid\":\"377999e9-0d6e-4e99-994b-747741a7e056\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Given the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":10}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":24},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"198342ef-9ff6-4f58-af0b-232bd6aab3c1\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s significance, it is perhaps surprising that this is the first complete English translation.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":24,\"end\":118},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"f96106b3-2f7f-40b7-b977-8e5e59b26309\",\"label\":\"31\",\"uuid\":\"a6f62bfc-1068-43a6-b418-a5bf917244a2\",\"start\":118,\"end\":118,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" It is based primarily on the Sanskrit text (edited by Mitra in 1888 and reproduced by Vaidya and Wogihara),\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":118,\"end\":226},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"cf6bc1a7-dbaa-4682-9c6e-eec81128d7e7\",\"label\":\"32\",\"uuid\":\"c8972618-5273-4028-bab5-95a2d406028a\",\"start\":226,\"end\":226,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and only secondarily on the Tibetan version in the Degé Kangyur. We have nevertheless consistently consulted the Tibetan and have recorded in the footnotes all substantial inconsistencies between the Sanskrit and Tibetan, mentioning which of the two readings was translated and why it was followed. Our reasons for relying more on the extant Sanskrit than on the Tibetan stem from considerations of history, meaning, and usefulness.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":226,\"end\":659}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"407e2776-4b63-4dd3-890c-f9e14729284f\",\"sort\":688,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.55\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":324,\"uuid\":\"407e2776-4b63-4dd3-890c-f9e14729284f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"From the historical perspective, Sanskrit is of course closer to the original Indic language in which the text was written. Fortunately, too, the Tibetan translation matches Mitra’s edition much more closely than is the case for Tibetan translations of some other canonical texts compared to their extant Sanskrit parallels.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":324}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0bc37e1d-9c03-44a3-b431-8ad203181400\",\"sort\":690,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.56\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":406,\"uuid\":\"0bc37e1d-9c03-44a3-b431-8ad203181400\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Second, translating the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":24,\"end\":38},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c287da01-c1c2-49a7-a1de-6d10f83b155e\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" from the Sanskrit has also helped produce a more meaningful translation, because the Sanskrit terminology is more transparent in its etymology and semantic range. The Tibetan translation sometimes limits or alters the sense of original terms, inadvertently obfuscates relationships between them, and renders opaque or invisible the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":371}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":371,\"end\":385},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7ff078cc-53c9-4681-be2a-f0e745c5aa72\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s Sanskrit wordplay.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":385,\"end\":406}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"40ee6dd5-f04a-44d8-bb2d-ed5dd1590845\",\"sort\":696,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.57\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":815,\"uuid\":\"40ee6dd5-f04a-44d8-bb2d-ed5dd1590845\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Third, we hope that having a translation of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":48}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":48,\"end\":62},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"627cb1b2-47be-45cf-ad44-3bf55cd80c1b\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" made primarily from the Sanskrit will make it easier to study the text through English translations of the two Sanskrit commentaries by Haribhadra and Ratnākaraśānti. Without reference to the Sanskrit text, English translations of the Sanskrit commentaries would make little sense, because what they both clarify is the terminological and syntactic ambiguities of the sūtra’s original Sanskrit text, and not any ambiguities introduced by the choices made in the Tibetan translation. The extant Tibetan translation of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":62,\"end\":584}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":584,\"end\":598},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4b0fa45d-0bdf-451c-8f9a-a0cdc2bb2aa1\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" did indeed follow Ratnākaraśānti’s and Haribhadra’s commentaries on many points, but a translation of the Sanskrit still provides a better starting point than the Tibetan for understanding the commentarial tradition.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":598,\"end\":815},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"cb24586c-b357-41ca-9ee4-e64c54c0fa86\",\"label\":\"33\",\"uuid\":\"858965be-26b1-43cb-9365-16a6a89e6d3f\",\"start\":815,\"end\":815,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c43691d8-70d1-44af-bcc0-a7e589ece232\",\"sort\":703,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.58\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":701,\"uuid\":\"c43691d8-70d1-44af-bcc0-a7e589ece232\",\"hasLeadingSpace\":true,\"leadingSpaceUuid\":\"ec4a9d47-7925-4627-a044-850bbb5c8c40\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The primary concern in this English translation of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":69},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5eddb1ae-e2e9-400c-b1fe-161cc5f1c6f5\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" has been to create a text that can serve as a basis for the traditional study that it deserves, while still being accessible to those who wish, as Paul Harrison puts it, “to read the English as English and make some sense of it.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":69,\"end\":299},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"081759ca-f904-4d63-abd8-1eb6aa98bceb\",\"label\":\"34\",\"uuid\":\"7523c5c5-b0df-4b89-b664-293775344e67\",\"start\":299,\"end\":299,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" For Sanskrit prose, the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":299,\"end\":324}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":324,\"end\":338},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9156f402-b2ef-4722-94e8-5b09110ca454\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is stylistically clunky and repetitive at the sentence level. But to facilitate in-depth study with Haribhadra and Ratnākaraśānti’s commentaries, which take the text sentence by sentence, the translation must match the Sanskrit and Tibetan versions sentence by sentence too, even if this has led to a style that could also be considered clunky for English prose.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":338,\"end\":701}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cdafaa22-4a23-4a02-b115-c195d24ae860\",\"sort\":711,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.59\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":489,\"uuid\":\"cdafaa22-4a23-4a02-b115-c195d24ae860\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"A secondary concern has been to use consistent Buddhist terminology, rather than different translations of the same words, to bring out the range of meanings or to produce more elegant prose. The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":196}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":196,\"end\":210},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9079958f-ce1a-470f-9c00-1cb32dd7d70b\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" makes use of many different rhetorical devices that require such consistency‍—meaningful plays on words, paradoxical statements, recoding of similar terms to challenge reader assumptions, and so on‍—all of which play a role in conveying the scripture’s tone and ultimate intent.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":210,\"end\":489}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"35136a00-d6fb-4ebc-ba49-e6ff58995ced\",\"sort\":715,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.60\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":496,\"uuid\":\"35136a00-d6fb-4ebc-ba49-e6ff58995ced\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":18},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6a84e969-df97-4c2e-babf-bf4638be6b40\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s repetitive style, too, has been preserved. Even if repetition is less a major feature of this text than it is of the longer sūtras, it is still very evident. Repetition was clearly used for its effect on reciters and their audience, or individual readers. For instance, some chapters include multiple repetitions of long passages with only one word or phrase change. Where repetition is either the point itself or central to that point, it would be a mistake to eliminate it.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":496}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"800c28a9-0067-4826-ae4b-3cad766a4989\",\"sort\":719,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.61\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":346,\"uuid\":\"800c28a9-0067-4826-ae4b-3cad766a4989\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Edward Conze, in his 1958 rendering of the text in English, chose to paraphrase rather than fully translate it, with the idea that this would make it available to a wider readership. The justification he used is worth analyzing, at least to highlight the different stylistic approach of this present translation. In his own preface, Conze states:\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":346}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f26d4f33-a351-42ba-8a88-5dc1421173e3\",\"sort\":721,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.62\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"blockquote\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":505,\"uuid\":\"e02705c0-000d-410e-a271-8f6b5adb9e68\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":505,\"uuid\":\"e02705c0-000d-410e-a271-8f6b5adb9e68\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"“The Sūtra itself was meant to be memorized, the translation is meant to be read. Lengthy repetitions, stereotyped phrases, and the piling up of synonyms were of great assistance to memory, but they irritate and distract the modern reader, and obscure from him the meaning of the text.…The reproduction of the literary conventions and of the stylistic peculiarities of Buddhist Sanskrit diction was not one of my aims. It would be of little, or no, value to scholars, and it bewilders the general reader.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":505},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"b0c42265-694d-42dd-b177-0c8aeee759ea\",\"label\":\"35\",\"uuid\":\"bbc38a01-9ca9-4853-b911-3f48d6f756c4\",\"start\":505,\"end\":505,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1def8a52-6d5b-4a6e-ad07-bf85d6605436\",\"sort\":724,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.63\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":988,\"uuid\":\"1def8a52-6d5b-4a6e-ad07-bf85d6605436\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here, Conze states several things that deserve closer scrutiny. First, he assumes that “the Sūtra was meant to be memorized, the translation is meant to be read.” Yet throughout its history, it seems quite likely that the scripture itself has been read far more than it has been memorized. Second, he assumes that “lengthy repetitions, stereotyped phrases, and the piling up of synonyms” obscure the meaning of the text. Yet the scripture’s overall meaning is not merely contained in certain individual words. It is also conveyed through those very stylistic devices, repetitions, and “piled-up” synonyms. What is valuable in this book, Conze assumes with his modern bias, cannot be what comes from the verbal performance of chanting it aloud. Finally, when Conze eliminates or paraphrases repetitions that the commentators find meaningful but he himself finds meaningless, he neglects the needs of those who might wish to read the translation along with the two main Indian commentaries.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":988}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"70f4bd93-9e1a-4504-ae96-f8c941aae8ae\",\"sort\":726,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.64\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":682,\"uuid\":\"70f4bd93-9e1a-4504-ae96-f8c941aae8ae\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Since no one would feel equipped to draw firm conclusions about the scripture without the full text or a traditional commentary on its meaning, a new English translation of both the scripture and its commentaries should help correct the historical, philosophical, and religious misunderstandings that have inadvertently arisen from Conze’s translation style and comments about the scripture. To illustrate this point simply, it may be helpful to give a brief example where Conze’s assumptions and his paraphrase obfuscate both the literal meaning and the traditional interpretation of even just a single passage. At the conclusion of a meaningful passage, Conze’s translation reads:\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":682}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"13187b5e-a513-41b3-aedf-d5253725bf3c\",\"sort\":728,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.65\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"blockquote\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":147,\"uuid\":\"b3c7a824-6788-4b02-b125-8b3d62b8e481\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":147,\"uuid\":\"b3c7a824-6788-4b02-b125-8b3d62b8e481\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"“A Bodhisattva who does not become afraid when this deep and perfect wisdom is being taught should be recognized as not lacking in perfect wisdom.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":147},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"ca612793-6e1d-4e22-b82f-4189ec5618f0\",\"label\":\"36\",\"uuid\":\"34ea9513-ee03-4cf5-9cfa-889eb7bc6e13\",\"start\":147,\"end\":147,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"67eca99e-46ac-4fd1-8bf1-da0484d13104\",\"sort\":731,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.66\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":102,\"uuid\":\"67eca99e-46ac-4fd1-8bf1-da0484d13104\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Consider now how much more meaning might be found in a literal translation that would read as follows:\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":102}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"606eff9b-3bfe-47f9-a009-44ab5c0f899d\",\"sort\":733,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.67\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"blockquote\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":511,\"uuid\":\"cc119e1c-d647-4da7-92db-64c30f3536f7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":511,\"uuid\":\"cc119e1c-d647-4da7-92db-64c30f3536f7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"“O \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":3}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Blessed One\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":3,\"end\":14},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7bf45dd5-3e8d-4495-bc65-ecf0a51d3597\",\"uuid\":\"65bd7518-d3d4-4a23-be26-46b39c00e37a\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", when this profound perfection of wisdom is being discussed, taught, and expounded in this way, if a bodhisattva \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":14,\"end\":128}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"great being\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":128,\"end\":139},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"be37efde-2f63-40d0-8e8e-e93b3b3a581e\",\"uuid\":\"f1f86984-ed46-4392-8d93-8ab2cc832181\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":139,\"end\":142}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mindset\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":142,\"end\":149},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"ad0b5c96-5b65-496d-bb1c-0e4fa6ad3bf4\",\"uuid\":\"04a99195-f385-4455-b2bf-d28b5e9ed4d4\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" does not become deflated, depressed, dejected, or \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":149,\"end\":200}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sunk in despondency\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":200,\"end\":219},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"12850e8f-bca6-487d-b286-8a071e49491f\",\"uuid\":\"0127ee3e-27de-4a24-bd81-42f024bde291\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and his or her \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":219,\"end\":236}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mental attitude\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":236,\"end\":251},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"71984920-52bd-485c-9f8f-1b4d1cb73d33\",\"uuid\":\"0dfaba3c-9428-43e4-a929-9a353a61ae08\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" does not become discouraged, shattered, frightened, terrified, or \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":251,\"end\":318}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"stricken with terror\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":318,\"end\":338},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2683095c-4a8b-4b93-a0f5-cb42d263f8e2\",\"uuid\":\"27ba23f2-471a-4c8d-8c8a-32298dad5227\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", then that bodhisattva \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":338,\"end\":362}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"great being\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":362,\"end\":373},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"be37efde-2f63-40d0-8e8e-e93b3b3a581e\",\"uuid\":\"d2d817ea-70dc-47bc-96a1-cff1bb41a563\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":373,\"end\":374}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"has firm conviction\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":374,\"end\":393},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"609d5abe-76ed-41e8-a714-30ff92acba34\",\"uuid\":\"bd39cfc1-cc38-4dfa-9dbf-becc723ba722\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" with an altruistic disposition. Hence, one should recognize him or her to be \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":393,\"end\":471}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"never lacking\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":471,\"end\":484},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"26e77994-e832-43f0-898f-17c9988c9ae9\",\"uuid\":\"9ae9dec1-76c6-450c-9e1a-3957b6a97e84\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" the perfection of wisdom.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":484,\"end\":511},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"8827af62-4386-4aae-9e2f-6817b162c363\",\"label\":\"37\",\"uuid\":\"c91030ce-27b8-4ab1-b133-36dd433456be\",\"start\":511,\"end\":511,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"48d2347e-d9cb-4b12-83dc-667ab0040247\",\"sort\":754,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.68\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":343,\"uuid\":\"48d2347e-d9cb-4b12-83dc-667ab0040247\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"It is easy to see that Conze’s paraphrases were not merely eliminating words that “irritate and distract the modern reader, and obscure from him the meaning of the text.” Conze’s paraphrase is also missing many words that Ratnākaraśānti’s commentary refers to. For instance, consider Ratnākaraśānti’s comments on the above literal translation:\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":343}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5f780414-9feb-463a-b26a-4b11d2cdaa05\",\"sort\":756,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.69\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"blockquote\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1153,\"uuid\":\"84ea3a15-4e3e-42be-91a2-f0e606d36855\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1153,\"uuid\":\"84ea3a15-4e3e-42be-91a2-f0e606d36855\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"“These sentences (in the above passage) accord with the way that the meditative object and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":91}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"meditative perspective\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":91,\"end\":113},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7bea5dcd-33ce-40af-aca6-9c1243d8e867\",\"uuid\":\"988a2ffe-9dc4-47dd-beb6-b8598f46a38f\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" are explained. Here, the word ‘profound’ means difficult to understand. This ‘perfection of wisdom’ refers to [a bodhisattva’s knowing on the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":113,\"end\":256}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"path of preliminary practice\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":256,\"end\":284},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"5b884783-353d-4b51-9f6e-5b8ab29c823b\",\"uuid\":\"2c6553cb-2918-4f98-afc8-def05414cbcc\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"] in the intermediate and advanced stages of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":284,\"end\":329}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"warming up\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":329,\"end\":339},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"23e021ed-df6a-4f14-a93a-9727a988896c\",\"uuid\":\"d10b521a-0a25-4069-86d1-3b6b81b61bfb\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". First, ‘discussed’ concerns the words; then, ‘taught’ and ‘expounded’ concern the meaning. By understanding that meaning (in practice), the bodhisattva develops tranquility (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":339,\"end\":515}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"śamatha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":515,\"end\":522},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":515,\"end\":522,\"uuid\":\"d8992412-0e85-4e4b-8383-b3d236de09fc\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":522,\"end\":524}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"zhi gnas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":524,\"end\":532},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":524,\"end\":532,\"uuid\":\"c5f60004-bc27-435e-9825-a7575a684190\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). The [nine] words beginning with ‘does not become deflated’ and so on [correspond to nine emotional difficulties that are progressively overcome through the nine stages of meditation practice aimed at tranquility,] as explained previously. The ‘altruistic disposition’ refers to a bodhisattva’s motivation [for practice], which indicates single-pointed determination [to awaken through practice]. ‘\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":532,\"end\":932}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Firm conviction\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":932,\"end\":947},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"14d822fc-e184-4e5e-affd-9e3b08918c08\",\"uuid\":\"ad59cf75-536d-4a02-8b17-5df55bbbb0cf\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’ is generated by force of the tranquility meditation and the insight meditation. The phrase ‘never separate’ means that, through this [meditation], a bodhisattva’s perfection of wisdom will only increase.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":947,\"end\":1153},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"744bbe4e-92d0-4436-896a-ee1cbffaebcd\",\"label\":\"38\",\"uuid\":\"05873ec0-dd3d-45d1-bdf0-31b6ddedcaa9\",\"start\":1153,\"end\":1153,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"79c7e5cd-18df-4c56-ac43-75a2528bb0b7\",\"sort\":771,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.70\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":860,\"uuid\":\"79c7e5cd-18df-4c56-ac43-75a2528bb0b7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The words Conze omits in his paraphrase are thus ones that the commentarial tradition holds to be meaningful. Omitting them forecloses the possibility that in English translation Ratnākaraśānti’s commentary could clarify the scripture’s esoteric meaning according to the received tradition. Where Ratnākaraśānti comments on the nine experiences (i.e., “deflated,” “depressed,” and so on, up to “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":395}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"stricken with terror\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":395,\"end\":415},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2683095c-4a8b-4b93-a0f5-cb42d263f8e2\",\"uuid\":\"2e54a011-9186-4be2-9126-1248794b9332\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”), Conze saw nothing but a “repetition” or “piling up of synonyms,” and abbreviated them all into the single word “afraid.” Yet according to Ratnākaraśānti these nine words correspond to nine emotional difficulties progressively overcome through the nine stages of meditation practice. Furthermore, Ratnākaraśānti situates the particular degree of tranquility and insight achieved here with a specific stage and level of the bodhisattva’s path.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":415,\"end\":860},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"c6b12135-a5f5-4fad-be9f-a42a235121bd\",\"label\":\"39\",\"uuid\":\"ec4c0516-1336-4489-b267-4ab4be6ffe2f\",\"start\":860,\"end\":860,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"82b72150-4d68-4306-af3a-bca73f652b14\",\"sort\":776,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.71\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":649,\"uuid\":\"82b72150-4d68-4306-af3a-bca73f652b14\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This is just one example of how Conze’s mixture of translation and paraphrase, pioneering though it was, distorts the meaning to be gleaned from certain esoteric passages, misrepresents the scripture’s use of language, and cannot be read alongside Ratnākaraśānti’s commentary. Among many other such instances, his rendering of chapter 5 omits the multiple repetitions of very long refrains, completely altering the nature of the chapter and its performative effect on a reader.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":477},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"f317de23-d0fa-47bb-a25c-d78ca4b7e3ed\",\"label\":\"40\",\"uuid\":\"3aa9d2c7-4759-41a7-9378-5915724c06bf\",\"start\":477,\"end\":477,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Needless to say, general readers, Buddhist practitioners, and scholars who unwittingly rely on Conze’s paraphrases‍—as though they are full translations‍—are being misled.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":477,\"end\":649}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f76ba1fb-593a-4225-a5d6-e5d21b368560\",\"sort\":780,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.72\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":948,\"uuid\":\"f76ba1fb-593a-4225-a5d6-e5d21b368560\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stylistically, the present new, complete English translation may not match the tastes of modern readers seeking concision. On the contrary, it preserves all sentence-level repetitions, piling up of synonyms, stock phrases, and so on, so that the traditional commentaries can easily be linked to it in the future, and so that an appreciation of the tradition can inform conclusions about the scripture itself. However, it makes no attempt to translate one word with only one word or to preserve syntactical relations between words. Many long sentences have been cut into shorter ones, adding words without brackets wherever necessary for clarity. The stylistic repetitions of words within a particular sentence have been eliminated only when it would make the English text too clumsy or difficult to understand. Thus, all language has been translated in a simple, straightforward way with a few key notes to make the scripture relatively accessible.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":948}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"41dd9c07-7d37-4656-b127-48207600d2b9\",\"sort\":781,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":4,\"start\":0,\"end\":41,\"uuid\":\"ae224d74-7ab9-4ae6-96e8-b88136b9f492\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Selections from the Commentaries as Notes\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"80b7b696-3f6e-4e2a-b94d-64d783f4b7e1\",\"sort\":783,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.73\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":879,\"uuid\":\"80b7b696-3f6e-4e2a-b94d-64d783f4b7e1\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":18},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b8f58509-4290-4a23-b86c-4d69fadcbf8f\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" can be fruitfully read even with less than a full understanding of its content. The scripture itself often states that simply by reading it the faithful will gain inconceivable merit. To read the scripture alone‍—without the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":244}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":244,\"end\":252},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e7d2e077-ce12-4302-b0a1-16d073bb3179\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s table of contents or the explanations of the commentaries‍—may thus offer readers much to explore. But for those with the time and interest it can be explored far more deeply by reading it with the aid of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":252,\"end\":464}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":464,\"end\":472},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b78eb9ab-e138-4e8d-ac71-a0ac194945cc\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and its explanatory commentaries. Complete translations of the commentaries are not yet available, but to provide some help for difficult passages, arcane metaphors, esoteric passages, and ambiguous words, we have provisionally included in the notes some translations of selected key comments from Haribhadra’s \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":472,\"end\":784}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Light\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":784,\"end\":789},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8ce86420-e27b-48ad-b49a-d8d99ec85f94\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (abbreviated “Hari”) and Ratnākaraśānti’s \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":789,\"end\":832}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Quintessence\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":832,\"end\":844},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"632375b0-3112-450c-a2f9-347a6ef75e03\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (abbreviated “Ratnākara” or “RK”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":844,\"end\":879}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"42103713-49c2-4db2-923a-3c90a118a21d\",\"sort\":795,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.74\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":286,\"uuid\":\"42103713-49c2-4db2-923a-3c90a118a21d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"To get the most use out of these notes and not feel overwhelmed by the commentarial detail, readers would do well to understand what purposes the commentator’s comments aim to serve, the types of comments that have been selected for inclusion, and how the comments have been translated.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":286}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7ff27fce-b3aa-4db5-94f6-c0d014c03e5c\",\"sort\":797,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.75\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":87,\"uuid\":\"c5bae77b-6717-4425-81db-76d35ce85536\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Haribhadra’s and Ratnākaraśānti’s commentaries generally aim to provide five services: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":87}}]},{\"type\":\"bulletList\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":484,\"uuid\":\"fa39be29-122e-4f93-9289-16710c671ba0\",\"spacing\":\"horizontal\",\"itemStyle\":\"numbers\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"to clarify ambiguous Sanskrit word divisions (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":133}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"padaccheda\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":133,\"end\":143},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":133,\"end\":143,\"uuid\":\"96184ff0-e791-4fe8-8596-f52de8678dbe\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"); \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":143,\"end\":146}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":146,\"uuid\":\"0c1c9ad1-f7f0-4f09-93df-d664ecd6c17c\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":146,\"uuid\":\"0c1c9ad1-f7f0-4f09-93df-d664ecd6c17c\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"to paraphrase the meaning of ambiguous words and syntactical relations (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":146,\"end\":218}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"padārthokti\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":218,\"end\":229},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":218,\"end\":229,\"uuid\":\"4b36ce3b-06b2-4c04-b03d-d658e967758b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"); \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":229,\"end\":232}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":146,\"end\":232,\"uuid\":\"aee1c788-f38b-4c9d-9067-3f78a8874d46\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":146,\"end\":232,\"uuid\":\"aee1c788-f38b-4c9d-9067-3f78a8874d46\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"to present etymological and grammatical analysis (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":232,\"end\":282}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vigraha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":282,\"end\":289},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":282,\"end\":289,\"uuid\":\"e37dbb94-7aeb-4f49-a734-f9ba544cdacc\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") of ambiguous Sanskrit terms; \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":289,\"end\":320}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":232,\"end\":320,\"uuid\":\"ebab09dc-a631-452f-b9dd-38cbd7088ada\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":232,\"end\":320,\"uuid\":\"ebab09dc-a631-452f-b9dd-38cbd7088ada\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"to interpret the meaning of ambiguous sentences (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":320,\"end\":369}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vākyayojanā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":369,\"end\":380},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":369,\"end\":380,\"uuid\":\"5473cebc-e2dc-465a-985e-6d671371c9e1\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"); and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":380,\"end\":387}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":320,\"end\":387,\"uuid\":\"0eed9775-08f7-4d96-b86d-cd6adbced8ce\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":320,\"end\":387,\"uuid\":\"0eed9775-08f7-4d96-b86d-cd6adbced8ce\"}},{\"type\":\"listItem\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"to address possible confusion or doubts about the intended meaning of the text (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":387,\"end\":467}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ākṣepasamādhāna\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":467,\"end\":482},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":467,\"end\":482,\"uuid\":\"c044e165-279a-47d1-9147-2eb6ff59379c\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":482,\"end\":484}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":387,\"end\":484,\"uuid\":\"6a056f08-0d68-4de7-be4e-7440c0235e18\"}}],\"attrs\":{\"start\":387,\"end\":484,\"uuid\":\"6a056f08-0d68-4de7-be4e-7440c0235e18\"}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c3004eba-6630-44b0-a1bf-559f1de3edef\",\"sort\":818,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.76\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":286,\"uuid\":\"c3004eba-6630-44b0-a1bf-559f1de3edef\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The first four mostly concern issues in the Sanskrit that the English translation already accounts for. Some of these comments contain tidbits that would be interesting to the average English reader but are submerged in points that only a Sanskrit reader would understand or care about.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":286}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2fe6c279-0c82-4fcb-bef3-b90722d3b876\",\"sort\":820,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.77\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":1380,\"uuid\":\"2fe6c279-0c82-4fcb-bef3-b90722d3b876\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The fifth service concerns the logic and meaning behind the theory and practice implied in the text. To this end, Haribhadra’s and Ratnākaraśānti’s commentaries are centered on demonstrating, section by section, the correlations between the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":241}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Eight Thousand\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":241,\"end\":255},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6ed285e2-3a51-433c-ae99-173ac310350a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":255,\"end\":264}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ornament\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":264,\"end\":272},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2e473519-56ff-4529-a7d5-d80965839299\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and they seek to provide enough philosophical, religious, and historical context so that an uninformed reader can understand the meaning of both texts. But comments of this type can be long and written in a style that requires additional explanation, so it is not always easy to extract the most relevant parts to include in a note. The notes to this translation therefore include no more than a minuscule portion of all the material held by Indo-Tibetan tradition as the theoretical underpinning of the text.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":272,\"end\":783},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"aa5e5a0b-23ab-45fa-bfa4-522f4b9aa3cc\",\"label\":\"41\",\"uuid\":\"169a364b-5ae7-4021-b613-bab1fdfb1016\",\"start\":783,\"end\":783,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Many of the comments that are included require, at least, a working knowledge of the stages of the five Mahāyāna paths that would normally be explained orally by a teacher. In selecting comments for the notes, our main aim was to provide Haribhadra’s or Ratnākaraśānti’s briefer comments where the scripture is difficult to understand on its own. The notes thus focus on the most easily extractable comments whose purposes fall under the second, fourth, and fifth categories listed above. The selection process was inevitably idiosyncratic, but was influenced by several further limiting factors.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":783,\"end\":1380}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b6a09801-2e7d-4418-93bb-e58a514eca85\",\"sort\":828,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.78\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":252,\"uuid\":\"b6a09801-2e7d-4418-93bb-e58a514eca85\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"First, comments that might be relevant to the interests of readers of any of several possible kinds‍—Buddhists, non-Buddhists, or academics of various disciplines‍—were included. In this regard, some footnotes might be interesting only to some readers.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":252}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"341bf0ad-ad81-4ed5-a295-b56931586a70\",\"sort\":832,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.79\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":624,\"uuid\":\"341bf0ad-ad81-4ed5-a295-b56931586a70\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Second, wherever a choice was necessary for brevity or clarity, Ratnākaraśānti’s comments, which have never been translated before, took precedence over Haribhadra’s comments, because an English translation of Haribhadra’s commentary already exists and can be independently consulted.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":284},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"8fd64f49-7f76-4b30-a5a1-aadb361ba06f\",\"label\":\"42\",\"uuid\":\"e84c1536-0052-4dfd-be49-593dc2b5b542\",\"start\":284,\"end\":284,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" But when Ratnākaraśānti’s comments are extant only in Tibetan translation rather than in Sanskrit,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":284,\"end\":383},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"5fcaf946-89f6-4aee-9f77-761b7a1940f4\",\"label\":\"43\",\"uuid\":\"d88c7483-a61c-4b44-ad4f-52caedc804d6\",\"start\":383,\"end\":383,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Haribhadra’s commentary is often provided, since the Tibetan translation of Ratnākaraśānti’s commentary systematically excludes information concerning Sanskrit grammar and etymologies that are helpful for understanding his overall comments.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":383,\"end\":624}}]}]}],\"body\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"28e1ad67-1dc3-4a87-9329-33645b98f493\",\"sort\":10000,\"type\":\"translationHeader\",\"label\":null,\"toh\":\"toh12\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":15,\"uuid\":\"94c0a02f-7dbe-451f-bc47-ba1e4b25596e\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Translation\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":15}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"93aaa1ed-7164-47a9-825c-f976abd47140\",\"sort\":10002,\"type\":\"translation\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{\"toh12\":{\"folioUuid\":\"4f16530d-04d6-43b9-84e4-b2fe9a909f2f\",\"toh\":\"toh12\",\"tibetan\":\"༄༅༅། །རྒྱ་གར་སྐད་དུ། ཨཱརྱ་ཨཥྚ་སཱ་ཧ་སྲི་ཀཱ་པྲཛྙཱ་པཱ་ར་མི་ཏཱ། བོད་སྐད་དུ། འཕགས་པ་ཤེས་རབ་ཀྱི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་ཕྱིན་པ་བརྒྱད་སྟོང་པ། བམ་པོ་དང་པོ། \",\"folioNumber\":1,\"volumeNumber\":33}}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":10,\"uuid\":\"825f593e-d02e-49a5-bf23-bfdeb3e3a676\",\"level\":2,\"class\":\"body-title-honorific\",\"hasLeadingSpace\":true,\"leadingSpaceUuid\":\"a56a090f-e96c-41bd-9466-7ec33d7f28b4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Noble \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":10}}]},{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":54,\"uuid\":\"676276d9-bc82-4481-8f67-657a24c9a8c7\",\"level\":2,\"class\":\"body-title-main\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Perfection of Wisdom in Eight Thousand Lines\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":54}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"473a1d26-1504-4ded-b63b-a021ae517be2\",\"sort\":10006,\"type\":\"translationHeader\",\"label\":\"1.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":57,\"uuid\":\"70ebae48-8037-491b-be36-b17e7d1c7012\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Chapter 1: Going About Life in the Knowing of All Aspects\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":57},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"addcf1e1-3aa5-4b9b-9461-0d8db8ce3835\",\"label\":\"64\",\"uuid\":\"0d84f89b-b03c-4b3b-b586-047e1d8bb445\",\"start\":57,\"end\":57,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null},{\"endNote\":\"6268941f-41a7-4f3c-9b6a-b80740f30837\",\"label\":\"65\",\"uuid\":\"025747d7-049a-4320-aff8-99bc75a7c4e9\",\"start\":57,\"end\":57,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ebda8847-d437-4b14-8ca1-981527180324\",\"sort\":10012,\"type\":\"translation\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"alignments\":{\"toh12\":{\"folioUuid\":\"4f16530d-04d6-43b9-84e4-b2fe9a909f2f\",\"toh\":\"toh12\",\"tibetan\":\"སངས་རྒྱས་དང་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་\\nདཔའ་དང་འཕགས་པ་ཉན་ཐོས་དང་རང་སངས་རྒྱས་ཐམས་ཅད་ལ་ཕྱག་འཚལ་ལོ། །\",\"folioNumber\":1,\"volumeNumber\":33}}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":77,\"uuid\":\"ebda8847-d437-4b14-8ca1-981527180324\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Homage to all buddhas, bodhisattvas, noble \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":43}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"disciples\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":52},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"26e83d8b-3cde-40df-8a66-f26ecb8b6243\",\"uuid\":\"e33f3cd7-3cea-4bb5-9c10-22a44f85b42d\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":58}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"solitary realizers\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":58,\"end\":76},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"91eb4850-6549-4ee5-ae57-ec33c68112f1\",\"uuid\":\"8cbeb454-e60f-4212-9f16-9002851742ba\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":76,\"end\":77},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"06af8d56-9a24-4d6f-b1c4-425f4e0b610e\",\"label\":\"66\",\"uuid\":\"82ae6e02-444e-4536-8f33-013cac9984f2\",\"start\":77,\"end\":77,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0c925f1d-7500-47c6-b369-64db9a95a9ec\",\"sort\":10019,\"type\":\"translation\",\"label\":\"1.2\",\"alignments\":{\"toh12\":{\"folioUuid\":\"4f16530d-04d6-43b9-84e4-b2fe9a909f2f\",\"toh\":\"toh12\",\"tibetan\":\"འདི་སྐད་བདག་གིས་ཐོས་པ་དུས་གཅིག་ན། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་རྒྱལ་པོའི་ཁབ་ན་བྱ་རྒོད་ཀྱི་ཕུང་པོའི་རི་ལ་བཞུགས་ཏེ། \\nདགེ་སློང་སྟོང་ཉིས་བརྒྱ་ལྔ་བཅུའི་དགེ་སློང་གི་དགེ་འདུན་ཆེན་པོ་དག་དང་ཐབས་ཅིག་གོ། །ཐམས་ཅད་ཀྱང་དགྲ་བཅོམ་པ། ཟག་པ་ཟད་པ། ཉོན་མོངས་པ་མེད་པ། དབང་དུ་གྱུར་པ། སེམས་ཤིན་ཏུ་རྣམ་\\nཔར་གྲོལ་བ། ཤེས་རབ་ཤིན་ཏུ་རྣམ་པར་གྲོལ་བ། ཅང་ཤེས་པ། གླང་པོ་ཆེན་པོ། །བྱ་བ་བྱས་པ། བྱེད་པ་བྱས་པ། ཁུར་བོར་བ། རང་གི་དོན་རྗེས་སུ་ཐོབ་པ། སྲིད་པར་ཀུན་ཏུ་སྦྱོར་བ་ཡོངས་སུ་ཟད་པ། \\nཡང་དག་པར་ཀུན་ཤེས་པས་སེམས་ཤིན་ཏུ་རྣམ་པར་གྲོལ་བ། སེམས་ཐམས་ཅད་ཀྱི་དབང་དམ་པའི་ཕ་རོལ་ཏུ་སོན་པ་ཐོབ་པ་ཤ་སྟག་སྟེ། གང་ཟག་གཅིག་མ་གཏོགས་པ་ནི་འདི་ལྟ་སྟེ། ཚེ་དང་ལྡན་པ་ཀུན་[F.2.a]དགའ་བོའོ། །\",\"folioNumber\":1,\"volumeNumber\":33}}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":899,\"uuid\":\"0c925f1d-7500-47c6-b369-64db9a95a9ec\",\"hasLeadingSpace\":true,\"leadingSpaceUuid\":\"6c5a8ec4-cbbd-42d5-a4bf-565c7c988024\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Thus did I hear at one time. The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":33}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Blessed One\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":44},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"7bf45dd5-3e8d-4495-bc65-ecf0a51d3597\",\"uuid\":\"63ad4306-4ae8-4dc4-874a-28fa3db9a0fb\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" was dwelling at \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":44,\"end\":61}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Vulture Peak\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":61,\"end\":73},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"d86dc1c3-f802-46fe-9bd6-4b2321d77a32\",\"uuid\":\"fed3bf45-ac76-4a4c-b157-6e2f1f151d36\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" near \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":73,\"end\":79}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Rājagṛha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":79,\"end\":87},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"5d05565c-7425-4bfd-bd3c-e6512ac83dd2\",\"uuid\":\"8179d124-6ff6-4693-8bbb-45d38af69fa7\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" together with a great monastic gathering of one thousand two hundred and fifty \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":87,\"end\":167}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"monks\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":167,\"end\":172},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"1edbce5c-7c22-429e-9fa2-11fdfaa759bb\",\"uuid\":\"19c5b88e-7b64-4fca-82b7-9d264821d95b\",\"toh\":\"toh12\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":172,\"end\":